<head>
<title>Arbitration under Georgia Law</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<h1>Recent Developments Affecting Arbitration Under Georgia Law</h1>
<h2>Daniel R. King</h2>
<H6>This article originally appeared in the June 1995 issue of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Coproate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by permission.</H6>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
Recent decisions of the United States Supreme Court and courts within Georgia will have a
significant impact on future arbitration practice in Georgia.  These cases highlight, among other
things, the need for full awareness of the applicable law and extreme care in drafting arbitration
clauses.  Otherwise, significant rights of a party may be prejudiced. <p>

<h4>1.  Pre-Dispute Contractual Waivers of Jury Trials Are Invalid.</h4>
The Georgia Supreme Court in <i>Bank South, N.A. v. Howard</i>, 264 Ga. 339, 444 S.E.2d 799, (1994), held that pre-litigation contractual waivers of the right to a trial by jury are not
enforceable under Georgia law.  Now, commercial entities such as banks, which had previously
been able to enforce contractual jury trial waiver provisions, no longer have that option. <p>

The <i>Bank South</i> decision makes arbitration and other forms of ADR all the more important to all parties seeking to avoid exposure to jury trials.  This is because, although by agreeing to settle their dispute in an arbitration forum, parties implicitly waive their right to a jury trial, valid agreements to arbitrate are still favored even after <i>Bank South</i>.  Therefore, parties who wish to avoid the possibility of trial by jury must hope that their opponents will not ask for a jury trial or draft an effective contractual provision for the arbitration of disputes. <p>

<h4>2.  One-Party Options To Arbitrate Are Valid.</h4>
In a significant, but not widely-known case, <i>W.L. Jorden &amp; Co. v. Blythe Indus., Inc</i>., 702 F. Supp. 282 (N.D. Ga. 1988), the Court, applying the Federal Arbitration Act ("FAA"), held that a
clause providing that one party, in its sole discretion, could elect to submit a dispute to
arbitration, is valid and binding.  This decision is important for parties concerned that they will
be unable to predict at the time of contracting whether ADR will be in their best interest in
resolving a dispute which may later arise under the agreement.  For entities with the bargaining
power to include such an arbitration option clause in their agreements, they will be able to pick
and choose which disputes they wish to arbitrate and which ones to litigate --after the dispute has
arisen.<p>

<h4>3.  The FAA Controls Arbitration Agreements Involving Interstate Commerce
Regardless Of What The Parties Contemplated.</h4>
In a resounding affirmation of the policy favoring arbitration, in January of 1995, the U.S.
Supreme Court decided <i>Allied-Bruce Terminix Cos., Inc. v. Dobson</i>, ____ U.S. ____, 115 S.Ct.
834 (1995).  This case arose out of a dispute between Allied-Bruce and the transferees of a home
Termite Protection Plan (the "Agreement"), which provided that:<p>

<blockquote><i>any controversy or claim . . . arising out of or relating to the interpretation,
performance or any breach of any provision of this agreement shall be settled
exclusively by arbitration.</i>
</blockquote>
The Alabama transferees of the Agreement sued Allied-Bruce, and the company moved to stay
the litigation pending the outcome of the arbitration.  The trial court denied the motion and the
Alabama Supreme Court affirmed, relying on an Alabama statute that made pre-dispute
arbitration agreements unenforceable.  In doing so, the Alabama Supreme Court noted that
Section 2 of the Federal Arbitration Act, 9 U.S.C.  2, provides:<p>

<blockquote><i>A written provision in . . . a contract evidencing a transaction involving commerce to settle by arbitration a controversy thereafter arising out of such contract or
transaction . . . shall be valid, irrevocable, and enforceable . . .</i>
</blockquote>
The Alabama Supreme Court, however, held that the FAA applied only if, at the time the parties
entered into an arbitration agreement, they contemplated substantial interstate activity.  The
Court found that a home termite protection plan was not the sort of an agreement where the
parties would contemplate substantial interstate activity--instead, activity was primarily local.<p>

The U.S. Supreme Court reversed the Alabama Supreme Court, explaining: "The basic purpose
of the Federal Arbitration Act is to overcome courts' refusal to enforce agreements to arbitrate."<p>

The Court also stated that Section 2 of the FAA indicated Congress' intent to exercise its
Commerce Clause powers to the fullest extent possible and that whether or not a transaction
"affects commerce" is determined by the "commerce in fact" test and not the "contemplation of
the parties" test applied by the Alabama Supreme Court.  Accordingly, if a pre-dispute
arbitration agreement relates to a transaction, which in fact "affects commerce," the FAA
preempts any conflicting state law that would make such an agreement unenforceable.  See also
<i>Primerica Fin. Serv., Inc. v. Wise</i>, No. A94A2290-91, 1995 Ga. App. LEXIS 361 (Ga. Ct. App.
March 14, 1995) (the Georgia Court of Appeals held that Georgia law requiring that all
employment related arbitration agreements must be initialed to be enforceable is not binding
when the FAA applies).<p>

<h4>4.  Additional Ripples From Allied-Bruce Which Affect Georgia Arbitrations.</h4>
Based on the <i>Allied-Bruce</i> broad definition of "affecting commerce," the FAA will preempt any
state law that would otherwise prevent the enforceability of an agreement to arbitrate that
involves interstate commerce.  In this regard, the Georgia Arbitration Code has specific areas in
which pre-dispute agreements to arbitrate are either prohibited or are otherwise exempted from
the general arbitration rules.  These exempted areas, all potentially affected by <i>Allied-Bruce,</i>
include medical malpractice claims, collective bargaining agreements, contracts involving
insurance, loan agreements or consumer financing agreements of $25,000 or less, contracts for
the purchase of consumer goods, residential real estate agreements, employment agreements, and
personal injury or wrongful death claims.  See O.C.G.A.  9-9-2. <i>Primerica Fin. Serv., Inc. v.
Wise,</i> No. A94A2290-91, 1995 Ga. App LEXIS 361 (Ga. Ct. App. March 14, 1995) Georgia law
requiring that employment related arbitration agreements must be initialed to be enforced is not
binding when the FAA applies).<p>

<h5>a.  When Would An Otherwise Enforceable Agreement To Arbitrate Be Deemed Invalid Under FAA's Savings Clause?</h5>
The primary open issue under <i>Allied-Bruce</i> is whether, and if so, to what extent, the FAA
savings clause in Section 2 (agreements to arbitrate are enforceable "save upon such grounds as
exist at law or in equity for the revocation of any contract") permits invalidation of arbitration
agreements based on such doctrines as adhesion, public policy, and unconscionability.  The
<i>Allied-Bruce</i> Court acknowledged that states can regulate contracts under general contract law
principles to protect "consumers against unfair pressure to agree to a contract with an unwanted
arbitration provision."  But the Court noted:<p>

<blockquote><i>What States may not do is decide that a contract is fair enough to enforce all its basic terms (price, service, credit), but not fair enough to enforce its arbitration clause.  The Act [FAA] makes any such state policy unlawful, for that kind of policy would place arbitration clauses on an unequal "footing," directly contrary to the Act's language and Congress's intent.</i>
</blockquote>
<h5>b.  Impact Of A Severability Clause.</h5>
Although the <i>Allied-Bruce</i> Court prohibited focusing solely on the arbitration clause in assessing the enforceability of an agreement, the Georgia Court of Appeals in <i>Primerica Fin. Serv., Inc. v. Wise, </i>No. A94A2290-91, 1995 Ga. App. LEXIS 361 (Ga. Ct. App. March 14, 1995), in accordance with a severability clause, upheld the trial court's decision to strike a section of an arbitration clause that provided for certain qualifications of arbitrators.  The trial court acknowledged that the FAA applied, but found that the qualifications provision was "an inherently unfair, unjust and inequitable procedure designed to favor only the defendants."  The Court so ruled even though the FAA at Section 5 provides: that "if in the agreement provision be made for a method of naming or appointing an arbitrator . . ., such method shall be followed." <p>
The trial court in <i>Primerica</i> held that given the parties' intention to arbitrate their disputes and the strong public policy in favor of arbitration, it would strike only the arbitrator qualifications section (i.e., blue-pencil the agreement) rather than striking the entire arbitration provision or invalidating the entire agreement.  Because the <i>Primerica</i> Court did not consider the "fairness" of the agreement taken as a whole (as required by <i>Allied-Bruce</i>), but instead invalidated only a portion of the arbitration clause, it is uncertain whether this approach will survive as a permissible application of the FAA savings clause in light of <i>Allied-Bruce</i> (which did not address the impact of a severability clause). <p>

<h4>5.  Parties May Alter The Role Of The Reviewing Court.</h4>
The <i>Primerica</i> case also highlights the importance of nuances in drafting arbitration clauses dealing with the scope of a court's review on appeal from an arbitration award.  In <i>Primerica</i>, the court ruled that the parties' agreement to expand the scope of the reviewing court's role did not violate the FAA or public policy.  The court reasoned that although the clause expanded the court's review of an arbitration award, it was nonetheless valid because the standard of review was similar to the "any evidence" standard applied to administrative agency appeals in Georgia.  <p>
<h4>6.  Parties Can Grant Arbitrators The Authority To Award Punitive Damages
Regardless Of Contrary State Law.</h4> The United States Supreme Court, in <i>Mastrobuono v. Shearson Lehman Hutton, Inc</i>., ____ U.S. ____, 115 S.Ct. 1212 (1995), addressed the authority of the arbitrators to craft awards.  The <i>Mastrobuono</i> court held that arbitrators may award punitive damages in an arbitration proceeding conducted pursuant to an arbitration agreement that incorporates an arbitration organization's rules permitting such awards.  The Court made this ruling even though the agreement also contained a choice-of-law provision stating that the agreement was governed by the laws of New York, which empowered courts, not arbitrators, to award punitive damages.<p>
<p>
<center><HR><p>
