<HEAD>
<TITLE> Is Design/Build The Right Choice for the Project Owner?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>Is Design/Build The Right Choice for the Project Owner?</H1><P>
<H2>Michael L. Bishop</H2><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
Full service project delivery may be the defining phrase for the construction industry in the 1990s, as owners seek alternatives to the "traditional" approach to project delivery. 
<P>
This bulletin will examine the choices available to a corporate owner in deciding which type of construction delivery method to use in completion of construction projects, and will offer perspectives on the relative strengths of traditional processes and the design/build model.
<P>
<H4>Traditional Construction Contracting Methods:</H4>
<STRONG>The Owner/Architect/Contractor Triangle</STRONG><P>
Traditionally, projects were accomplished using the "design-bid-build” method. This involves a separation of roles between the designer and builder, with each being retained separately by the owner. Responsibilities are fragmented under the traditional model, and the owner is placed in the position of being arbiter of disputes and claims. 
<P>
The contractor is typically a latecomer to the scene in the design-bid-build model. 
<P>
The conventional design-bid-build method offers clear lines of authority and clear divisions of contractual responsibility. Its critics also argue that it is slow, inefficient, and tends to drive up costs. And it complicates the owner’s position by making him the contractual privity of two parties who may end up pointing at each other in the event problems arise.
<P>
<STRONG>Design/Build: The Ideal Model?</STRONG><P>
In an attempt to accelerate design and construction, reduce costs, and minimize the owner’s efforts in managing the construction process, the design/build concept has emerged. 
<P>
Design/build refers to a project delivery system in which a single entity provides to the owner all services necessary to design and construct the project. 
<P>
Many observers of the construction industry believe that the design/build model brings together an optimal selection of the best features of the traditional project delivery methods while adding its own unique benefits.
<P>
During the predesign phase, the design/builder typically may assemble a variety of experts to address predesign factors and issues. During the design phase, the design/builder may either call on its own architectural staff or subcontract with an architect. Either way, the architect is charged with interpreting the owner’s needs. The design/builder’s in-house experts typically take on scheduling, costing, constructability and quality assurance analysis tasks. The design/builder assumes full liability for design efficacy. 
<P>
During the construction phase, the design/builder actually builds the project. Projects may be fast-tracked, insofar as the interface of design/build functions is streamlined within one organization. 
<P>
<STRONG>When is Design/Build the Best Option?</STRONG><P>
No single set of project characteristics dictates the use of design/build. The design/build model has been successfully used on extraordinarily complex facilities and on "straightforward" office buildings. 
<P>
Owner’s criteria that might be considered for determining when to use design/build include (1) time constraints for delivery of the project; (2) the capability and experience of potential contractors with the design/build process; and (3) the capability (or inability) of the owner to manage the project, including personnel to oversee the project who are familiar with the design/build process.
<P>
<STRONG>The Owner’s Role in the Design/Build Process</STRONG><P>
For the design/build approach to be used successfully, the owner must clearly define the needs and requirements of the project so that they are understood by design/build contractors submitting proposals on the project. It is crucial that the owner issue comprehensive scope of work information that may include some or all of the following: detailed space and equipment requirements, site surveys, soil borings, outline specifications, budget parameters and scheduling requirements. <P>
<STRONG>Advantages of the Design/Build Model</STRONG><P>
Experience with the design/build approach has demonstrated its benefits: 
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>Establishes Single Source of Responsibility</STRONG>. Eliminates disagreements over project responsibility and reduces the owner’s administrative tasks.
<LI><STRONG>Encourages Contractor Participation</STRONG>. Greater participation by the contractor during the design process results in a more cost-effective design.
<LI><STRONG>Facilitates Communication</STRONG>. Communications between design and construction personnel result in more effective transformation of design concepts into construction reality.
<LI><STRONG>Reduces Total Project Delivery Time</STRONG>. Design documentation can be reduced due to the direct collaboration of the contractor and architect. Construction on some phases of the work can begin while later phases of project design are still in process (i.e., "fast tracking"). Schedule delays may also be reduced because "finger-pointing" is unlikely to occur. 
<LI><STRONG>Reduces Change Orders</STRONG>. Swift and informal internal communication can take care of problems that would have become change orders under the traditional project delivery methods.
<LI><STRONG>Lowers Total Project Costs</STRONG>. Reducing project delivery time saves construction overhead costs and, for the owner, saves project financing costs. Less time may also be spent on construction administration due to collaborative decision-making.
<LI><STRONG>Fosters Innovative Solutions</STRONG>. Creative design and construction solutions can be developed within the design/build process (e.g., value engineering is an implicit aspect of the process).
<LI><STRONG>Enhances Owner’s Protection from Liability</STRONG>. If any defects or omissions in design or construction occur, the owner is free to hold the entire design/build entity liable.
</UL>
<STRONG>Disadvantages of the Design/Build Model</STRONG><P>
An obvious disadvantage of the design/build model is that the combination of design and construction responsibilities in one provider may deprive the owner of the "checks and balances" protection inherent in more traditional project delivery systems. <P>
Other concerns exist:<P>
<UL>
<LI><STRONG>Loss of Independent Architect</STRONG>. The owner may not receive the same type of guidance and advice from an architect who is only a part of the design/ builder, and who has a direct financial interest in the construction of the project.
<LI><STRONG>Inspection Services</STRONG>. Owners will not have the benefit of independent architectural inspection during construction of the project, whereas traditionally, architects reviewed both the individual structural components and the overall integrity of the project design. The owner may have to provide its own inspection services or hire an independent inspection team.
</UL>
<STRONG>"Bridging": A Variation on Design/Build</STRONG><P>
The design/build model has spawned its own variation, called "Bridging."
<P>Bridging is a hybrid of the traditional process and the design/build model, and seeks to promote involvement by the owner in design aspects of the project.
<P>The owner selects an architect to conceptualize the project design through the design development phase and prepare scope of work documents that form the basis for competitive selection of the project design/build team. The owner’s architect specifies the project’s functional and aesthetic requirements but leaves the details of construction technology up to the design/builder. The design/builder then has responsibility for final design and construction of the project.<P>
<STRONG>Conclusion</STRONG><P>
In either the traditional or design/build context, the owner must make an assessment of its own capacity, and inclination, to manage the construction process. An owner that regularly engages in the planning, design and construction of its own facilities, and maintains a sufficient staff of experienced construction professionals, may be capable of managing designers and contractors and, in essence, performing the role of construction manager. 
<P>In most cases, however, corporate owners are not in the business of construction and it is not economical to maintain a staff of employees for such purposes. For these owners, the design/build model - the modern "full service" option - may be the best choice for successful construction project completion.
<P>
<center><HR><p>
