<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Georgia Mechanics’ Liens: Winning Stategies for Owners and General Contractors</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>Georgia Mechanics’ Liens: Winning Stategies for Owners and General Contractors</H1><P>
<H2>Michael L. Bishop</H2><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
Filing and perfecting a lien on a construction project is not an easy procedure. The entire process provides a variety of opportunities for mistakes, missteps and missed deadlines. For a subcontractor wishing to file and recover on a lien, the process presents headaches. For an owner or general contractor who wishes to avoid or fight liens, this presents a series of opportunities to stop a lien claim dead in its tracks.<P>
Therefore, when a subcontractor files a claim of lien on a project, it is important that the project owner or general contractor identify any defects in the claim of lien, or in the subcontractor’s efforts to enforce its claim of lien. <P>
Many lien defenses are "fact-based", that is, they require the project owner or general contractor to be aware of, and to communicate to their attorneys, any defects observed in the lien claim.<P>
The following checklist will be helpful in determining if a lien, or a subcontractor’s efforts to recover on a lien, suffers any fatal defects:
<UL>
<LI>Georgia law requires that a project owner file a Notice of Commencement. If the owner files the Notice of Commencement, a lien claimant must, in turn, serve a notice to contractor on both the general contractor and the owner if the lien claimant does not have a direct contract with the owner or the general contractor. The notice of contractor ‘announces’ that the subcontractor is supplying labor, materials or services to the owner’s project. If a subcontractor files a lien on a project, and they have not filed a notice to contractor, they have forfeited their right to claim a lien.<P>
<LI>In order to maintain a lien, a lien claimant must have substantially complied with its own contract responsibilities. In other words, a lien claimant who has breached his own performance responsibilities cannot recover on a lien claim against the project owner.<P>
<LI>The lien claim must have been filed within three months (not 90  days) of the date on which the last labor, materials or services were furnished to the project by the lien claimant. (For example, if the last day of a subcontractor’s work was January 1, the subcontractor’s lien would have to be filed by April 1.)<P>
<LI>The claim of lien may not be filed prior to the completion of the lien claimant’s work on the project.<P>
<LI>The lien claimant must show that it segregated the labor and material charges for which the lien is claimed from other labor and materials that may have been provided on other projects.<P>
<LI>The lien claimant must show that it is an authorized subcontractor or supplier and has not performed work or supplied materials on the project in violation of a relevant contractual provision (for example, a clause against subcontracting or assignment).<P>
<LI>A claim of lien can only be maintained if the services, labor or materials were actually furnished to the project.<P>
<LI>The claim of lien document must correctly name the property owner.<P>
<LI>The claim of lien document must correctly identify the property on which the lien is to be placed. (For example, a claim of lien that incorrectly identifies your neighbor’s property rather than the project property may be an irritation to your neighbor, but it is not a valid claim of lien on your property.)<P>
<LI>The claimant must sue the original debtor (i.e., the party to whom the lien claimant supplied materials or labor) within 12 months from the last date labor or materials were furnished.<P>
<LI>The lien claimant must file a notice of suit with the clerk of the Superior Court of the Georgia county where the property is located at the time the suit against the original debtor is filed.<P>
<LI>If the original debtor is bankrupt, the lien claimant must sue the owner within twelve months of the last date on which labor or materials were furnished.<P>
<LI>A subcontractor that is a non-resident of Georgia cannot maintain an action to enforce lien rights in the Georgia courts unless the subcontractor has registered with the Georgia Department of Revenue pursuant to the Georgia Non-Resident Contractors Act.<P>
<LI>A subcontractor that has released and waived its claims by providing an unconditional final waiver cannot maintain a lien on the property that is the subject of the release.<P>
</UL>

When a lien claimant fails to meet one or more of the above requirements, the lien may be invalid under Georgia law.<P> 
And remember: Under Georgia Law a subcontractor’s avenue of recovery against an owner is pursuant to the lien law. A subcontractor’s breach of contract claim is typically brought against the party with whom it contracted, not the owner.
Determining whether any of the foregoing legal defenses are applicable requires investigation and the careful keeping of records by the owner and general contractor on a project. <P>
The foregoing list of possible defects is provided in order to assist owners and general contractors in making a quick evaluation of the strengths, or weaknesses, of liens that may be filed against their projects. Armed with this assistance, you should be able to negotiate with lien claimants from a position of strength.<P>
<P>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center></BODY>
