<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The Georgia Prompt Pay Act: Issues and Answers For Owners and General Contractors
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>The Georgia Prompt Pay Act: Issues and Answers For Owners and General Contractors
</H1><P>
<H2>Michael L. Bishop</H2><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
The Georgia Prompt Pay Act (Georgia Code §§13-11-1. - 11. the "Act") establishes conditions and time limits for payments to general contractors and to subcontractors.<P>
The Act also sets out grounds for withholding of such payments, specifies conditions for payments of retainage, provides for the collection of interest on late payments under certain circumstances, and allows recovery of attorneys’ fees in actions to enforce claims under the Act. <P>
<STRONG>Can parties avoid the Act?</STRONG>
Section 13-11-7 contains the most important limitation on the coverage of the Act. <P>
Subsection (b) expressly allows agreement by contract to interest rates, payment periods and other terms different from those stated in the Act, and in the event of such agreement the contract terms will control. <P>
<U>The Act is applicable only where no superseding contract provisions have been entered into by the parties. </U><P>
We suggest that this preemption be made clear by including the following language in all construction agreements: <P>
<EM>The parties hereby agree that the provisions stated in this Agreement with respect to payment(s), withholding of payment(s), interest rates on late payment(s), and recovery of attorneys’ fees supersede and replace the terms of the Georgia Prompt Pay Act, O.C.G.A. §13-11-1, et seq.  The provisions of the Georgia Prompt Pay Act shall not apply to this Agreement.</EM><P>
<STRONG>Who is covered by the Act?</STRONG><P>
In addition to contractors and subcontractors, the coverage of the Act’s payment requirements extends to private owners as well as state, local and municipal government agencies, excepting counties with populations of less than 10,000 and cities of less than 2,500 people. <P>
The Act’s definition of "real property" includes not only land and the improvements thereon but also lease-holds, thereby subjecting to the Act tenants who order improvements.
Who is a subcontractor?<P>
A subcontractor is defined by the Act as any person who contracts to furnish, or who furnishes, labor or materials to a contractor or subcontractor in connection with a contract for improvements to real property. <P>
Including those "contracting to furnish" and of those "actually furnishing" labor and materials, the definition appears to include subcontractors and materialsmen not strictly in a chain of privity of contract with the owner.<P>
<STRONG>What are payment conditions?</STRONG><P>
The Act states the prerequisites to a contractor’s or subcontractor’s entitlement to payment. 
These prerequisites are:<P>
1.	Performance of the terms of the contract; and<P>
2.	Satisfaction of any contractual conditions precedent to payment.<P>
Presumably, although the statute uses the unqualified terms "performance" and "satisfaction," the concept of substantial performance will be engrafted judicially upon the statute and such performance will suffice for entitlement to payment.<P>
<STRONG>What are payment terms?</STRONG><P>
The basic "prompt pay" requirements of the Act are set out in §13-11-4, which mandates payment by an owner to a contractor within 15 days of any payment request by the contractor for completed work. <P>
This section further provides that each contractor and subcontractor must pay to their respective subcontractors within 10 days of receipt of any periodic or final payment the full amount received for the subcontractors’ work.<P>
Unlike the time deadline for payment by an owner to the prime contractor, the deadline for payments to subcontractors is qualified. <P>
The 10-day payment provision must be met only when the subcontractor provides "satisfactory reasonable assurances of continued performance and financial responsibility," within the discretion of the contractor, including, but not limited to, the posting of payment and performance bonds. <P>
General contractors and upper tier subcontractors are limited only by the subjective standard of "reasonable discretion" in refusing payment to subcontractors based upon some real or reasonable fear of future default.<P>
<STRONG>When can payment be withheld?</STRONG><P>
The Act also sets out a variety of grounds upon which payment may be withheld. <P>
Section 13-11-5 provides that owners may withhold payment from contractors, and that contractors and subcontractors may withhold payment from their subcontractors, for unsatisfactory job progress, defective work, disputed work, actual or potential third-party claims, failure to make timely payments for labor or materials, damage to other entities connected with the project, or reasonable evidence that the contract cannot be completed for the balance of the contract price. <P>
In addition, this section allows withholding of retainage. Retainage withheld from a contractor cannot exceed the contractual retainage percent. Retainage withheld from a subcontractor cannot exceed the percentage retained by the owner on account of the subcontractor’s work.<P>
Further conditions upon the 10-day limit for payment to subcontractors are set out in §13-11-6. Pass through of payments and reduction of retainage for subcontractors is required within the Act’s time constraints only where the value of the subcontractor’s completed work equals 50% of the subcontract value, including change orders. <P>
In addition, this section restates that the Act’s time limitations for payments to subcontractors are applicable only upon provision by the subcontractor of reasonable assurances of performance.<P>
<STRONG>What are interest and penalties?</STRONG><P>
Section 13-11-7(a) states the penalty for failure to make payment within the Act’s time constraint in the form of a statutory interest provision. <P>
Amounts due and unpaid under the terms of the Act will bear interest at the rate of 1% per month, provided that, at the time of the request for payment, the person to be charged was notified of the interest provision of the code section. <P>
Apparently, a contractor or subcontractor lien claimant may include in its lien claim the interest provided under the Act, rather than the lower interest rate of 7% per annum typically allowed under Georgia Code §7-4-2. <P>
Acceptance of a progress payment or of final payment releases any claim for interest on that payment under the Act.<P>
The prevailing party in any action to enforce a claim under the Act is entitled to recover attorneys’ fees, including, but not limited to, fees incurred in trial, appeal or arbitration of such a claim, pursuant to §3-11-8. <P>
This right to recover attorneys’ fees and the right to recover interest under the Act are nonexclusive remedies, and the Act does not modify remedies available under differing contract or statutory terms. (Section 13-11-9). <P>
Presumably, therefore, suppliers of materials on account remain entitled to collect 1.5% interest per month as provided in Georgia Code §7-4-16.<P>
<STRONG>A pay-when-paid provision?</STRONG><P>
Another potentially far-reaching and perhaps unintended consequence of the Act arises from §13-11-4, which sets up the 10-day limit for payments to subcontractors. <P>
The section on its face appears to be a boon to subcontractors in that it is meant to speed payments to them from the higher tiers of the project. <P>
However, this section could be used by higher tier contractors to the extreme detriment of these same subcontractors. <P>
As a general proposition, payment to a subcontractor is not conditioned upon receipt of payment by the entity obligated to pay, absent a contractual "pay when paid" clause. <P>
The language of §13-11-4, in mandating that contractors and subcontractors pay their subcontractors within 10 days of receipt of payment from above, appears to be a statutory "pay when paid" provision, arguably applicable wherever not expressly contradicted by contract terms. <P>
The Act could therefore create a significant defense to payment obligations in the construction field, which had previously existed only when specified by contract. <P>
Clearly, the courts will have the final say on this interpretation.<P>
<STRONG>The bottom line</STRONG><P>
The new Prompt Pay Act is essentially a "default" mechanism: It applies unless the parties agree otherwise. <P>
The key, then, is for owners and contractors who desire to be exempted from the Act to provide their own terms of payment, retainage, etc., and parties should make it clear that they are providing "preemptive" terms by utilizing the contract insert suggested in this bulletin.<P>
<P>
Please contact us if you have further questions regarding the Georgia Prompt Pay Act, or if we can be of any other assistance.
<P>
<center><HR><p>
