<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Advice For Georgia Owners and General Contractors: How To Use The Notice of Commencement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>Advice For Georgia Owners and General Contractors: How To Use The Notice of Commencement</H1><P>
<H2>Michael L. Bishop</H2><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
The Notice of Commencement procedure set out in Georgia Statute §44-14-361.5 requires mutual disclosure of information by Owners and General Contractors on one hand, and Sub-subcontractors on the other. A “Notice of Commencement” must be filed by the Owner, an agent of the Owner, or the General Contractor on a construction project no later than 15 days after the General Contractor has physically begun work on the Owner’s property. The “Notice of Commencement” must be:<P>
<UL>
<LI>filed with the Clerk of the Superior Court in the county in which the project is located; and<P>
<LI>a copy posted on the Project site. <P>
</UL>
The following items must be included within the Notice:<P>
<UL>
<LI>a legal description of the property upon which the improvements are being made,<P>
<LI>the name and location of the project being constructed, and<P>
<LI>the names and addresses of the General Contractor; the true owner of the property, or the person other than the Owner at whose instance the work is being furnished, if other than the true owner (e.g., a tenant); the surety (if applicable); and the construction lender (if applicable). <P>
<LI>Subsequent to the “Notice of Commencement” filing, any potential lien claimant who is not in privity with the General Contractor (i.e., sub-subcontractors) must furnish a “Notice to Contractor” to the Owner, or the Owner’s agent and the General Contractor within 30 days from the date that the “Notice of Commencement” was filed, or 30 days from the time that the potential lien claimant first furnished materials or labor on the project, whichever is later. <P>
</UL>
The “Notice to Contractor” must include the name, address and telephone number of the lien claimant, the name and address of each person at whose instance the labor, services or materials are being furnished, the name and location of the Project and a description of the labor, services or materials being provided, including the contract price or anticipated value. <P>
If the potential lien claimant fails to furnish the “Notice to Contractor” within the required time period, the claimant will not be entitled to enforce its lien rights. <P>
However, if a “Notice of Commencement” has not been filed, then sub-subcontractors are relieved from their duty to file a “Notice to Contractor,” and this section will not be applicable. If a party requests a copy of the “Notice of Commencement” from the General Contractor, the General Contractor is obligated to provide such copy to the requesting party within 10 days of the request.<P>
There are two underlying purposes for the “Notice of Commencement” procedure. First, it permits the potential lien claimant a better opportunity to file a lien, as the necessary filing information will be provided in the “Notice of Commencement.” Second, the “Notice of Commencement” provides the Owner and the General Contractor with the mechanism for keeping track of all of the entities performing work or supplying materials on the project and for making sure that payments are made. <P>
<P>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center></BODY>
</HTML>
