<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>STRANDED INVESTMENT THE BUCK STOPS WHERE?</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">STRANDED INVESTMENT:<BR>THE BUCK STOPS WHERE?</H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/htm/swenson.htm">Erik J.  Swenson</A></H2>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the June 1996 issue of
<I>Competitive Utility</I>, an INFOCAST publication. For subscription
information, please call 818-902-5400.</H6>
<HR>
<P>The issue of stranded utility investment in electric generating facilities
is not new.  The huge cost over-runs associated with many nuclear power plants
constructed in the mid-1970s were in many cases thought to be sufficiently large
as to prevent their immediate and direct recovery from ratepayers.  Stranded in
time, those costs were transformed into &quot;regulatory assets&quot; and
special arrangements were made to collect the costs from ratepayers, often on a
deferred basis.</P>
<P>The delayed recovery of these stranded costs did not make them go away, it
merely shifted the problem in time -- to now.  The public clamor over high
electric rates, in the very states that previously &quot;solved&quot; the
problem via regulatory assets, has made it clear that such an approach will not
work.   Thus, the quest has begun to find another way to recover uncompetitive
generation costs, while simultaneously affording electric consumers access to
lower cost, competitive electric generating markets.</P>
<P>At the federal level, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (&quot;FERC&quot;)
has proposed allowing access to competitive generation by opening the interstate
electric transmission grid.  If this comes to pass, customers may use the
opportunity to flee from utilities with high electric prices.  However, the FERC
proposes to protect those high priced utilities that previously built generating
facilities (or entered into long-term fuel or purchased power contracts),
expecting to provide continued generation services.  Under the FERC's proposal,
a utility would be entitled to recover such stranded investments by increasing
transmission charges imposed pursuant to Sections 205, 206 and 211 of the
Federal Power Act.  See Recovery of Stranded Costs by Public Utilities and
Transmitting Utilities, Docket No.  RM94-7-000, 59 Fed.  Reg.  35,274 (July 11,
1994).  In other words, the uneconomic generation costs would be passed onto the
interstate electric transmission system and recovered there.</P>
<P>State regulatory commissions are acting, or considering acting, along a
similar path.  For example, the Public Utilities Commission of the State of
California has instituted proceedings to consider restructuring the California
electric services industry to permit access to competition.  However, the
stranded investment of utilities would be recovered through Competition
Transition Charges  (&quot;CTCs&quot;).  See, e.g., Commissioner Jessie J.
Knight, Jr.'s May 24, 1995 Proposal and Recommendations in Dockets R.94-04-031
and I.94-04-032 (proposing to compensate utilities for 90 percent of uneconomic
generation assets).  &quot;[B]ecause the utility will retain its monopoly on
local distribution, the Commission can apply [CTCs] to customers of the
[electric distribution company] without regard to which generation company [the
customers] choose, or whether they remain a utility service customer.&quot;  Id.
at 85.</P>
<P>Recently, the Commonwealth of Massachusetts Department of Public Utilities
imposed very similar charges in a case involving the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology (&quot;MIT&quot;), which has installed its own on-site generation
facilities.  Petition of Massachusetts Institute of Technology, D.P.U. 94-
101/95-36 (Sept. 28, 1995).  There, a Customer Transition Charge (in the amount
of 75% of Cambridge Electric Light Company's stranded generating costs)  was
added to MIT's bill for stand-by services provided by Cambridge.  Although the
charge was assessed against generation, transmission and distribution services
provided to supplement MIT's own generation, and not just wire services, the
only reason the charge could be imposed is because Cambridge enjoys a monopoly
on transmission and distribution that prevents MIT from looking to a third party
for stand-by services.</P>
<P>Each of these methods of recovering utilities' stranded costs relies on the
existence of a utility monopoly on transmission and distribution services and
the electric consumer's presumed inescapable need to use such services in
obtaining competitive generation service.  Each of these methods also
frustrates, in whole or in part, the ultimate goal of consumers in seeking to
obtain electric generation service at competitive rates.  That goal, of course,
is simply to lower their total cost of electric supply.  Lowering the cost of
generating service, while raising the cost of other related and necessary
services, does not achieve that goal; hence consumers cannot be expected to be
satisfied with the new arrangements being proposed.  Having succeeded in
obtaining low cost generation, they will next seek to avoid the high costs of
transmission and other services.</P>
<P>The question raised here is whether the monopoly status of transmission and
distribution facilities is sufficiently secure, and those services so necessary,
that regulators can safely assume that CTCs will succeed in spreading the cost
of stranded investment over a broad base of consumers.  In other words, can the
consumers' quest for lower electric bills be held in check?  If a significant
amount of electric load can find economic routes to avoid CTCs by declining to
take the services to which they are attached, a death spiral for such charges
may ensue.  That is, as consumers bypass the transition charges, the same
stranded utility investment will have to be spread over a smaller number of
electric consumers, thereby necessitating higher CTCs.  In turn, the higher CTCs
will make it economic for more consumers to find ways to  avoid the over-priced
services, and so on, until no one is left who is either willing or able to pay
down the utility's stranded investment.</P>
<P>It is useful to recall that what makes a monopoly &quot;natural&quot; is its
ability to charge a lower price for a product than its competitors charge for
competing products.  This situation is normally the result of economies of scale
that reduce the monopoly's average and marginal costs of output with each
additional unit sold.  The addition of CTCs to a utility's rate can swamp the
utility's cost advantage, such that competing products have a lower price if the
CTCs can be avoided.  Under these circumstances, the monopoly provider loses its
ability to drop prices to attractive levels in the face of competition and
monopoly rents can only be charged if artificial, in this case regulatory, means
are used to preserve the monopoly.</P>
<P>As is so often the case, the regulatory scheme used to secure a utility's
monopoly hold on transmission and distribution is not perfect.  One source of
potential competition is privately held electric transmission and distribution
lines that eliminate the need to use utility facilities.  Even before the advent
of CTCs, privately operated transmission lines were used to deliver power from
independent power projects to electric consumers.  While the majority of these
lines are under a mile in length and serve just one producer and customer,
longer lines exist.  For example, a group of Public Utility Regulatory Policies
Act Qualifying Facilities share a 214-mile long transmission line running from
Nevada to California.  Another Qualifying Facility owns and operates a 10-mile
long line running between Pennsylvania and New York.</P>
<P>Throughout the New England states, and undoubtedly many other states, 
numerous industrials own small hydroelectric projects that are near, but not
directly connected to, the  owners' industrial loads.  Historically, it made
economic sense for such industrials to sell their generating projects' output to
utilities and separately purchase power to serve their industrial loads. 
However, as regulators allow the prices paid for generation to drop, while
holding the cost of delivered power essentially constant through CTCs, it will
quickly become economic to build transmission lines to link generation to load.</P>
<P>Despite the general perception that siting electric transmission lines is
difficult, the potential for the installation of competing transmission and
distribution facilities by entities who would not need to collect CTCs is
enormous.  The United States is covered with potential pathways for competing
transmission lines.  For instance, according to the Association of American
Railroads, there are approximately 155,000 miles of active railroad rights of
way in the United States today.  Add to this, close to another 100,000 miles of
abandoned rail beds, and their total length of approximately 250,000 miles is on
the same order of magnitude as the current electric transmission grid.  (The
U.S. transmission network consists of approximately 340,000 circuit miles. 
Multiple circuits along the same rights of way mean that the total miles of
electric transmission rights of way is something less.)</P>
<P>The U.S. Congress may soon clear the way for at least one competitor to make
ready use of such rights of way.  The Amtrak and Local Rail Revitalization Act
of 1995, currently pending in Congress, would permit Amtrak to purchase power at
wholesale (allowing access to existing wholesale competition in electric
generation) and resell the power at retail.  See Section 803 of 1995 S.  1318. 
Whether or not the Amtrak bill succeeds, many hundreds of thousands of miles of
rights away will remain waiting to be used by potential transmission
competitors.</P>
<P>State laws may create still other opportunities.  Upon close examination,
what are often considered to be exclusive utility service franchises are not. 
For example, the New Hampshire Public Utilities Commission recently declared
that Public Service Company of New Hampshire's franchise to provide electric
service to certain discrete geographical regions of the state is not exclusive
as a matter of law.  Re Freedom Electric Company, 161 PUR 4th 491 and 163 PUR
4th 223 (1995).  Similarly, the Georgia Territorial Electric Service Act
provides for at least two exceptions (i.e., new load or unsatisfactory service)
to otherwise exclusive franchises granted in Georgia.</P>
<P>In sum, once CTCs are imposed, it is only a matter of time before new
competitors, not saddled with stranded costs, offer services that allow
consumers to bypass CTC-charging utilities altogether.</P>
<P>Even if the routes for competition from third-party providers are blocked by
law or regulation, the opportunity for self-generation is likely to remain. 
Recent improvements in technology will make it economically feasible for many
industrial customers to install self-generation in response to the first wave of
CTCs.  Thomas Casten, president, CEO and founder of Trigen Energy Corp., has
observed that, when the waste heat associated with electric generation is fully
used for productive thermal uses, gas-fired combustion-turbine generators in the
three to five megawatt range are the most economical form of electric generation
today.  The cost of electric power from these cogeneration units, when running
baseloaded, is just 2.0 to 2.5&#162; per kilowatt-hour.  See Casten, &quot;Whither
Electric Generation?  A Different View,&quot; The Energy Daily's News
Environment Extra, September 7, 1995.</P>
<P>The increments of capacity involved are small enough and the cost low enough
that industrial electric consumers that wish to self-generate will be able to
install redundant capacity sufficient to ensure that such on-site generation is
as or more reliable than utility delivered electricity.  Consider that a common
industrial heat load is 250 mmBTU per hour, which will support up to 15
megawatts of electric production by a cogeneration facility with full heat use. 
Assuming that the 15 MW of generation was comprised of five 3 MW generators,
each of which operates  at 90% reliability (a conservative reliability estimate
based on experience), the probability of all five generators working at any
given time would be only 59%.  However, if a sixth generator is added, the
probability of at least five generators being in operation at any time jumps to
88.5%.  Furthermore, unlike a single 90% reliable unit, an outage would not be 
&quot;all or nothing.&quot;  The probability that at least four generators would
be available is 98.4%.  Many industrial and commercial facilities could handle
the infrequent loss of the fifth 3 MW generator through load shedding.</P>
<P>The cost for electricity in this hypothetical, but not unrealistic, case is
1.2 times 2.5&#162; per kWh or just 3.0&#162; per kWh.  Adding even a 50%
allowance, for the inability to perfectly match electric and thermal loads and
other inefficiencies, produces a cost estimate of 4.5&#162; per kWh.  This is a
highly competitive price against utilities with CTCs.  No transmission or backup
services would be required, and the regulatory impediments to self-generation
would be manageable in every jurisdiction with which we are familiar.</P>
<P>As the industrial self-generators with the most cost-effective combinations
of thermal and electric loads bypass utility CTCs, those charges will increase
for other customers.  Utility costs may spiral so that even facilities with 3 MW
electric loads could cost-effectively put in fully redundant capacity (with the
added advantage of system reliability of approximately 99% without load
shedding).  At some point, if utility shareholders do not relent, stranded
investment will be spread over so few users that even residential customers may
find existing technologies such as solar or small packaged cogeneration
facilities financially attractive.  Alternatively, the widespread formation of
new municipal electric utilities may prove to be the lowest cost option.</P>
<P>To conclude, it is not safe to assume that CTCs can be successfully
employed.  Before trying to pass the buck once again, it is time to squarely
face the realities facing the electric utility industry.  Naturally, it would be
prudent for utility management to push the pain of stranded investment onto
others, if they can.  But successful utility competitors should realize the
technological and entrepreneurial limitations on pursuing that strategy and
start thinking differently about competition -- the sooner, the better.  </P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG
SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="Home Page"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG
SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="Practice Groups"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG
SRC="/gif/atty.gif" ALT="Attorneys"><BR></A>
<A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" ALT="Articles"></A>
<A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" ALT="Legal Resources"></A>
<A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></P></BODY></HTML>
