<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>If You Can't Beat 'Em, Join 'Em; Utility Participation In Qualifying
Facilities</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">If You Can't Beat 'Em, Join 'Em; Utility Participation In
Qualifying Facilities</H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="/htm/swenson.htm">Erik J. Swenson</A><BR>Andrew
D. Schifrin</H2>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the August 1996 issue of
<I>Competitive Utility</I>, an INFOCAST publication. For subscription
information, please call 818-902-5400.</H6>
<HR>
<P>The destination is now recognized as inevitable.  We are on the road to full
competition in electric generation.  Many utilities would like to prepare for
such competition by gaining experience outside their rate-regulated world. 
However, not every utility is ready to bet the farm on competition, many
regulators are not yet prepared to fully deregulate utility generation, and the
existing playing field may be tilted in favor of facilities enjoying qualifying
facility (&quot;QF&quot;) status under the Public Utility Regulatory Policies
Act of 1978 (&quot;PURPA&quot;).   Utilities, through unregulated subsidiaries,
can get a head start on competition and gain valuable experience by acquiring
ownership interests in, and operating, QFs.  </P>
<P>Some utilities may believe that they should discount the potential for
developing QFs or taking advantage of opportunities to purchase operating QFs
because their participation in such projects would necessarily be limited to a
non-controlling interest.  However, they are wrong.</P>
<P>Under the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's (&quot;FERC&quot;) existing
rules, a utility can exercise almost complete control over a QF provided that
the project documents are properly structured.  The primary restrictions are:
the utility must share fifty percent of the QF's benefit stream with one or more
non-utility partners; and the utility owner must lack the power to engage in
self dealing at above-market rates.  Thus, utilities can invest in QFs, take
advantage of the many statutory and regulatory exemptions to which QFs are
entitled, and actively manage these ventures, without sharing control.  </P>
<P>PURPA gives little guidance with regard to the level of involvement that a
utility may have in the ownership, development and operation of a QF.  It merely
states that a QF must be &quot;. . . owned by a person not primarily engaged in
the generation or sale of electric power (other than electric power solely from
[QFs]).(1)  The FERC's regulations provide that a QF will be &quot;considered to
be owned by a person primarily engaged in the generation or sale electric power,
if more than 50 percent of the equity interest in the facility is held by an
electric utility or utilities, or by an electric utility holding company or
companies [or subsidiaries of these entities.](2) </P>
<P>While the term &quot;equity interest&quot; is not defined, a review of the
FERC's case-by-case determinations reveals that it is possible for a utility to
enjoy unilateral control over a QF's management, without violating the fifty
percent equity interest limitation.  For example, the FERC has certified a QF
whose management committee was controlled by subsidiaries of Pacificorp and
Southwestern Public Service Company.(3)  Further, a utility can enter into a
wide variety of service contracts with a QF.  Some of the services provided to
QFs by utility-owner affiliated companies include: construction, start-up and
testing, management, and  operation and maintenance. (4) </P>
<P>Of course, if the utility would control the QF, one might well ask who is
going to be willing to supply the other fifty percent of the capital needed to
develop or own the project.  Surprisingly, it can be the QF-owning utility.  In
the many decisions issued since its PURPA regulations were promulgated, the FERC
has determined that the fifty percent equity interest limitation does not
necessarily relate to the amount of capital a utility supplies to a project. 
Instead, the FERC's analyses have focussed on the electric-utility owner's share
of the stream of economic benefits from a particular QF, and the ability to
control that stream of benefits.  In one of its early decisions on this issue,
the FERC certified a QF even though the utility partner provided two thirds of
the initial capital and the non- utility partner provided one third.  The FERC
determined that the initial capital contribution was not part of the &quot;equity
interest&quot; as that term is used in the FERC's regulations, and that the
capital contribution should be viewed as debt rather than equity, since it
conveyed no management rights and did not affect the stream of benefits from the
QF.(5)</P>
<P>In considering a variety of other arrangements relating to utilities'
capital investment in QFs, the FERC has consistently followed its stream of
benefits analysis.  For example, in CMS Midland, Inc.,(6) the assets owned by
Consumers Power Company were to be transferred to the partnership that would own
and operate the QF.  Alternatives to a pure equity investment by the utility
were examined, such as the partnership's purchase of the assets in exchange for
a promissory note, or a lease of the assets to the partnership.  The FERC
observed that if excessive payments were made in exchange for such assets, they
could effectively constitute a distribution of profits from the facility, and
thereby, could result in more than fifty percent of the benefits from the QF
flowing to the utility -- in contravention of the FERC's rules.  However, the
FERC determined that the purchase or lease of the assets from the utility would
be acceptable, provided that such arrangements were not priced above market. 
The ability to lend a joint venturer, or the joint venture, the funds needed to
finance or participate in a project may expand the universe of willing, silent
partners.</P>
<P>Furthermore, recent decisions from the FERC demonstrate that a utility owner
may, at any one time,  be permitted to own and share in more than fifty percent
of the stream of benefits from a QF, so long as the fifty percent limitation is
not exceeded over the term of their involvement.  For example, in Saguaro Power
Company, the FERC recertified a QF in which the stream of benefits flowing to
the  utility owners could exceed fifty percent in certain years, when a true-up
agreement ensured that the utilities' benefit stream would not exceed fifty
percent over the entire period of their participation in the project.(7)</P>
<P>In sum, utilities that want to expand their competitive arsenals before
their existing generation portfolios are deregulated should consider investing
in QFs.   These utilities need not fear that they will be unable to control
their QF ventures or find partners that will concede control to them.  Of
course, as Brooklyn Navy Yard Cogeneration Partners found out when their
application for certification was initially denied by the FERC,(8)  it is vital
to structure the project documents carefully so as not to run afoul of the
FERC's requirements.  With the proper expertise, forward thinking utilities need
not hesitate to play the QF card when the opportunity arises.</P>
<P>Mr. Swenson is a counsel and Mr. Schifrin is an associate with the national
law firm of King &amp; Spalding.  King &amp; Spalding guides utilities, lending
institutions, independent power producers, and industrial and large commercial
electric consumers through the complex energy, banking and finance, corporate,
environmental, litigation, real estate and tax issues in today's changing energy
markets.  Mr. Swenson is a regular contributor to Competitive Utility.</P>
<HR>
<H3>Footnotes</H3>
<P>(1) PURPA &#167; 201.</P>
<P>(2) 18 C.F.R. &#167; 292.206.</P>
<P>(3) See, e.g., Carolina Energy, Limited Partnership, 73 FERC &#182; 62,106
(1995).</P>
<P>(4) See, e.g., Birchwood Power Partners, L.P., 72 FERC &#182; 62,007 (1995);
and Onondaga Cogeneration Limited Partnership, 62 FERC  &#182; 62,140 (1993).
</P>
<P>(5) Ultrapower 3, 27 FERC &#182; 61,094 (1984). </P>
<P>(6) CMS Midland, Inc., 38 FERC &#182; 61, 244 (1987).</P>
<P>(7) 75 FERC &#182; 62,025 (1996).</P>
<P>(8) See Brooklyn Navy Yard Cogeneration Partners, L.P., 74 FERC &#182;
61,015 (1996).</P>
<P></P>
