<html>
<head>
<title>Competition, Telephones</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<h1>Competition, Telephones </h1>
<h1>and the New Marketplace</h1>
<p>
<h2><a href="/htm/bankoff.htm">Joseph R. Bankoff</a></h2>
<H6>This article originally appeared in the December 1995 issue of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Coproate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by permission.</H6>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
A few years from now we will look back on the change from monopoly to competition for local
telephone service as the dividing line between the old and the new information marketplace. The
change is not limited just to "who" provides local telephone services. There is a fundamental
change in "what" are telephone services. <p>

Traditional regulation of point to point voice communications is being completely reshaped by
new competitive and technology forces. These forces are creating big changes for all companies
that transport, create, sell, use or compete with information.<p>

Those in the old "local telephone" and "long distance" businesses are busy buying and selling
new technology and ventures. It is not idle talk. Billions of dollars are being invested to combine
traditional "cable", "movie", "television" and "telephone" businesses. Like the ancient alchemists
seeking a formula for gold - the modern search is to create greater value by mixing elements of
"content" and the "conduit" which carries the information.<p>

These markets, however, are subject to legal and regulatory overlays that have created a virtual
tower of Babel. The federal government through the FCC, the Justice Department and Judge
Greene, regulate parts of broadcast, cable, telephone and radio based telecom (cellular, PCS,
trunk radio). The states through the public service commissions regulate local and intra-state
communications. The local city governments regulate (for a fee) the cable franchise and access
to local utility right of way.<p>

In the early 1990's the Congress "re-regulated" the cable business when opinion polls showed
that people were tired of price gouging monopolies that provided indifferent service. There are
now bills pending before Congress seeking to require the states to open up their telecom markets
to new competition.<p>

Georgia, however, has already taken an important step in this new direction. In 1995 Georgia
enacted Senate Bill 137 which changes the state's reliance on public regulation to a reliance upon
private competition in the market. Under the new Georgia Act the role of the Public Service
Commission changes from master planning (comprehensive rate of return regulation) to
referee(protecting the competitive marketplace). A 5 year freeze in the price for single line
residential and business phones (universal service) is granted in exchange for permitting the
telephone companies to start setting prices for their other services.<p>

Georgia SB 137 opens the Georgia local telephone market to competition. The Act authorizes
new local service providers and requires that services needed to operate and interconnect to
existing networks be sold separately at non-discriminatory rates. The Act also allows the resale
of services purchased by one service provider from another.<p>

All this will have major impacts even on businesses that do not see themselves as being in the
"telecommunications" business.<p>
<ul>
  <li>	If you sell services to telephone companies - they will be getting smaller and much more
competitive.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
  <li>	If you sell to the public - they will increasingly demand that you provide them with immediate,
individualized and hassle free services with quality support at times that are convenient to them.
The new telecom will be the new weapon of choice in the competition for quality, service and
low unit cost.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
  <li>	If you are a big company - you have had your own network for some time. These changes will
convert you to a possible seller (and certainly a reuser) of your own business information. Both
your suppliers and your customers are likely to become new competitors.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
  <li>	If you are a small company - the increase in capacity and the lowing costs mean that you will
combine with other firms to provide competitive services on a "peer" basis with and to larger
firms.</li>
</ul>
In the "new" telecom market the line between "local" and "long distance" will disappear. The
growth of radio based communications will shift the telephone from communications to a
"place" to a "person" regardless of location. The binding together of firms and customers with
fiber, cable and radio lines of data, pictures will create new demands and new services. In next
few years the intense rivalry between phone, cable, wireless and power companies to provide
telecom will create remarkable opportunities for cost savings and new partnering.<p>
<p>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center>
</body>
</html>
