<html>
<head>
<title>Doing Business on the Internet</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<p>
<h1>Doing Business on the Internet:<br>Protection of Intellectual Property</h1>
<h2>Bradley A. Slutsky</h2>
<p><H6>An earlier version of this article originally appeared in the December 1995 issue of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by permission.</H6>
<HR></center>
<p>
With the rapid expansion of commerce on the Internet, the need to control and protect intellectual property on the Internet has increased dramatically.  Among the key emerging issues are questions of:<p>
<ul>
<li>How companies can protect their trademarks against domain name piracy</li>
</ul><p>
<ul><li>How companies can address trademark and copyright infringements on the Internet</li></ul><p>
<ul><li>How companies can address potential liability associated with providing Internet access</li></ul><p>
<ul><li>Jurisdictional considerations associated with doing business on the Internet</li></ul>
<h4>Protecting Trademarks Against Domain Name Piracy</h4>
Disputes over Internet domain names are occurring more and more frequently as companies begin to seek protection for the use of their trademarks in "cyberspace".  Hasbro, Inc. obtained an injunction prohibiting the Internet Entertainment Group from using the CANDYLAND name or the candyland.com domain name in connection with its adult-oriented World Wide Web site, MTV sued former "VJ" Adam Curry over the "mtv.com" domain name, <EM>see MTV Network v. Curry</EM>, 867 F. Supp. 202 (S.D.N.Y. 1994), and Kaplan Educational Centers is reputed to have won an arbitration against Princeton Review after Princeton Review registered the Internet domain name "kaplan.com".<p>

Unlike in "real space", in "cyberspace" it is not currently possible to resolve these disputes by permitting geographically disparate users to use the same name in different territories, or to use the same name in the same territories for different goods or services.  What should a company do if it finds "its" domain name taken?<p>

Network Solutions, Inc. ("NSI") is the entity responsible for allocating domain names on the Internet.  If someone is using your trademark as a domain name, you can provide NSI with a copy of your registration and, if the holder of the domain name does not also have a registration, the domain name will automatically be placed on hold (and thus will be unusable) until the dispute is resolved through traditional means. <EM>See </EM><a href="ftp://rs.internic.net/policy/internic.domain.policy"><EM>
ftp://rs.internic.net/policy/internic.domain.policy</EM></a>.<p>

<h4>Addressing Copyright And Trademark Infringements On The Internet</h4>
Suppose you are the author of a copyrighted work or the owner of a trademark, and a fan takes pieces of your work and places them on the Internet or uses your trademark in connection with a page on the World Wide Web.  In many cases, the only information you will initially have about the person is their e-mail address.  Do you send them a standard cease-and-desist letter by e-mail?  If you choose to follow this traditional route, be prepared to have millions of copies of your letter circulated around the world.<p>

It pays to think through this situation before sending a typical demand letter.  If you can logically explain the reasons for your concerns to a nonlawyer, you are less likely to encounter retaliation. A phone call, perhaps followed by a confirming letter, may be in order.  Such disputes can also be resolved by contacting the user's Internet Service Provider--particularly in light of recent legal decisions in this area.  Should litigation prove necessary, the practice of inserting "steganographic" signatures into data can be effective in demonstrating that materials were copied.<p>

<h4>Addressing Potential Liability For Providing Internet Access</h4>
Those who provide unfettered access to infringing materials on the Internet can be held liable as direct or contributory copyright infringers.  <EM>Compare <A HREF="http://www.cybercom.net/~rnewman/scientology/erlich/whyte-11.21.95">Religious Technology Center v. NETCOM On-Line Communication Services, Inc.</A>,</EM> No. C-95-20091 RMW (N.D. Cal. November 21, 1995) with <EM>Sega Enterprises, Ltd. v. MAPHIA, </EM>857 F. Supp. 679 (N.D. Cal. 1994) and <EM>Playboy Enterprises, Inc. v. Frena</EM>, 839 F. Supp. 1552 (M.D. Fla. 1993).  Even e-mail access to the Internet can expose one to such liability.<p>

On the other hand, too much editorial control over the contents of computer files can result in liability for defamatory statements "published" through one's computer network.  <EM>Compare Stratton Oakmont, Inc. v. Prodigy Services Co.</EM>, 23 Media L. Rep. 1794, 1995 N.Y. Misc. LEXIS 229 (S.Ct. N.Y. 1995) with <EM>Cubby, Inc. v. CompuServe, Inc.</EM>, 776 F. Supp.135 (S.D.N.Y. 1991). This puts access providers in a dilemma.  If they do not control users' actions, they can be held liable for copyright infringements.  If they control users' actions, they may be considered "publishers" and may face exposure in defamation cases.<p>

Well crafted policies and procedures can help decrease potential liability for providing access to the Internet.  The trick is to balance sensitivity to suspected or alleged infringements with limited editorial control over the contents of e-mail messages and other documents.<p>

<h4>Jurisdictional Considerations Associated With Doing Business On The
Internet</h4>
Suppose your World Wide Web home page says that your widget is 50% better than the brand X widget.  Also suppose your World Wide Web page is accessed by someone who resides in one of the many countries that prohibit comparative advertising.  Are you liable for violating foreign comparative advertising laws?
<p>
CompuServe recently restricted (but now has restored) access to various UseNet Newsgroups based on threats from the Bavarian government. Similarly, in <EM><A HREF="http://www.callaw.com/tommy.html">United States v. Thomas</A>, </EM> 1996 U.S. App. LEXIS 1069 (6th Cir. January 29, 1996), the United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit affirmed the conviction in Tennessee of a couple that distributed allegedly obscene images from a computer bulletin board in California.  The community standards in Tennessee were applied to determine whether the materials were obscene. The Minnesota Attorney General also recently sued six entities for offering allegedly fraudulent and/or illegal schemes to Minnesota residents over the Internet.  According to the Minnesota Attorney General, "persons outside of Minnesota who transmit information via the Internet knowing that information will be disseminated in
Minnesota are subject to jurisdiction in Minnesota courts for violations of state criminal and civil laws."  <EM>See <a href="http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/memo.txt">http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/memo.txt</a>.</EM><p>

Jurisdictional issues remain problematic.  Until generally accepted rules evolve, the "least
common denominator" may control what is safe and what is risky with respect to commerce on
the Internet.<p>

<h4>Conclusion</h4>
Although there are few "Internet law" precedents at this time, some early lessons have emerged. 
First, if you have taken the time and effort to register a trademark, you should register an Internet
domain name now, before someone beats you to it.  Second, think twice about using traditional
means to pursue infringers on the Internet.  If you send a standard cease and desist letter by
e-mail, you are playing on the infringer's turf.  Third, if you provide access to the Internet,
carefully crafted policies and procedures can help decrease your potential exposure to liability. 
Finally, it is important to consider the implications of potentially nation-wide or world-wide
jurisdiction over one's actions on the Internet.<p>

<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center>
</body>
</html>
