<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trend in Outsourcing</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<p>
<h1>Trends in Outsourcing</h1>
<h2>Steven J. de Groot</h2>
<H6>This article originally appeared in the December 1995 issue of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Coproate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by permission.</H6>
<HR><p>
<p></CENTER>
Ask five people in the "outsourcing industry" where the industry is today and where it will be
tomorrow and you'll get five different answers.  The industry has changed and will continue to
change rapidly; the future face of technology is uncertain.  These changes and uncertainties
make it difficult for the prognosticators to predict with any certainty what the outsourcing
landscape will look like tomorrow, much less years from now. <p>

Despite the uncertainties of the future landscape of the outsourcing industry, certain trends are
emerging in the way today's outsourcing deals are being done:<p>
<ul>
<li>A broader variety of enterprise functions are being outsourced today.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Outsourcing is being used as a stategic tool to add enterprise value.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Joint ventures and other types of strategic alliances are becoming more prevalent in structuring outsourcing deals.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Outsourcing deals today tend to have shorter lives than earlier deals.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li>A variety of economic models are being used to price outsourcing deals.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Many of yesterday's outsourcing deals are being restructured.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Consultants and lawyers are increasingly being used as a means of adding value to the
outsourcing process.</li>
</ul>
<h4>A Broader Variety of Functions are Being Outsourced</h4>
The types of enterprise functions being outsourced today have expanded dramatically in scope. 
Ten years ago management was hesitant to depend on third parties to undertake core
competencies at a time when outsourcing was a relatively new phenomenon.  As a result, to the
extent managers outsourced enterprise functions at all, they tended to outsource nonessential
functions such as payroll, accounts payable and other more mundane data processing functions. 
With the maturation of the outsourcing industry and the growth of proven niche outsourcing
vendors, managers are now outsourcing such "mission critical" functions as design, process and
quality control management, logistics, sales and customer support, telecommunications,
LAN/WAN management, applications development, maintenance and training, help desk, and
human resource management.<p>

<h4>Outsourcing is Being Used as a Tool to Add Value</h4>
More than simply a means to reduce enterprise costs, management is now looking at outsourcing
as a strategic tool to add value to the enterprise and  help achieve and/or maintain a competitive
edge in the marketplace.  Cost reduction remains a significant driver in many of today's decisions
to outsource.  However, management is increasingly insisting that the outsourcing vendor
perform the outsourced function more efficiently, effectively and creatively, and in a manner that
assists the outsourcer to maintain a competitive edge in the market.  The decision to outsource is
as often a strategic one as it is an economic one.<p>

<h4>There is an Increased Focus on the Relational Aspects of Outsourcing</h4>
Outsourcers and vendors are beginning to focus on the relational aspects of outsourcing
transactions; hence more transactions are being structured as joint ventures, partnerships and
other types of strategic alliances.  While the "service contract" model of outsourcing continues to
be the norm, outsourcers and vendors are becoming more creative in the structuring of their
arrangements.  Such creativity is permitting outsourcers and their vendors to take advantage of
risk and cost sharing, as well as capture the synergies resulting from their alliances. <p>

<h4>Use of the "One-Stop" Shopping vs. Integrator Model</h4>
The "one-stop" shopping approach to vendor selection is giving way to a paradigm that typically
includes a large vendor serving as the integrator of a number of "niche vendor" outsourcing
arrangements.  Increasingly, these integrators are managing outsourcing arrangements which
have components being performed by telecom, applications development and maintenance, help
desk, sales and customer support, and other specialty vendors.<p>

<h4>More Deals Have Shorter Lives</h4>
Today's outsourcing deals tend to have shorter terms than those of even a few years ago.  Most
of today's vendors prefer long-term deals, permitting the vendor to lock up customers, take
advantage of historical reductions in the cost of technology and amortize the "up-front" costs of
their investment in the customer over a longer period of time.  Conversely, outsourcers are
typically seeking shorter terms (e.g., 3-5 years) to preserve vendor flexibility as new players
enter the outsourcing arena and enterprise needs change, and to take advantage of historical cost
reductions and advancements in technology.<p>

<h4>Creative Pricing Models are Being Utilized</h4>
Fixed fees pricing models, now generally a small component of any outsourcing deal, are being
replaced by a variety of variable pricing schemes, including per unit (e.g., per call, CPU, seat,
server, MIP), technology replacement and refresh, indexing and benchmarking schemes.  As
outsourcing services become more of a commodity in today's market, outsourcers are
increasingly insisting on provisions that require their vendors to price and provide their services
on market terms.  Additionally, many outsourcing economic models are incorporating
"benchmarking" schemes which reward and/or penalize the vendor for meeting or failing to meet
stated objectives or benchmarks.<p>

<h4>Old Outsourcing Arrangements are Being Restructured</h4>
Increasingly, many outsourcing deals being entered into today are actually restructures of
existing outsourcing arrangements.  Deals are being restructured today for a variety of reasons,
including changes in technology and the cost of technology, migrations of the outsourcer's
business that requires changes in the IT function, management changes, competition in the
outsourcing marketplace and entities' increasing use of outsourcing to gain a competitive edge in
the marketplace.<p>

<h4>Consultants and Lawyers are Being Used to Add Value</h4>
The use of consultants and lawyers as a means of adding value to the outsourcing process is
becoming prevalent.  It has long been an industry paradox that, while a significant corporate
transaction has historically attracted teams of financial advisors, consultants and lawyers to
undertake the task at hand, many outsourcing transactions involving significantly greater sums of
money have garnered little attention from groups other than the organization's management
information personnel.  This approach appears to be changing as outsourcing entities are
increasingly utilizing outside consultants and lawyers to add value to the outsourcing process. 
Entities are recognizing that in arrangements which include the payment of significant sums of
money, and perhaps more importantly, the entrustment of "mission critical" functions to outside
parties, it is important that the deal be structured and documented in a manner that adequately
protects the interests of the outsourcer.<p>

As the outsourcing industry continues to evolve from the "cottage" industry it was ten years ago
and the multi-billion dollar industry it is today, outsourcers, vendors and their consultants and
counsel will continue to be challenged by the array of issues such evolution inevitably spawns.<p>
<p>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
