<TITLE>Jurisdiction Over Commerce On The Internet</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">Jurisdiction Over Commerce On The Internet</H1>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B><FONT SIZE="+5"><FONT SIZE="+2"><a
name="TEXT1">Bradley A. Slutsky</a>
<FONT SIZE="-3"><a href="#FN1">(1)</a></FONT></FONT></FONT></B></P>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">An earlier version of this article was published in the
September, 1996 and November, 1996 issues of <I>The DataLaw Report</I>. </H6>
<HR>
<H2>I.   Introduction</H2>
<P>The process of conducting commercial transactions over the Internet can take
several forms.  For instance, a business can advertise its goods or services
using electronic mail, through Usenet newsgroups, and over the World Wide Web. 
Similarly, a business can accept orders by various methods, including by
electronic mail and through a World Wide Web site.  It also has become possible
for a number of businesses to fill orders over the Internet.  If the goods or
services that are being ordered consist of digital information, that information
can be sent to users as an attachment to an electronic mail message, users can
be given access to the information through File Transfer Protocol, or users can
download the information directly from a World Wide Web site.</P>
<P>In such transactions, the seller may be located in one jurisdiction, the
buyer may be located in another jurisdiction, the computer that sends or
receives the electronic mail messages or the hypertext transfer protocol
messages of the World Wide Web may be located in another jurisdiction, and the
computers in between the buyer and the seller which facilitate their
communications likely are located in one or more other jurisdictions.</P>
<P>The laws that govern the commercial transaction between the seller and the
buyer traditionally have been territorial in nature.  Federalist and social
contract theories of government teach us that &quot;the people are the only
legitimate fountain of power, and it is from them that the constitutional
charter, under which the several branches of government hold their power, is
derived&quot;.  The Federalist No. 49 (Alexander Hamilton or James Madison).  In
other words, &quot;the persons within a geographically defined border are the
ultimate source of law-making authority for activities within that border.&quot;
 David R. Johnson and David G. Post, <a href="http://www.cli.org/X0025_LBFIN.html">Law
and Borders--The Rise of Law in Cyberspace</a>, ___ Stan. L. Rev. ___ (1996) (hereinafter Rise
of Law in Cyberspace). 
Thus, as the United States Supreme Court has noted, &quot;[a]ll legislation is
prima facie territorial.&quot; <U>American Banana Co. v. United Fruit Co.</U>, 213 U.S.
347, 357 (1909).  These principles typically also are inherent in our domestic
view of the power of foreign sovereigns. <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, Restatement (Third) of
Foreign Relations Law of the United States &#167; 201 (1987) (&quot;Under
international law, a state is an entity that has a defined territory and a
permanent population, under the control of its own government ... .&quot;); <U>Id.</U> &#167;
402 (a state has &quot;jurisdiction to  prescribe law with respect to (1)(a)
conduct that, wholly or in substantial part, takes place within its territory;
(b) the status of persons, or interests in things, present within its territory;
(c) conduct outside its territory that has or is intended to have substantial
effect within its territory ... .&quot;)</P>
<P>Thus, if a buyer and seller both are located in the same state in the United
States, the law governing their transaction typically will be the law of the
state in which the transaction occurred, unless the parties agree to apply the
law of another jurisdiction and that jurisdiction has a reasonable relationship
to the transaction.  <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, 15A C.J.S. Conflict of Laws &#167;&#167;
11(4)a,b.  If the buyer is located in one jurisdiction and the seller is located
in another, we have choice of law rules that govern which law applies.  In
contract cases, the law of the jurisdiction where the contract was created--the
lex loci contractus-- typically will govern.  <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, 15A C.J.S. Conflict of
Laws &#167;&#167; 11(1),(2).  In tort cases, the law of the jurisdiction where
the harm was suffered--the lex loci delicti--often will govern.  <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, 15A
C.J.S. Conflict of Laws &#167;&#167; 12(2)b.</P>
<P>The Internet breaks down barriers between physical jurisdictions.  When a
buyer and seller consummate a commercial transaction through a World Wide Web
site, there is no need for the traditional physical acts that often determine
which jurisdiction's law will apply and whether the buyer or seller will be
subject to personal jurisdiction in the courts where the other is located.</P>
<P>Thus, in assessing whether and under what circumstances governments can
assert jurisdiction over commerce on the Internet, it also is relevant to ask
whether and under what circumstances they should assert such jurisdiction.  In
other words, to what extent should we force old models and analogies on this new
way of communicating and doing business?  While this topic easily could form the
subject of an entirely separate paper, there are at least two issues one should
consider when approaching this problem.  First, because physical jurisdiction
boundaries typically have delineated legal boundaries as well, we have come to
expect that &quot;[p]roper boundaries have signposts that provide warning that
we will be required, after crossing, to abide by different rules ... .&quot;  <a
href="http://www.cli.org/X0025_LBFIN.html">Rise of Law In Cyberspace</a>, ___ Stanford
Law Review at ___.  Since &quot;Cyberspace
has no territorially- based boundaries&quot;, &quot;[t]he Net thus radically
subverts a system of rule-making based on borders between physical spaces&quot;.  <U>Id.</U> 
Second, as was noted in <a
href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Comm_Decency_Act/HTML/960612_aclu_v_reno_decision.html">American Civil Liberties Union v. Reno</a>, &quot;[i]t
is no exaggeration to conclude that the Internet has achieved, and continues to
achieve, the most participatory marketplace of mass speech that this country - -
and indeed the world -- has yet seen.&quot;  929 F. Supp. 824, 881 (E.D. Pa.
1996).  As such, many believe that &quot;the Internet deserves the broadest
possible protection from government-imposed, content-based regulation.&quot; 
<U>Id.</U></P>
<P>Substantive and procedural law often vary from  jurisdiction to
jurisdiction.  Thus, the questions of what laws govern transactions over the
Internet and where the buyer and seller are subject to jurisdiction can be
important.  This article analyzes those questions in the context of Internet
transactions involving electronic mail, Usenet posts, and World Wide Web sites. 
While the law in this area still is somewhat unsettled, it seems fair to say
that electronic mail messages targeted at specific recipients in identifiable
locations probably can give rise to jurisdiction over the sender in the
recipients' locations.  Further, if the messages violate the laws of the
recipients' locations the sender likely can be judged by those laws.  For Usenet
posts and World Wide Web sites, the analysis is more difficult.  While there are
significant legal and policy-based defenses to jurisdiction in such cases, the
recent trend of court decisions seems to indicate that jurisdiction may be
asserted over the sender or seller conducting business through Usenet or the
World Wide Web, particularly if the identity and location of the buyer is known
to the seller.</P>
<H2>II. Electronic Mail Transactions</H2>
<P>Sending e-mail to an individual whose location is known to the sender is
similar to sending regular mail addressed to an individual at a known location. 
Thus, one could argue that there is little reason not to exercise jurisdiction
over the sender in the location to which the e-mail was sent.
 <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, <U>McGee v. International Life Insurance Co.</U>, 355 U.S.
220, 222-24 (1957) (&quot;Today
many commercial transactions touch two or more States and may involve parties
separated by the full continent.  With this increasing nationalization of
commerce has come a great increase in the amount of business conducted by mail
across state lines.  At the same time modern transportation and communication
have made it much less burdensome for a party sued to defend himself in a State
where he engages in economic activity.  ...  It is sufficient for purposes of
due process that the suit was based on a contract which had substantial
connection with that State.  [cit. om.]  The contract was delivered in
California, the premiums were mailed from there and the insured was a resident
of that State when he died.  It cannot be denied that California has a manifest
interest in providing effective means of redress for its residents when their
insurers refuse to pay claims.  These residents would be at a severe
disadvantage if they were forced to follow the insurance company to a distant
State in order to hold it legally accountable.  When claims were small or
moderate individual claimants frequently could not afford the cost of bringing
an action in a foreign forum -- thus in effect making the company judgment
proof.  ...  Of course there may be inconvenience to the insurer if it is held
amenable to suit in California where it had this contract but certainly nothing
which amounts to a denial of due process.&quot;).</P>
<P>There are, however, complicating factors introduced by the technology of the
Internet.  For instance, if one sends e-mail to JohnDoe@CompuServe.com, Mr. Doe
could be located almost anywhere in the world, as CompuServe has subscribers
throughout the world.  If one sends e-mail to JohnDoe@atlanta.com, Mr. Doe could
have implemented a &quot;forward&quot; file that forwards his mail from his
computer in Atlanta, Georgia to anywhere in the world.  If one sends e-mail to
JohnDoe@alpha.c2.org (alpha.c2.org is a re-mailer designed to maintain the
anonymity of those with accounts there), not only does one not know where Mr.
Doe is located, but Mr. Doe has specifically taken steps to try to ensure that
one does not know where he is located.  As the District Court recognized in <a
href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Comm_Decency_Act/HTML/960612_aclu_v_reno_decision.html">ACLU v. Reno</a>, &quot;[a]n e-mail address provides no authoritative information
about the addressee, who may use an e-mail 'alias' or an anonymous remailer.&quot; 
929 F. Supp. at 845.  &quot;With the possible exception of an e-mail to a known
recipient, most content providers cannot determine the identity and age of every
user accessing their material.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at 854.  Thus, except for e-mail sent
to a known recipient, it may be difficult to say that e-mail distribution is a
method by which a company &quot;purposefully avail[s] itself of the privilege of
conducting activities within the [recipient's] forum State.&quot; <U>Hanson v. Denckla</U>,
357 U.S. 235, 253 (1958).</P>
<H2>III.  Advertising Through Usenet Newsgroups</H2>
<P>Posting commercial information to Usenet newsgroups is, in some ways,
similar to sending e-mail.  In other ways, however, it is completely different. 
In the case of a Usenet post, the poster knows or should know that their post
will be sent to computers in every State in the United States and in many
locations throughout the world.  <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, <a
href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Comm_Decency_Act/HTML/960612_aclu_v_reno_decision.html">ACLU v. Reno</a>, 929 F. Supp. at 835 (&quot;USENET
newsgroups are disseminated using ad hoc, peer to peer connections between
approximately 200,000 computers (called USENET 'servers') around the world.&quot;).
 The poster does not necessarily know, however, that their post will be received
and read by a person in any particular location (although the poster of a
commercial advertisement presumably hopes that the advertisement will be
distributed and read as widely as possible).  If a fraudulent sale is made by
delivering worthless goods to the recipient's location, that presumably would
provide an independent basis for jurisdiction.  If, however, the post is alleged
to be harmful in itself (perhaps because it is libelous or solicits
participation in a &quot;scam&quot;), the jurisdiction issue becomes more
difficult.</P>
<P>The fact that it is foreseeable that a Usenet post may end up in a
particular jurisdiction probably is not, alone, sufficient to give rise to
jurisdiction.  <U>See</U>, <U>e.g.</U>, <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27444+u!2Es!2E+286!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27444+u!2Es!2E+286!27]/doc/{@298303}/hit_headings?">World-Wide
Volkswagen Corp. v. Woodson</a>, 444 U.S. 286,
297-98 (1979) (&quot;the foreseeability that is critical to due process analysis
is not the mere likelihood that a product will find its way into the forum
State.  Rather, it is that the defendant's conduct and connection with the forum
State are such that he should reasonably anticipate being haled into court
there.  ...  The forum State does not exceed its powers under the Due Process 
Clause if it asserts personal jurisdiction over a corporation that delivers its
products into the stream of commerce with the expectation that they will be
purchased by consumers in the forum State.&quot;).  The law is somewhat
unsettled, however, with respect to whether knowledge that the post will be
received in the jurisdiction is sufficient, <U>see</U> <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27465+u!2Es!2E+770!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27465+u!2Es!2E+770!27]/doc/{@203551}/hit_headings?">Keeton v.
Hustler Magazine, Inc.</a>, 465 U.S. 770, 774 (1983) (&quot;Such regular monthly sales of
thousands of magazines cannot by any stretch of the imagination be characterized as random,
isolated, or fortuitous.&quot;), or whether additional conduct is required.  <U>See</U>
<a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+102!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+102!27]/doc/{@143486}/hit_headings?">Asahi Metal
Industry, Inc. v. Superior Court of California, Solano County</a>, 480
U.S. 102, 112 (1987) (&quot;Additional conduct of the defendant may indicate an
intent or purpose to serve the market in the forum State, for example, designing
the product for the market in the forum State, advertising in the forum State,
establishing channels for providing regular advice to customers in the forum
State, or marketing the product through a distributor who has agreed to serve as
the sales agent in the forum State.  But a defendant's awareness that the stream
of commerce may or will sweep the product into the forum State does not convert
the mere act of placing the product into the stream of commerce into an act
purposefully directed toward the forum State.&quot;) (plurality decision). 
Regardless of one's ability to control the destination of one's communication,
however, if the communication is calculated to cause injury in a specific
geographic location one will be subject to jurisdiction there.  <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27465+u!2Es!2E+783!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27465+u!2Es!2E+783!27]/doc/{@203502}/hit_headings?">Calder v.
Jones</a>, 465 U.S. 783, 789-90 (1983) (&quot;petitioners are not charged with mere
untargeted negligence.  ... [T]hey knew that the brunt of that injury would be
felt by respondent in the State in which she lives and works and in which the
National Enquirer has its largest circulation.  Under the circumstances,
petitioners must 'reasonably anticipate being haled into court there' to answer
for the truth of the statements made in their article.&quot;).</P>
<H2>IV. Commerce Over The World Wide Web</H2>
<P>The issues raised by World Wide Web sites are slightly more difficult.  In
the case of a Usenet post, the poster at least undertook some action
specifically designed to send the communication to computers outside of their
location.  In so doing, they knew or should have known that their post would end
up residing on computers in every state in the United States and in many foreign
countries, and it probably is fair to assume that one who posts commercial
advertising hopes and perhaps anticipates that the advertising will be read in
those locations.  The unpredictable element, in that circumstance, is whether
the advertisement will be read by a person--not whether the post will find its
way into a particular foreign jurisdiction.  In the case of a World Wide Web
site, there is no way for a person to know, in advance, where the materials on
the Web site will be received.  &quot;[T]he creation and posting of a Web site
allows users anywhere in the country [and in many places throughout the world]
to see that site&quot;. <a
href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Comm_Decency_Act/HTML/960612_aclu_v_reno_decision.html">ACLU v. Reno</a>, 929 F. Supp. at 878.  One can take steps
to try to encourage the viewing of one's Web Site by users in certain locations
(such as by advertising the Web site in local newspapers or placing links to the
Web site on other Web sites that would be of interest to people in specific
geographic locations).  Perhaps such steps would amount to the &quot;additional
conduct&quot; that the plurality in <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+102!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+102!27]/doc/{@143486}/hit_headings?">Asahi</a>
sought to require.  One also can fail
to take steps to prohibit users in certain locations from accessing one's Web
site.  For instance, one can require registration and a password to view a World
Wide Web site, and part of the registration process could involve verification
of the user's address.  One also can attempt to restrict access to a World Wide
Web site to users at certain Internet domains, although such efforts usually
will not be successful<a name="TEXT2">.</a><a href="#FN2">(2)</a> The failure to take such
steps, however, may not be sufficient to give rise to jurisdiction.  <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+112!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+112!27]/doc/{@143536}/hit_headings?">Asahi
Metal</a>, 480 U.S. at 112 (&quot;a defendant's awareness that the stream of commerce may or
will sweep the product into the forum State does not convert the mere act of placing the product
into the stream into an act purposefully directed toward the forum State.&quot;);
<a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27444+u!2Es!2E+297!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27444+u!2Es!2E+297!27]/doc/{@298341}/hit_headings?">World-Wide
Volkswagen</a>, 444 U.S. at 297 (&quot;the foreseeability that is
critical to due process analysis is not the mere likelihood that a product will
find its way into the forum State.&quot;).</P>
<P>Nevertheless, the Minnesota Attorney General has taken the position that
those who solicit business over the Internet as a whole, such as through a World
Wide Web site, are subject to jurisdiction in Minnesota if the information can
be viewed by Minnesota residents.  The Minnesota Attorney General has filed at
least six lawsuits against out-of-state residents in connection with on-line
activities that allegedly are harmful to Minnesota residents.  <U>See</U>
<a href="http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/">http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/</a>.  The
alleged activities of the various
defendants include:  allegedly false claims about the health benefits of &quot;germanium&quot;;
the alleged sale of information about using two-cent stamps instead of
thirty-two-cent stamps to save money; a credit repair service that allegedly
recommends the use of an Employer Identification Number (instead of a Social
Security Number) when applying for credit; an alleged pyramid scheme; a Web site
&quot;advertising&quot; that a company is &quot;planning&quot; to offer an
on-line gambling service; and the alleged sale of information about making money
by locating people who are owed money by HUD.</P>
<P>According to a brief filed by the Minnesota Attorney General in response to
a motion to dismiss one of those cases for lack of personal jurisdiction, &quot;courts
have repeatedly held in consumer enforcement cases that defendants who advertise
or solicit business within a state have the requisite minimum contacts with that
state.&quot;  <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/brief.txt">http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/brief.txt</a>, pg. 22.  The
Minnesota Attorney General argues that contacts with the nation as a whole,
though not directed at any particular State, are sufficient for jurisdiction.  <U>Id.</U> at 23-24
(<U>citing</U> <U>Tobin v. Astra Pharmaceutical Prod.</U>, 993 F.2d 528, 543-44 (6th Cir.),
<U>cert.</U> <U>denied</U>, 510 U.S. 914 (1993); <U>A. Uberti &amp; C. v.
Leonardo</U>,
892 P.2d 1354, 1362 (Ariz.), <U>cert.</U> <U>denied</U>, __ U.S. __, 116 S. Ct.  273 (1995);
<U>In re Minnesota Asbestos Litig.</U>, 540 N.W.2d 896, 901-02 (Mn. Ct. App. 1995),
<U>review</U> <U>granted</U> (Minn. Feb. 9, 1996); and <U>Sunrise Specialty Contracting 
v. S.A.
Komet</U>, No. C7-92-924, 1992 WL 295127 *1, *2  (Minn.  Ct. App. Oct. 20, 1992)). 
In fact, this position may draw some support from the 1993 amendment to Federal
Rule of Civil Procedure 4.  Rule 4(k)(2), which was added in 1993, provides that
for claims arising under federal law, service of process may be made on a
foreign entity that has sufficient contacts with the United States as a whole,
even if the entity does not have sufficient contacts with any individual State
to be subject to jurisdiction in any individual State based on those contacts.</P>
<P>The Minnesota Attorney General's brief goes on to argue as follows:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The Attorney General is not maintaining that anyone who places information
on the Internet is subject to jurisdiction in Minnesota.  The Attorney General
is contending that businesses who advertise to Minnesota residents on the
Internet, seeking business from all who view those advertisements, are subject
to Minnesota's consumer protection statutes.</P>
<P>Defendants also claim that the facts of this case are similar to a Minnesota
resident going to a library, seeing an advertisement for a business in an
out-of-state phone book and then calling that business for further information. 
This analogy is a gross understatement of defendants'  activities and, once
again, ignores the nature of their advertising contacts with Minnesota. 
Defendants have not placed their advertisements in a place, such as an
out-of-state phone book in a library, where advertisers would not reasonably
anticipate that a consumer would view it.  Defendants' conduct is much more
purposeful. Indeed each time a Minnesota computer user views defendants'
advertisements an electronic impulse is sent into Minnesota.  [cit. om.]  A more
accurate parallel to defendants' purposeful and continuous advertising conduct
would be the placement of an enormous billboard directly across the state's
borders.  Defendants' actions are also similar to the placing of an
advertisement in a nationally distributed magazine listing an 800 number for
consumers to call to receive further information, and then giving out
information to all consumers who call in, regardless of where the consumer
lives.  <U>See</U> <U>Classic Auto Sales</U>, 832 P.2d at 234 (upholding jurisdiction where
plaintiff saw advertisement and then called for more information).  ... 
Defendants, like advertisers in other media, place their advertisements where
Minnesota consumers are sure to read them.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><a
href="http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/brief.txt">http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/brief.txt</a>, pp. 30-32.</P>
<P>In one of the cases brought by the Minnesota Attorney General, the defendant responded to
the complaint by filing a motion to dismiss for lack of personal jurisdiction.  The Minnesota state
trial court denied the motion and upheld the arguments asserted by the Attorney General.  The
court noted that "[i]n matters of consumer protection, courts routinely hold that out of state
defendants soliciting in-state residents have purposely availed themselves of the privilege of
conducting business within the State. ... Here, Rogers and WagerNet maintain a Web-site which
can be accessed by any Internet user, and which logically appears to be maintained for the purpose
and in anticipation of being accessed and used by any and all Internet users, including Minnesota
residents.  This activity certainly arises to the type of promotional activity or active solicitation to
provide the minimum contacts necessary for exercising personal jurisdiction over non-residents."
 <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.ag.state.mn.us/consumer/news/OnlineScams/ggOrder.html">State of
Minnesota v. Granite Gate Resorts, Inc.</a>, No. C6-95-7227 (Minn. Dist. Ct., 2d Dist,
December, 1996).  The court also noted that the factors of
inconvenience, and whether the defendants could reasonably anticipate being sued in Minnesota,
weighed in favor of jurisdiction, because the defendants' Web site apparently contained a notice
that the defendants "can either sue you [their customers] in your State or Belize."  <U>Id.</U> 
The court thus held that the defendants were not in a position to assert that it was inconvenient or
unanticipated for them to be in court in Minnesota.  <U>Id.</U></P>
<P>The Illinois Attorney General apparently has brought a series of similar suits, and the Texas
Attorney General has expressed similar views regarding jurisdiction.  <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.oag.state.tx.us/WEBSITE/OPENGOVT/OPINIONS/OPINIONS/dm-344.txt">Texas Attorney General Opinion DM-344</a> (&quot;A third party's operation of a
bulletin board service, by means of which he knowingly assisted persons in
playing and betting on card games located on that bulletin board service and
charged for the services used by the persons playing the game, would violate one
or more of the penal provisions of chapter 47, Penal Code.&quot;).</P>
<P>In contrast, the Florida Attorney General has concluded that regulation of
Internet activities is a matter for national or international authorities,
rather than a matter that states should address individually.  According to
Florida's Attorney General, &quot;any effort to regulate the use of the Internet
is better suited to federal regulation than to patchwork attention by the
individual states.  Evolving technology appears to be far outstripping the
ability of government to regulate gambling activities on the Internet and of law
enforcement to enforce such regulations. Thus, resolution of these matters must
be addressed at the national, if not international, level.&quot;  <a
href="http://legal1.firn.edu/ago.nsf/aaee37715760bbce852563cc001bacf7/5bfc8db232c406828525626900683218?OpenDocument">Florida Attorney General Formal Opinion 95-70</a>.</P>
<P>After <U>McGee</U>, there seemingly is little problem in asserting jurisdiction
over an entity that knowingly engages in a transaction with a resident of a
particular state.  As the Minnesota Attorney General noted, &quot;[t]he fact
that a transaction is conducted entirely by 'telephone, mail and facsimile is of
no significant consequence when the defendant purposefully avails itself of
conducting activities within the forum state....'  <U>Marquette</U>, 270 N.W.2d at
295-96; <U>see</U> <U>also</U> <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27471+u!2Es!2E+476!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27471+u!2Es!2E+476!27]/doc/{@177823}/hit_headings?">Burger
King</a>, 471 U.S. at 476, 105 S. Ct. at 2184.&quot; 
<a
href="http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/brief.txt">http://www.state.mn.us/ebranch/ag/brief.txt</a>, pg. 23.</P>
<P>Similarly, the Supreme Court has cleared the way for the application of
varying standards based on the varying laws of the jurisdictions in which
defendants may find themselves sued. <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27492+u!2Es!2E+115!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27492+u!2Es!2E+115!27]/doc/{@96015}/hit_headings?">Sable
Communications of California, Inc. v. F.C.C.</a>, 492 U.S. 115, 125 (1989) (&quot;the fact that
'distributors of allegedly obscene materials may be subjected to varying community standards in
the various federal judicial districts into which they transmit the materials
does not render a federal statute unconstitutional because of the failure of
uniform national standards of obscenity.'&quot;).  According to the Supreme
Court,</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>While Sable may be forced to incur some costs in developing and implementing
a system for screening the locale of incoming calls, there is no constitutional
impediment to enacting a law which may impose such costs on a medium electing to
provide these messages.  ...  If Sable's audience is comprised of different
communities with different local standards, Sable ultimately bears the burden of
complying with the prohibition on obscene messages.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><U>Id.</U> at 125-26.</P>
<P>A recent application of these principles can be seen in <a
href="http://www.leepfrog.com/E-Law/Cases/US_v_Thomas2.html">United States v.
Thomas</a>, 74 F.3d 701 (6th Cir. 1996), <U>cert.</U> <U>denied</U>, ___ U.S. ___, 117 S.
Ct. 74 (1996).  The defendants in that case operated the
Amateur Action Computer Bulletin Board System from their home in California.  A
United States Postal Inspector located in Tennessee called the bulletin board,
registered under an assumed name, and viewed various graphics files.  The
defendants asserted that venue was improper in the Western District of Tennessee
because &quot;it was Dirmeyer, a government agent, who, without their knowledge,
accessed and downloaded the GIF files and caused them to enter Tennessee&quot;. 
<U>Id.</U> at 709.  The Sixth Circuit noted that &quot;'there is no constitutional
impediment to the government's power to prosecute pornography dealers in any
district into which the material is sent.'&quot;  <U>Id.</U>  The Court found that
pornography is a continuing offense &quot;'that occurs in every judicial
district which the material touches'  ... [and that] 'venue for federal
obscenity prosecutions lies &quot;in any district from, through, or into which&quot;
the allegedly obscene material moves.'&quot;  <U>Id.</U>  The Court also noted that
materials from the bulletin board system &quot;were distributed to an approved
AABBS member known to reside in the Western District of Tennessee.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> 
These jurisdictional considerations &quot;'may result in prosecutions of persons
in a community to which they have sent material which is obscene under that
community's standards though the community from which it is sent would tolerate
the same material' ... [for] it is not unconstitutional to subject  interstate
distributors of obscenity to varying community standards.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at 711.</P>
<P>Another case finding jurisdiction based on electronic transmissions into a
state is <a
href="http://www.leepfrog.com/E-Law/Cases/Compuserve_v_Patterson.html">CompuServe, Inc.
v. Patterson</a>, 89 F.3d 1257 (6th Cir. 1996).  In that
case, the United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit reversed the
District Court and held that a shareware author who sold his shareware though
CompuServe's shareware registration system was subject to jurisdiction in Ohio. 
CompuServe sued Patterson in Ohio seeking a declaratory judgment that CompuServe
had not infringed Patterson's trademarks for certain computer software packages.
 Although Patterson never had set foot in Ohio and had sold his software to but
12 Ohio residents (for a total of less than $650), the Court found that
Patterson had purposefully availed himself of the privilege of doing business in
Ohio.  The Sixth Circuit relied on the Supreme Court's decision in World-Wide
Volkswagen for the proposition that &quot;the confluence of the 'increasing
nationalization of commerce' and 'modern transportation and communication,' [has
resulted in the] relaxation of the limits that the Due Process Clause imposes 
on courts' jurisdiction.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at 1262.  The Court found that there was &quot;no
question&quot; that Patterson had taken steps to create a connection with Ohio:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>He subscribed to CompuServe, and then he entered into the Shareware
Registration Agreement when he loaded his software onto the CompuServe system
for others to use and, perhaps, purchase.  Once Patterson had done those two
things, he was on notice that he had made contracts, to be governed by Ohio law,
with an Ohio-based company.  Then, he repeatedly sent his computer software, via
electronic links, to the CompuServe system in Ohio, and he advertised that
software on the CompuServe system.  Moreover, he initiated the events that led
to the filing of this suit by making demands of CompuServe via electronic and
regular mail messages.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><U>Id.</U> at 1264.  The Court noted that &quot;[a]dmittedly, merely entering into
a contract with CompuServe would not, without more, establish that Patterson had
minimum contacts with Ohio.  [cit. om.]  By the same token, Patterson's
injection of his software product into the stream of commerce, without more,
would be at best a dubious ground for jurisdiction.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at 1265. 
Nevertheless, because Patterson had done both of these things and more, the
Court found that Patterson was subject to jurisdiction in Ohio.</P>
<P>In the context of World Wide Web sites, a District Court in New York applied
similar reasoning to hold an Italian company in contempt of court in the United
States.  In <a
href="http://zeus.bna.com/e-law/cases/playmen.html">Playboy Enterprises, Inc. v. Chuckleberry
Publishing, Inc.</a>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 8435, 39 U.S.P.Q.2d 1746 (S.D.N.Y. 1996), a
group of companies had been enjoined in 1981 from &quot;using 'PLAYBOY', 'PLAYMEN' or
any other word confusingly similar ... in connection with the sale, offering for sale or
distributing in the United States, importing into or exporting from the United
States, English language publications and related products.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at *4, 39
U.S.P.Q.2d at 1748.  The defendants had (in 1981) been distributing in the
United States a magazine called &quot;Playmen&quot;.  Playboy obtained an
injunction against the publication of the magazine in the United States and in
several other countries, but was unsuccessful in obtaining an injunction in
Italy.  The defendants thus continued to publish &quot;Playmen&quot; in Italy.</P>
<P>Around 1995, the defendants created a &quot;Playmen&quot; World Wide Web
site at http://www.playmen.it.  When Playboy discovered the site, it brought a
contempt proceeding.  The primary question before the court, in determining
whether the defendants were in contempt, was whether the defendants had used the
name &quot;PLAYMEN&quot; &quot;in connection with the sale, offering for sale or
distributing in the United States, importing into or exporting from the United
States, English language publications and related products.&quot;  The
defendants argued that they were</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>merely posting pictorial images on a computer server in Italy, rather than
distributing those images to anyone within the United States.  A computer
operator wishing to view these images must, in effect, transport himself to
Italy to view Tattilo's pictorial displays.  The use of the Internet is akin to
boarding a plane, landing in Italy, and purchasing a copy of PLAYMEN magazine,
an activity permitted under Italian law.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><U>Id.</U> at *21, 39 U.S.P.Q.2d at 1752.  The Court, however, disagreed.  The
Court found that the</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Defendant has actively solicited United States customers to its Internet
site, and in doing so has distributed its product within the United States. 
When a potential subscriber faxes the required form to Tattilo, he receives back
via e-mail a password and user name.  By this process, Tattilo distributes its
product within the United States.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><U>Id.</U> at *21-22, 39 U.S.P.Q.2d at 1752.  Recognizing the territorial limits of
its authority, the court held that the defendants could continue to maintain
their World Wide Web site, but the court prohibited the defendants from
accepting subscriptions from customers in the United States.</P>
<P>More troubling, however, is the court's expansion of its opinion in
connection with a motion for reconsideration.  <U>See</U> <U>Playboy Enterprises, Inc. v.
Chuckleberry Publishing, Inc.</U>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 9865 (S.D.N.Y. 1996).  On
reconsideration, the court clarified its ruling with respect to the
non-subscription portion of the Playmen World Wide Web site--the portion that
could be visited without the defendants knowing the identities or locations of
the users viewing the site.  The court held that the fact that users &quot;pull&quot;
the images from a computer in Italy rather than having the transaction initiate
in Italy &quot;is irrelevant.  By inviting United States users to download these
images, Tattilo is causing and contributing to their distribution within the
United States.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at *9.  The Court thus required the defendants to
&quot;either shut down PLAYMEN Lite completely or prohibit United States users from
accessing the site in the future.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at *11.</P>
<P>Using similar reasoning, a District Court in Connecticut found that a
Massachusetts company was subject to jurisdiction in Connecticut based merely on
the Massachusetts company's use of an Internet domain and an 800 number that
were accessible from Connecticut.  <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.leepfrog.com/E-Law/Cases/Inset_v_Instruction.html">Inset Systems, Inc. v.
Instruction Set, Inc.</a>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 7160 (D. Conn. April 17, 1996).  According to
the Court, &quot;[t]he Internet as well as toll-free numbers are designed to
communicate with people and their businesses in every state.  Advertisement on
the Internet can reach as many as 10,000 Internet users within Connecticut
alone.  Further, once posted on the Internet, unlike television and radio
advertising, the advertisement is available continuously to any Internet user.
[The defendant] has therefore, purposefully availed itself of the privilege of
doing business within Connecticut.   ... [S]ince [the defendant] purposefully
directed its advertising activities toward this state on a continuing basis
since March, 1995, it could reasonably anticipate the possibility of being
hailed into court here.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at *11.</P>
<P>Note that there was little if any discussion in the <U>Inset</U> case regarding
whether any users within Connecticut actually had accessed the defendant's
domain or called the defendant's 800 number.  There also was little if any
discussion of any allegation or evidence that the defendant in that case was
aware that individuals in Connecticut had accessed the domain or called the
number.  Thus, the exercise of jurisdiction in that case would seem to violate
the principle that one does not &quot;appoint the chattel his agent for service
of process&quot;, <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27444+u!2Es!2E+296!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27444+u!2Es!2E+296!27]/doc/{@298340}/hit_headings?">World-Wide
Volkswagen</a>, 444 U.S. at 296, for the foreseeability
that individuals in Connecticut &quot;could&quot; access the defendant's
Internet domain or call the 800 number forms an insufficient basis for the
assertion of jurisdiction.  &quot;'[F]oreseeability' alone has never been a
sufficient benchmark for personal jurisdiction under the Due Process Clause.&quot;  <U>Id.</U>
at 295.</P>
<P>With at least one exception, this issue is similar to the &quot;stream of
commerce&quot; issue on which the Supreme Court split in <U>Asahi Metal</U>.  The issue
in <U>Asahi Metal</U> was whether the foreign defendant could be subject to
jurisdiction in California because its goods made their way to California and
were used there.  The Supreme Court split in that case on the issue of whether &quot;[t]he
placement of a product into the stream of commerce, without more, is not an act
of the defendant purposefully directed toward the forum State.&quot; <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+112!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+112!27]/doc/{@143536}/hit_headings?">480 U.S.
at 112</a>.  There is at least one way in which a Web site is &quot;in the stream of
commerce&quot; in a different way than a product that enters a state.  When a
product enters a state and a consumer uses it, the product has, in a sense, been
directed to the state, even if only by the stream of commerce.  When a Web site
is available on the Internet, it typically is not directed anywhere in
particular.  An Internet user typically needs to take affirmative steps to get
to the site, and often will understand that the server providing the Web site's
information is located elsewhere.  Finding a Web site with a search engine and
then viewing the site on the World Wide Web is like calling long distance
information to get a business' telephone number and then calling that number for
information about the business.  In both cases, the location of the caller may
not be known to the business providing the information, and the caller reached
out to the business' location more so than did the business reach out to the
caller's location.</P>
<P>One recent decision that recognizes these principles is <a
href="http://www.leepfrog.com/E-Law/Cases/Bensusan_v_King.html">Bensusan Restaurant
Corp. v. Richard B. King</a>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 13035 (S.D.N.Y. September 9,
1996).  In Bensusan, a jazz club named The Blue Note had set up a Web site
located on a computer server in Missouri.  The Web site listed a telephone
number that users could call to order tickets to attend shows at the club.  The
plaintiff owned a jazz club in New York which also was known as The Blue Note,
and the plaintiff had a federally registered trademark for &quot;The Blue Note&quot;.
 In assessing the defendant's motion to dismiss for lack of jurisdiction, the
Court noted that the plaintiff's &quot;primary argument in support of both
statutory bases for personal jurisdiction is that, because defendant's Web site
is accessible in New York, defendant could have foreseen that the site was able
to be viewed in New York and taken steps to restrict access to his site only to
users in a certain geographic region, presumably Missouri.  Regardless of the
technical feasibility of such a procedure [cit. om.], mere foreseeability of an
in-state consequence and a failure to avert that consequence is not sufficient
to establish personal jurisdiction.&quot;  <U>Id.</U> at *14.  The Court carefully
analyzed the facts, and noted that</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>It takes several affirmative steps by the New York resident, however, to
obtain access to the Web site and utilize the information there.  First, the New
York resident has to access the Web site using his or her computer hardware and
software. [cit. om.] Then, if the user wished to attend a show in defendant's
club, he or she would have to telephone the box office in Missouri and reserve
tickets.  Finally, that user would need to pick up the tickets in Missouri
because King does not mail or otherwise transmit tickets to the user.  Even
assuming that the user was confused about the relationship of the Missouri club
to the one in New York, such an act of infringement would have occurred in
Missouri, not New York.  The mere fact that a person can gain information on the
allegedly infringing product is not the equivalent of a person advertising,
promoting, selling or otherwise making an effort to target its product in New
York. [cit. om.] Here, there is simply no allegation or proof that any
infringing goods were shipped into New York or that any other infringing
activity was directed at New York or caused by King to occur here.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><U>Id.</U> at *10-11.  Thus, the Court also concluded that the defendant had</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>done nothing to purposefully avail himself of the benefits of New York. 
King, like numerous others, simply created a Web site and permitted anyone who
could find it to access it.  Creating a site, like placing a product into the
stream of commerce, may be felt nationwide -- or even worldwide -- but, without
more, it is not an act purposefully directed toward the forum state. <U>See</U> <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+112!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27480+u!2Es!2E+112!27]/doc/{@143536}/hit_headings?">Asahi
Metal Indus. Co. v. Superior Court</a>, 480 U.S. 102, 112, 107 S.Ct. 1026, 1032, 94
L.Ed.2d 92 (1991) (plurality opinion).  There are no allegations that King
actively sought to encourage New Yorkers to access his site, or that he
conducted any business -- let alone a continuous and systematic part of its
business -- in New York.  There is in fact no suggestion that King has any
presence of any kind in New York other than the Web site that can be accessed
worldwide.  Bensusan's argument that King should have foreseen that users could
access the site in New York and be confused as to the relationship of the two
Blue Note clubs is insufficient to satisfy due process.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><U>Id.</U> at *16<a name="TEXT3">.</a><a href="#FN3">(3)</a></P>
<P>Note the implications of a contrary ruling such as <U>Inset</U> or those sought by
the Minnesota Attorney General.  If the mere presence of a Web site subjects the
owner of the site to jurisdiction anywhere the site can be accessed, then the
same argument will apply to foreign jurisdiction as well.  Thus, every
individual and company outside the United States suddenly would be subject to
jurisdiction in every state in the United States if the individual or company
has a Web site<a name="TEXT4"),</a><a href="#FN4">(4)</a> and likewise every individual
and company in the United
States would be subject to jurisdiction in numerous foreign countries if the
individual or company has a Web site.  While this hardly makes sense, it follows
closely from holdings, such as that in <U>Inset</U>, that the accessability of a Web
site from within a jurisdiction equates to &quot;purposeful availment&quot; of
the privilege of doing business within the jurisdiction such that Web site owner
should &quot;reasonably anticipate the possibility of being hailed into court&quot;
there.  <U>Inset Systems</U>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 7160, *11. </P>
<P>As a final note, it is important to recognize that the FTC, DOT, and other
federal agencies also exercise jurisdiction over commerce on the Internet.  For
information about the FTC's recent action against a company alleged to be
conducting a pyramid scheme through a World Wide Web site, see <a
href="http://www.ftc.gov/opa/9605/fortuna.htm">http://www.ftc.gov/opa/9605/fortuna.htm</a>. 
For information about a Department of
Transportation fine levied against Virgin Atlantic Airways for failing to update
the airfares on its Web site, see <a
href="http://www.dot.gov/affairs/virad.htm">http://www.dot.gov/affairs/virad.htm</a>.</P>
<H2>V. Conclusion</H2>
<P>As the Sixth Circuit noted in CompuServe, the judicial trend has been to
relax jurisdiction requirements in connection with the globalization of our
economy.  The Internet is, perhaps, the epitome of that globalization.  Yet with
that globalization comes the obliteration of traditional physical jurisdiction
boundaries, and the minimization of the effort, or purposeful availment, that
formerly was necessary to do business in a foreign jurisdiction (and to assert
personal jurisdiction over one doing such business).  On the Internet, &quot;[m]essages
can be transmitted from any physical location to any other location without
degradation, decay, or substantial delay, and without any physical cues or
barriers that might otherwise keep certain geographically remote places and
people separate from one another.&quot; <a href="http://www.cli.org/X0025_LBFIN.html">Rise
of Law In Cyberspace</a>, ___ Stanford
Law Review at ___.  It also frequently is true that, as popularized in a New
Yorker cartoon, &quot;on the Internet, nobody knows you're a dog&quot; (i.e.,
sellers often will not know the identity or location of buyers).</P>
<P>The trend toward relaxing jurisdiction requirements seems to have manifested
itself in many of the recent decisions that have addressed jurisdiction in the
context of electronic transmissions.  While the analogy between electronic mail
sent to a known recipient and regular mail sent to a known recipient is,
perhaps, justifiable, Usenet posts and World Wide Web transactions--entered into
with individuals whose identities and locations are unknown--make for difficult
analogies.  Perhaps the closest analogy is the United States Supreme Court's
plurality decision in <U>Asahi Metal</U> relating to stream of commerce jurisdiction. 
Because that was a plurality decision, however, its lessons are, in the words of
the Sixth Circuit, somewhat &quot;dubious&quot;--particularly given the
differences between a Web site that a user must seek out and &quot;bring&quot;
to their jurisdiction, and a physical product that may come to an individual's
attention after it already is within the individual's jurisdiction</P>
<P>Until the law in this area becomes more clear, there are at least some
lessons we can learn from the cases that have been decided thus far.  For
instance, the Sixth Circuit in CompuServe emphasized the importance of the
contracts into which Patterson had entered and the fact that the contracts
stated they were entered into in Ohio and were governed by Ohio law.  Similarly, the Minnesota
court in <a
href="http://www.ag.state.mn.us/consumer/news/OnlineScams/ggOrder.html">State v. Granite
Gate Resorts</a> emphasized the fact that the defendant's Web site
warned users they could be sued in their home state.  Thus, if
one is concerned about jurisdiction in connection with commercial transactions,
it may be advisable to create on-line agreements that govern those transactions
and to specify the jurisdiction in which any disputes will be litigated and
the law that will be applied.  It probably also is advisable to require users to
manifest their assent to such agreements before they enter into any transactions
(in order to help avoid &quot;shrink wrap&quot;-type arguments that the
agreements are unenforceable).  In addition, if jurisdiction is a concern,
consider what portions of a transaction need to be conducted with knowledge of a
user's address.  Once you have valid credit card information, not only is it
easier and cheaper to send that software to JohnDoe@CompuServe.com (that is, 
easier and cheaper than mailing the software to John Doe's physical address),
but it also is less jurisdictionally risky.  Finally, there may be some
jurisdictions in which you will not want to do business at all.  The Thomases,
for instance, thus far have learned the hard way that their amateur action
graphics files were not welcome by the authorities in Tennessee.  If the nature
of your business requires that users be a certain age or if your business is
banned or regulated in certain areas (for example, gambling), then it may become
necessary to identify all users before they can be permitted to engage in
transactions, and to prohibit transactions with certain users and in certain
jurisdictions.</P>
<HR>
