Georgia
office of King &amp; Spalding.  Mr. Slutsky was elected to the partnership of
King &amp; Spalding in 1996, effective January 1, 1997.  Mr. Slutsky's practice
focuses on computer and copyright litigation.  He may be reached at
<A HREF="mailto:bslutsky@kslaw.com">bslutsky@kslaw.com</A>.<P>
Nothing in this paper constitutes legal advice.  This paper is copyright 1996 by King &amp;
Spalding.<BR>
<UL><LI><a href="#TEXT1">Back</a> to text</UL><BR>
<a name="FN2">(2)</a> Restricting access to users at certain Internet domains is likely to
prove ineffectual in many circumstances because it can be difficult if not
impossible to determine the  location of users at domains such as
compuserve.com, aol.com, netcom.com, etc.  It also is possible for users in
restricted domains to use a web proxy server to bypass domain- related
restrictions.  As noted in <a
href="http://www.eff.org/pub/Censorship/Comm_Decency_Act/HTML/960612_aclu_v_reno_decision.html">ACLU v. Reno</a>, &quot;[o]nce a provider posts its
content on the Internet, it cannot prevent that content from entering any
community.&quot;  929 F. Supp. at 844.<BR>
<UL><LI><a href="#TEXT2">Back</a> to text</UL><BR>
<a name="FN3">(3)</a> For other decisions on this topic, <U>see</U> <U>Edias Software
Int'l, L.L.C. v. Basis Int'l, Ltd.</U>, 1996 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 18279, *19-20 (D. Az. Nov. 19,
1996) (&quot;Basis' e-mail messages to Arizona and Compuserve Web site which reaches
Arizona customers count as an additional 'contacts' under a minimum contacts analysis, but
additionally confer jurisdiction in Arizona under the 'effects test.'&quot;); <a
href="http://www.jmls.edu/cyber/cases/panavis.html">Panavision International, L.P.
v. Toeppen</a>, 938 F. Supp. 616, 1996 WL 534083 (C.D. Cal. Sept. 19, 1996)
(&quot;Toeppen allegedly registered Panavision's trademarks as domain names with the
knowledge that the names belonged to Panavision and with the intent to interfere with
Panavision's business.  Toeppen expressly aimed his conduct at California. 
Finally, Toeppen has harmed Panavision, the brunt of which Panavision has borne
in California, which Toeppen knew would likely happen because Panavision's
principal place of business and the heart of the theatrical motion picture and
television camera and photographic equipment business are in California. 
Toeppen's actions are anything but 'random, fortuitous or attenuated.' <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27471+u!2Es!2E+476!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27471+u!2Es!2E+476!27]/doc/{@177823}/hit_headings?">Burger
King</a>, 471 U.S. at 476.  He has not engaged in 'untargeted negligence' but has
'expressly aimed' his tortious activities at California. <a
href="http://www.nfoweb.com/folio.pgi/ussc-1/query=[field+citation!3A!27465+u!2Es!2E+790!27]+or+[field+pages!3A!27465+u!2Es!2E+790!27]/doc/{@203533}/hit_headings?">Calder</a>,
465 U.S. at 790.  Jurisdiction is proper because Toeppen's out of state conduct was intended
to, and did, result in harmful effects in California.&quot;); <a
href="http://www.jmls.edu/cyber/cases/maritz.html">Maritz, Inc. v. CyberGold, Inc.</a>,1996
U.S. Dist. LEXIS 14978 (E.D. Mo. Aug. 19, 1996) (&quot;[T]he
courts determined that the 'commission of a tortious act' provision of
Missouri's long-arm statute permitted jurisdiction over a defendant corporation
where the sole basis for jurisdiction was an extraterritorial act of tortious
interference with a contract which produced an effect in the State of Missouri. 
Based on these decisions, the Court concludes that Missouri's long-arm statute
reaches the defendants, even assuming CyberGold's allegedly infringing
activities were wholly outside of Missouri, because the allegedly infringing
activities have produced an effect in Missouri as they have allegedly caused
Maritz economic injury. ...  Clearly, CyberGold has obtained the website for the
purpose of, and in anticipation that, internet users, searching the internet for
websites, will access CyberGold's website and eventually sign up on CyberGold's
mailing list.  Although CyberGold characterizes its activity as merely
maintaining a 'passive website,' its intent is to reach all internet users,
regardless of geographic location. ...  Through its website, CyberGold has
consciously decided to transmit advertising information to all internet users,
knowing that such information will be transmitted globally.  Thus, CyberGold's
contacts are of such a quality and nature ... that they favor the exercise of
personal jurisdiction over defendant.&quot;); <U>Beverage Management Solutions,
Inc. v. Yankee Spirits, Inc.</U>, 218 Ga. App. 95, 460 S.E.2d 564 (1995) (no
jurisdiction in Georgia over Massachusetts company based on Massachusetts
company's sending computer data to Georgia); <a
href="http://www.leepfrog.com/E-Law/Cases/Pres-Kap_v_System_One.html">Pres-Kap, Inc. v.
System One,
Direct Access, Inc.</a>, 636 So.2d 1351 (Fla. Ct. App. 1994) (no jurisdiction in
Florida over a New York travel agent who contracted to use an airline
reservation system that maintained its primary database in Florida); <U>Plus
System, Inc. v. New England Network, Inc.</U>, 804 F. Supp. 11 (D. Colo. 1992)
(finding jurisdiction in Colorado over a New England company that regularly used
the plaintiff's ATM computer system); <U>California Software, Inc. v. Reliability
Research, Inc.</U>, 631 F. Supp. 1356, 1358, 1361-62 (C.D. Cal. 1986) (&quot;White
placed a message on a nationally disseminated computer based information service
known as the Computer Reliability Forum ... .  Defendants made tortious
statements which, though directed at third persons outside California, were
expressly calculated to cause injury in California. ...  Because defendants
intentionally influenced third parties to injure the California plaintiffs,
defendants should have foreseen answering for the veracity of their statements
and the propriety of their conduct in California.&quot;).<BR>
<UL><LI><a href="#TEXT3">Back</a> to text</UL><BR>
<a name="FN4">(4)</a> In many if not most instances this would be a question of specific
jurisdiction, so it also would be necessary for the Web site itself to be
harmful in some way such as by giving rise to trademark infringement.<BR>
<UL><LI><a href="#TEXT4">Back</a> to text</UL><BR>
