<TITLE>Technology Stock Values</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>Technology Stock Values</H1>
<H2>Kenneth R. Hannahs, Jr.</H2><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
As the values of some technology stocks fell sharply in January 1996, the long awaited technology correction appeared to have arrived.  Notwithstanding the recent stabilization of technology stock values, many once solid companies such as Apple Computer now seem close to becoming insignificant, at best, and extinct, at worst.  Increasingly, these companies as well as thriving companies such as Microsoft have focused on Internet related products to ensure financial success in the future.  This trend is founded on the dramatic growth of the World Wide Web and the increasingly wide acceptance of the Web's point and click graphical user interface.
<P>
In Georgia, the announcements of the sales of hi-tech companies and proposed ventures between these companies were common.
<P>
Two Atlanta based companies, American Software Inc. and Intellimedia Sports, Inc. formed a venture to provide Internet services.  The company will be known as Intellimedia Commerce and will be headed up by President and CEO Ben Dyer, who is currently chairman and CEO of Intellimedia Sports.  Cox Enterprises will also own an interest in the new venture.
<P>
Hayes Microcomputer Products Inc., one of the largest producers of modems, is seeking approval in its Chapter 11 Bankruptcy proceeding for the sale of 49% of the company to Northern Telecom and ACMA of Singapore.  Other prospective purchasers of Hayes are US Robotics, Inc. and Diamond Multimedia Systems, Inc.
<P>
Servantis Systems, Inc. was sold for approximately $170 million in cash and stock to Checkfree Corp. of Columbus, Ohio.  Both companies have either developed of are developing products for use on the Internet.  Checkfree's expertise is the electronic processing of transactions over the Internet, while Servantis produces banking software and is reported to be developingInternet related products.  The fate of Servantis' management and five hundred employees is not currently known.  
<P>
Dun & Bradstreet Software, Inc. was put up for sale by its parent Dun & Bradstreet Corp. on January 10, 1996.  Dun & Bradstreet Corp. purchased DBS in 1990 for $330 million.
<P>
Atlanta based Five Paces Software, Inc. and SecureWare, Inc. supplied an authentication and encryption security platform package used by Security First Network Bank.  SFNB is the world's first "Virtual Bank" in which all services are provided on line.  Information concerning the services of SFNB may be found on SFNB's home page at <A HREF="http://www.sfnb.com">http://www.sfnb.com</A>.

<P>Several initial public offerings of Atlanta based hi-tech companies occurred in the second half of 1995.  For example, A.D.A.M. Software, Inc. a developer of educational multimedia software products that provide anatomical, medical, scientific and health-related information for academic, professional and consumer markets went public in November, 1995;  Harbinger Corp., a developer of electronic commerce software went public in August, 1995; and IMNET Systems, Inc., a developer of information and document management systems went public in July, 1995.  
<P>
Illustrative of the changes taking place among some of the world's largest hi-tech companies, recent editions of the Wall Street Journal and other national publications disclosed the following:
<P>
<OL>
<LI><STRONG>Potential Sale of Apple Computer Company</STRONG>.  Stung by weak fourth quarter performance, Apple's board of directors is negotiating with Sun Microsystems, Inc. Sun made an initial offer to purchase Apple's stock at a price equal to $23.00 per share.  Apple's financial troubles are generally blamed on Apple's failure to license the right to build Mac clones in the 1980's.  During this time, large numbers of IBM PC clones were being manufactured.  As a result, Apple's market share deteriorated despite the fact that the sales of its Mac personal computers have actually increased. Some analysts believe that Sun's expertise in the advanced business and academic settings and Apple's expertise in the personal computing market would make a good fit.  Earlier in 1995, Apple rejected overtures made by IBM for close to $40.00 per share.  However, reports indicate that Apple may again be seeking out IBM as a possible purchaser.  Apple's shares were trading for $30.625 on Friday, January 26, 1996.
<P>
Another area of synergy between Apple and Sun noted by analysts is the development of products for the Internet by both companies.  For example, Sun unveiled a prototype of a cheap desk top computer that uses Sun's Java networking language to browse the Internet(See PC junior, below).  The Java computer language, once fully developed, will permit any program written in Java to run on any operating system.  As a result, the "stranglehold" currently held by PCs running Windows software may be loosened.
<P>
<LI><STRONG>PC Juniors</STRONG>.  The $500 Internet browser is an active subject of discussion in financial and trade periodicals.  These "pc juniors" would contain minimal or no hard disk memory and may be hooked directly to a consumer's television sets. Oracle Corp. has indicated that its machine will cost approximately $500.  Sun's proposed system would be a streamlined version of today's PCs and would include a 110 megahertz chip and other circuitry in a 5x9x2 inch box, with minimal memory.  Sun has not committed to introducing this package.  The slower thanexpected sales growth of  personal computers in the fourth quarter 1995 (25% v. 20%) indicates that the population at large is either unwilling or unable to buy a $2,500 system.  The newer systems, which may operate without keyboards, would perform basic functions using a point and click interface directly on an individual's television set. Some analysts believe that once the $500 threshold is passed, wide scale public acceptance will occur thereby further fueling the use of the World Wide Web.
<P>
<LI><STRONG>Miscellaneous</STRONG>.  MCI and Microsoft have agreed to form a partnership to sell each other's products worldwide.  The agreement will be non-exclusive and took place after talks between Microsoft and AT&T stalled.  The Wall Street Journal reported the imminent sale of the WordPerfect Corp. subsidiary of Novell Inc. to Corel Corp. for $50,000,000.  WordPerfect's sharp declines in sales can be attributed in part to the increase in sales of Microsoft Word.  Microsoft and NBC announced the formation of MSNBC, which will combine the expertise of the two companies in the area of the internet (Microsoft Network) and in television broadcasting (NBC Network).  The proposed transaction between Microsoft and Intuit (the maker of the popular Quicken personal finance personal software) failed as the result of anti-trust concerns.  
</OL>
<P>
<center><HR><p>
