<HEAD>
<TITLE>Compliance with the Revisions to U.S. Export Control Regulations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">Compliance with the Revisions to U.S. Export Control
Regulations</H1>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the November 1996 issue
of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by
permission.</H6>
<HR>
<P>The agreements negotiated in the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade (&quot;GATT&quot;) and the North American Free Trade Agreement
(&quot;NAFTA&quot;) have raised expectations for the expansion of export
opportunities for U.S. industries. Companies that are currently exporting or are
planning to take advantage of new export opportunities, however, should ensure
that they comply with U.S. export control laws and regulations, including the
revised Export Administration Regulations (&quot;EAR&quot;) recently promulgated
by the U.S. Department of Commerce. The EAR applies to virtually all exports,
reexports (i.e., shipments between foreign countries of U.S.-origin goods or
technology), and other transactions involving U.S. goods, software, technology,
and certain services. Violations of the EAR can result in substantial civil and
criminal penalties.</P>
<P>On March 25, 1996, the Bureau of Export Administration (&quot;BXA&quot;) of
the U.S. Department of Commerce issued an interim rule simplifying the EAR. 61
Fed. Reg. 12,714 (Mar. 25, 1996). The new interim rule is intended to clarify
the language of the EAR, simplify its application, and generally make the export
control regulatory regime more user-friendly. Final regulations will be issued
after consideration of public comments on the interim rule, although the interim
rule will be effective while BXA considers any appropriate amendments.</P>
<P>The new rule simplifies BXA's export control regime by establishing a
presumption that exports or reexports are authorized unless the EAR expressly
prohibits such transactions without a license. Under the EAR, exporters and
reexporters are only required to obtain a license if one of the ten General
Prohibitions applies and no License Exception is available.</P>
<P>Companies that are exporting or reexporting any goods, software, technology,
or services should carefully evaluate whether any obligations under the EAR
apply to their transactions. The EAR, however, is generally intended to control
exports and reexports to certain countries that pose national security or
foreign policy concerns. The items controlled under the EAR generally include
advanced goods, software, and technology that could be used for military or
intelligence-gathering uses (especially relating to nuclear, chemical, and
biological weapons and missile technology). Only a relatively small number of
exports and reexports subject to the EAR require an application to BXA for a
license. Items that are not listed in the EAR's Commodity Control List (&quot;CCL&quot;)
do not require a license, and some items on the CCL require a license only to a
limited number of destinations. License Exceptions may apply to other
transactions.</P>
<P>Notwithstanding the limited scope of export or reexport transactions that
may require a license, virtually all exports or reexports involving U.S. goods,
software, or technology are covered by the EAR. Accordingly, companies should
develop an internal checklist or export compliance program (discussed below) to
enable company personnel to identify efficiently whether a more comprehensive
analysis of the EAR's application to a particular transaction may be needed. For
example, if an exporter or reexporter answers &quot;no&quot; to the following
questions, it likely does not need a license for the transaction and is only
obligated to comply with certain documentation requirements under the EAR.</P>
<P>(1) Could the item be used for military or intelligence-gathering purposes,
including goods, software, or technology in the electronic, computer,
telecommunications, or other high-tech industries?</P>
<P>(2) Is the country of ultimate destination in the Middle East, Far East, or
former Soviet Union?</P>
<P>(3) Is the ultimate end-user using the item for military,
intelligence-gathering, or other uses that may be adverse to the national
security or foreign policy interests of the United States?</P>
<P>If the &quot;no&quot; answers to the above questions are not absolutely
certain, the exporter or reexporter should analyze its transaction under the EAR
in more detail.</P>
<P>The EAR describes four questions that exporters and reexporters should
address in determining their obligations under the EAR: (1) whether an item or
transaction is subject to the EAR, (2) whether a General Prohibition applies,
(3) whether a License Exception applies, and (4) whether other documentation and
reporting requirements are applicable. </P>
<H3>ITEMS AND TRANSACTIONS SUBJECT TO THE EAR</H3>
<P>The EAR covers the following items:</P>
<UL>
<LI> All items in the United States, including items in a U.S. foreign trade
zone or moving in-transit through the United States from one foreign country to
another;
</LI>
<LI> All U.S. origin items wherever located;
</LI>
<LI> U.S. origin parts, components, materials, or other goods incorporated
abroad into foreign-made products; U.S. origin software commingled with foreign
software; and U.S. origin technology commingled with foreign technology in
quantities above de minimis levels;
</LI>
<LI> Certain foreign-made products of U.S. origin technology or software; and
</LI>
<LI> Certain goods produced by any plant or major component of a plant located
outside the United States that is directly produced using U.S.-origin technology
or software.
</LI></UL>
<P>The EAR covers the following types of transactions:</P>
<UL>
<LI> Traditional exports;
</LI>
<LI> Reexports;
</LI>
<LI> Foreign products -- exports of technology from the United States that may
be subject to assurances that the direct product of the technology will not be
exported to certain destinations;
</LI>
<LI> Non-traditional exports -- examples include release of technology to a
foreign national in the United States through demonstration or oral briefing;
return of foreign equipment to its country of origin after repair; shipments
from a U.S. foreign trade zone; and electronic transmission of non-public data
received abroad; and
</LI>
<LI> U.S. persons' activities -- the provision of services or support by U.S.
persons anywhere in the world for transactions relating to nuclear, chemical, or
biological weapons technology.
</LI></UL>
<P>The EAR also enumerates items and transactions that are not subject to the
EAR. If an item is not subject to the EAR, the exporter or reexporter is not
subject to any obligations under the EAR.</P>
<P>Transactions not subject to the EAR include (1) exports under the exclusive
jurisdiction of another federal agency, (2) exports of &quot;publicly available&quot;
software and technology (as defined under the EAR), and (3) certain reexports of
items shipped from one foreign country to another.</P>
<H3>GENERAL PROHIBITIONS AND LICENSE EXCEPTIONS</H3>
<P>If an export or reexport is subject to the EAR, the exporter or reexporter
must determine whether one of the ten enumerated General Prohibitions applies.
The General Prohibitions include, inter alia, prohibitions on (1) exports and
reexports based on CCL classification and designated end-use, end-user, or
country of destination; (2) transactions involving parties that have been denied
export privileges by BXA; (3) exports, reexports, and other transactions
involving embargoed countries (Boznia-Herzegovina, Croatia, Cuba, Iran, Iraq,
Libya, North Korea, Rwanda, and Serbia and Montenegro); and (4) unloading and
shipping certain items in-transit to specified countries.</P>
<P>If a General Prohibition applies, the EAR provides a number of License
Exceptions that exempt exporters and reexporters from licensing requirements,
although certain conditions and documentation requirements may still apply. If a
License Exception does not apply, an exporter or reexporter is obligated to
obtain an export license from BXA or to refrain from making the export,
reexport, or other transaction. If a General Prohibition does not apply, an
exporter or reexporter is only obligated to comply with certain documentation
requirements. </P>
<H3>PENALTIES</H3>
<P>Violations of the EAR include engaging in prohibited conduct under the EAR
or otherwise aiding, attempting, conspiring, or acting with knowledge of a
violation. BXA may impose a civil penalty not to exceed $10,000 for each
violation (not to exceed $100,000 for each violation involving national security
controls) and restrict the ability of named persons to engage in designated
export or reexport transactions.  With respect to criminal penalties, anyone
knowingly violating or conspiring to or attempting to violate the EAR or any
order or license issued thereunder may be fined not more than five times the
value of the exports involved or $50,000, whichever is greater, or imprisoned
not more than five years, or both. For exports controlled for foreign policy
purposes or knowingly used for military or intelligence gathering purposes,
firms may be fined not more than five times the value of the export involved or
$1,000,000, whichever is greater. An individual may be fined not more than
$250,000 or imprisoned not more than 10 years, or both.</P>
<H3>EXPORT COMPLIANCE PROGRAM</H3>
<P>The most effective method for companies to mitigate potential civil or
criminal penalties under the EAR for inadvertent violations is to establish an
internal export compliance program (&quot;ECP&quot;). ECPs are intended to
monitor and maintain compliance with laws and regulations governing the export,
reexport, and transfer of goods, software, technology, and services originating
in the United States or involving U.S. entities. ECPs generally consist of
written internal procedures administered by a company to provide checks and
safeguards at key steps in the order processing system to ensure compliance with
the U.S. export control laws and regulations. The EAR specifies that voluntary
disclosure of potential violations is a mitigating factor in determining what
administrative sanctions, if any, will be sought, and the establishment of an
ECP is recognized as a mitigating factor under the Federal Corporate Sentencing
Guidelines of 1991.</P>
<P>Whatever the level of a company's international trading activity, the
implementation of an ECP is highly recommended. An effective ECP benefits a
company by (1) providing for the early identification and prevention of
potential export control violations; (2) acting as a mitigating factor in civil
and criminal cases for inadvertent violations of the EAR; (3) facilitating
adherence to new Customs Service standards of &quot;informed compliance&quot;
and &quot;reasonable care&quot;; and (4) restricting the potential subjects of
administrative proceedings to isolated individuals, departments, or
subsidiaries, rather than the entire company. </P>
<HR>
