<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>COUNTRY-OF-ORIGIN DETERMINATIONS UNDER NAFTA </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">Country-Of-Origin Determinations Under NAFTA </H1>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the November 1996 issue
of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by
permission.</H6>
<HR>
<P>Imagine that you are a manufacturer with facilities in the United States,
Mexico, and France.  Some of the products you sell in the United States are
processed in Mexico using ingredients or components produced in France.  Other
products you sell in the United States are processed in both Mexico and the
United States prior to sale.  What rate of duty applies to the merchandise
imported into the United States?  Do the products need to be labeled to indicate
their country of origin?  If so, what is the country of origin?  The answers to
these questions depend on an analysis of how the imported  merchandise is
produced and the location of the manufacturing operations, based on rules
promulgated by the U.S. Customs Service.</P>
<P>Under the North American Free Trade Agreement (&quot;NAFTA&quot;), tariff
duties have been eliminated (or are being phased out) on products imported from
Canada and Mexico.  Imported merchandise originating in a NAFTA country is
either duty-free or subject to lower duties than products imported from
non-NAFTA countries.  Therefore, if the country of origin of merchandise
imported into the United States from a NAFTA country is determined to be a NAFTA
country, a preferential duty rate can result in substantial savings to the
importer.  Moreover, because U.S. customs law requires articles of foreign
origin to be labeled to indicate their country of origin, the origin of all
merchandise imported into the United States must be ascertained to enable
importers to comply with country-of-origin marking requirements.</P>
<P>On September 5, 1995, Customs published its final rules for determining
whether an imported product is subject to preferential duty treatment under
NAFTA.   These rules, called the Origin Rules, became effective October 1, 1995.
 On June 6, 1996, Customs published its final rules for determining the
country-of-origin marking requirements for imports into the United States (other
than textile and apparel products) from Canada or Mexico.  These rules, called
the Marking Rules, became effective August 5, 1996.  Both the NAFTA Origin Rules
and the NAFTA Marking Rules fundamentally alter the analysis used to determine
the country of origin, and, consequently, the tariff rates and marking
requirements for imports into the United States from Canada and Mexico.</P>
<P>For non-NAFTA trade, Customs generally determines a product's country of
origin based on the location where the product was wholly obtained or produced
or the country of the last &quot;substantial transformation&quot; of the
product.  The country in which the last substantial transformation occurred is
usually the country in which the product assumed its final and distinctive
identity prior to importation.  A substantial transformation generally occurs
when processing results in a &quot;new and different article&quot; having a &quot;new
name, character, and use.&quot;  For example, Customs has ruled that the
assembly of semiconductors into integrated circuits constitutes a substantial
transformation.</P>
<P>To determine origin for purposes of NAFTA, however, the United States,
Canada, and Mexico rejected the substantial transformation standard and adopted
a tariff-shift approach.  For NAFTA origin determinations, therefore, Customs
generally determines that a product originated in a NAFTA country if the product
was wholly grown or manufactured in that country using domestic materials, or if
processing in that country resulted in a change in the product's Harmonized
Tariff System classification at the six-digit level.  For some products, the
value of the NAFTA-origin ingredients or components must reach a certain
percentage of the product's total value for the product to be considered a
product of a NAFTA country.  For example, passenger cars must have a &quot;regional
value content&quot; of at least 50 percent to be considered NAFTA-origin
merchandise.  For products subject to the tariff-shift analysis, Customs no
longer attempts to determine whether a &quot;substantial transformation&quot;
has occurred, but instead bases its origin determination for NAFTA solely on
whether processing in a NAFTA country has resulted in a change in tariff
classification.  Nevertheless, in most cases, a substantial transformation is
sufficient to change the tariff classification of a product.  </P>
<P>Some of the NAFTA tariff-shift provisions in the Marking Rules also have
local content requirements.  For example, a change of origin can occur as a
result of blending certain imported bulk pharmaceuticals with NAFTA-origin
pharmaceuticals if at least 40 percent, by weight, of the total active
ingredients in the finished product are NAFTA-origin.  The importer must make
this determination on a product-by-product basis, applying the applicable
tariff-shift provisions.</P>
<P>To answer the questions posed at the beginning of this article, an importer
would ordinarily need to determine the tariff classification of (1) the
merchandise imported into Mexico from France and (2) the merchandise imported
into the United States from Mexico.  Using this information, the importer would
then review Customs' tariff-shift tables to determine whether the necessary
tariff shift occurred to change the country of origin of the merchandise.  As
noted above, different tariff-shift rules apply to determine origin for
preferential duty and marking purposes.</P>
<P>In general, if processing in Mexico resulted in a change in tariff
classification under the NAFTA Origin Rules, the product would become Mexican
origin.  The product would then be subject to the preferential NAFTA duty rate
upon importation into the United States.  If processing in Mexico also resulted
in a change in tariff classification under the NAFTA Marking Rules, the product
would need to be marked &quot;Made in Mexico&quot; in a manner conspicuous to
the ultimate U.S. purchaser of the product.  If no tariff shift occurred in
Mexico under either the Origin Rules or the Marking Rules, the product would be
considered French origin and therefore not subject to the preferential NAFTA
duty rate.  It would also need to be marked &quot;Made in France.&quot;  In
either case, if a tariff shift based on the Marking Rules occurred in the United
States prior to sale to the ultimate purchaser, the product would be considered
U.S. origin and no country-of-origin marking would be required.</P>
<P>On July 8, 1996, in <I>CPC International, Inc. v. United States</I>, the
U.S. Court of International Trade (CIT) ruled that the NAFTA Marking Rules were
contrary to law.  The CIT held that Customs must continue to apply the
substantial transformation standard in determining origin for marking purposes. 
Customs has appealed the ruling to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal
Circuit and intends to continue applying the Marking Rules pending a decision by
the Court of Appeals.  Pending this appeal, importers who object to the NAFTA
Marking Rules and would prefer application of the substantial transformation
standard for determining marking requirements should seek a ruling from Customs,
and, if the ruling is adverse, file suit in the CIT seeking to have the holding
of <I>CPC International </I>applied in their case.</P>
<P></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG
SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="Home Page"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG
SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="Practice Groups"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG
SRC="/gif/atty.gif" ALT="Attorneys"><BR></A>
<A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" ALT="Articles"></A>
<A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" ALT="Legal Resources"></A>
<A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></P></BODY></HTML>
