<html>
<head>
<title>Executive Guide to Antidumping Law</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<h1>Executive Guide to the Antidumping Law Under the Uruguay Round Agreements
Act</h1>
<p>
<h2><a href="/htm/mabile.htm">Michael P. Mabile</a></h2>
<H6>This article originally appeared in the November 1995 issue of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by permission.</H6>
<HR><p>
</CENTER>
<p>
The U.S. antidumping statute provides U.S. producers of manufactured goods and agricultural
products a tariff remedy against economically injurious imports that are sold at "less than fair
value" (dumped).  The Uruguay Round Agreements Act, effective January 1, 1995, significantly
changed the statute to implement the requirements of the international Antidumping Agreement
that was negotiated during the Uruguay Round.  These GATT negotiations sparked considerable
controversy between countries, like the United States, that wanted to retain effective remedies
against unfairly traded imports and other countries whose economies are highly dependent upon
exports and wanted to weaken these remedies.  The Uruguay Round did result in a number of
changes to the GATT Antidumping Agreement and to the U.S. laws implementing the
Agreement.  Perhaps the most significant change is the incorporation of a five-year "sunset"
requirement for antidumping orders.  Even with these changes, the antidumping law remains an
effective measure to counter unfairly priced imports.<p>

The antidumping law can provide a U.S. industry significant relief against unfairly priced
imports, as demonstrated by the successful experience of the cement industry (described below). 
Successful cases have been brought on behalf of a wide variety of industries, including those
engaged in producing basic industrial goods, agricultural products, chemicals and
pharmaceuticals, advanced technology products, and consumer goods.  <p>

If import prices and volume are adversely affecting a domestic producer's profitability, it may be
time for that company to consider whether to seek a trade remedy from the U.S. Government. 
The antidumping duty law usually provides more effective relief than other available remedies
against imports.  Unlike other forms of trade relief, such as an "escape clause" action under
section 201 of the Trade Act of 1974, the decision whether to grant a tariff remedy under these
laws is not subject to White House discretion, but is based on the application of legal standards
by administrative agencies that are subject to review by the courts.  In addition, the standards for
obtaining relief are less rigorous than under section 201 and other forms of trade relief.  Finally,
the antidumping law responds directly to the situation most commonly faced by companies
concerned about import competition--sales of imports at unfair prices in the United States.  <p>

For an importer or foreign producer, imposition of antidumping duties can greatly increase the
cost of doing business in the United States or make it uneconomical to continue importing into
this country.  Any company importing significant quantities of a product that competes with
U.S.-produced goods should be aware of the risk that it may have to defend against an
antidumping action and should consider reviewing its business practices either to make such an
action less likely or to prepare possible defenses.<p>

Dumping is essentially price discrimination between purchasers in different national markets. 
Under U.S. law, dumping is defined as selling a product in the United States at less than its
"normal value," which is usually the price at which the foreign exporter sells the product in its
home market.  Additional duties are assessed to offset the amount by which the normal value
exceeds the price in the United States.<p>

These laws are administered by the International Trade Administration of the U.S. Department of
Commerce and the U.S. International Trade Commission ("ITC"), an independent federal
agency.  Commerce is charged with determining whether imports of a product are dumped.  The
ITC determines whether the imports are materially injuring or threatening to materially injure a
domestic industry.  Congress and the White House have no role in the determinations.<p>

Antidumping investigations seek to remedy, not punish, foreign unfair trading practices.  If an
action is successful, it does not lead to an award of damages to the domestic producer.  Rather,
the U.S. Government will collect additional duties to remedy the unfair practice.  The additional
tariffs will only be imposed prospectively, and thus will not affect imports on which the Customs
Service has finally assessed the duties owed by the importer.<p>

<h4>Antidumping Investigations</h4>
Antidumping investigations are initiated by a petition filed by a U.S. producer, a trade
association, or an ad hoc coalition of producers representative of the industry producing the
product that is the subject of the petition.  Commerce decides whether to initiate an investigation
based on the sufficiency of the information in the petition.  Before initiating an investigation,
Commerce must determine that  the domestic producers supporting the petition account for at
least 25 percent of total U.S. production of the affected product and more than 50 percent of
production by those companies expressing a position on the petition.  <p>

In the course of the investigation at both Commerce and the ITC, the parties are given the
opportunity to present evidence, file briefs, and appear at hearings.  The ITC first makes a
preliminary determination whether there is a "reasonable indication" that the domestic industry is
materially injured or threatened with material injury by the allegedly dumped or subsidized
imports.  Because the "reasonable indication" standard is relatively easy to satisfy, few
investigations are terminated at this preliminary stage.<p>

If the ITC finds a reasonable indication of injury, Commerce then makes a preliminary
determination whether there is a "reasonable basis to believe" that imports are sold at less than
fair value.  If the determination is affirmative, Commerce will require importers of the affected
goods to post bonds or make cash deposits with the U.S. Customs Service in the amount of the
estimated dumping margin.  Commerce then "verifies" the data provided by the foreign exporter
by reviewing its books and records and issues a final determination of the margin.  A negative
final determination by Commerce terminates the investigation, at which time all bonds or cash
deposits posted by importers are released or refunded..  <p>

If Commerce's final determination is affirmative, the ITC will make a final injury determination. 
If the ITC determines that the imports are causing or threatening material injury to the domestic
industry, Commerce will issue an antidumping order directing the Customs Service to collect
cash deposits from importers on future customs entries of the product under investigation in the
amount of the final margins.  A negative ITC determination terminates the investigation,
resulting in the release or refund of all bonds and cash deposits.<p>

Cash deposits are payable upon the entry into the United States of merchandise covered by an
antidumping order.  All duties and cash deposits are the responsibility of the importer, and the
law forbids the foreign producer or exporter to reimburse the importer.<p>

The agencies' determinations must be made within strict statutory deadlines.  The schedule of a
typical antidumping case is as follows: <p>
<p>
<dl>
<dt>Day 20</dt>
<dd><i>Commerce initiates investigation</i></dd>
<dt>Day 45</dt>
<dd><i>ITC issues preliminary injury determination</i></dd>
<dt>Day 160</dt>
<dd><i>Commerce issues preliminary dumping determination</i></dd>
<dt>Day 235</dt>
<dd><i>Commerce issues final dumping determination</i></dd>
<dt>Day 280</dt>
<dd><i>ITC issues final injury determination</i></dd>
<dt>Day 287</dt>
<dd><i>Commerce publishes antidumping order</dd>
</i></dl>
<p>
Commerce bases its determination of whether imports are dumped primarily on price and cost
information submitted by the foreign exporters in response to questionnaires from Commerce. 
This information usually covers sales in the six-month period ending with the last day of the
month in which the petition is filed.  Commerce compares the U.S. price of the imports to their
"normal value," which is usually the price of the same or most similar product in the home
market.  Commerce will disregard home market sales that are at prices below the cost of
production or that are outside the ordinary course of trade.  Because goods sold in the foreign
market and in the United States may differ in physical characteristics, quantities, the level of
trade at which they are sold, selling costs, transportation costs, and other circumstances of sale,
Commerce makes adjustments to the gross price in each market to arrive at "ex-factory" prices. 
The difference between the ex-factory price for sales in the home market and the ex-factory price
for U.S. sales determines the dumping margin.  Thus, if the ex-factory price of a product sold in
the home market is $1.00 and the ex-factory price of the identical product sold in the United
States is $.80, the dumping margin calculation is as follows:<p>

<p>

1.00-.80/.80 =  .20/.80  =  25%<p>

<p>

If there is an insufficient quantity of home market sales to allow a comparison with the U.S.
price, Commerce will compare U.S. price either to the ex-factory price for sales to a third
country or to the "constructed value" of the merchandise, which is calculated as the sum of the
cost of production (including the cost of materials, direct labor, and general, selling, and
administrative expenses), profit, and packing cost.  <p>

Dumping margins are normally based on a comparison of the foreign producer's weighted
average price for sales in the United States to the weighted average price of its sales in the home
market (or third country market) or the constructed value.  The margins may also be based on a
comparison of prices of individual transactions in the two markets.  Margins are calculated on a
company-by-company basis for foreign exporters that participated in the investigation.  Other
exporters from the same country are subject to an "all others" margin that is based on the
weighted average of the margins for all companies that participated in the investigation.    <p>

The ITC gathers information for its injury determination from questionnaire responses by
domestic producers, purchasers, and importers and from other information obtained from the
parties to the investigation or from public sources.  In determining whether imports are injuring
the domestic industry, the ITC examines the volume of imports, the imports' market share, and
the effect of imports on the domestic industry's pricing, production, capacity utilization, sales,
market share, profit, and employment.  The ITC may consider the combined or "cumulated"
effects of imports from more than one country.  <p>

To determine that dumped or subsidized imports threaten material injury to the industry, the ITC
must find that the threatened injury is "real and imminent."  In assessing threat of injury, the ITC
considers whether the volume of imports and their share of the U.S. market are rapidly
increasing, the likelihood that increasing imports will depress U.S. prices, and the existence of
unused foreign production capacity that could lead to increased exports to the United States.<p>

Agency determinations in antidumping cases involving imports from countries other than
Canada and Mexico are reviewable by the U.S. Court of International Trade, a federal court. 
The court may not second-guess the issues determined by an agency, but may only review
whether the agency has complied with legal standards and has based its decision on the evidence
in the agency's record.  Cases involving imports from Canada and Mexico may be appealed to
binational review panels established under dispute resolution provisions of the North American
Free Trade Agreement ("NAFTA").  NAFTA panels have five members, selected from the
importing country and the exporting country.  NAFTA panels are required to apply the same
laws and the same standards for judicial review that would apply if the appeal were taken to a
court in the importing country.  Thus, U.S. law governs appeals in cases arising from U.S.
antidumping cases. <p>

An antidumping order establishes the rate at which importers must pay cash deposits of
estimated duties.  Actual duties on customs entries of goods covered by an order are not finally
assessed until Commerce conducts an administrative review to determine the precise duty rate
that must be paid.  Commerce conducts reviews annually, if requested by a party.  If no party
requests a review, imports into the United States for the affected period are finally assessed
antidumping duties at the cash deposit rate (the dumping margin) established in the investigation
or the last administrative review.  If a review is conducted, Commerce's determination
establishes the duties to be paid on prior entries during the period covered by the review and the
cash deposit rate on future entries pending the next review.<p>

As a result of the changes brought about by the Uruguay Round, an antidumping order is
required to terminate five years after its imposition, unless it is determined that expiration of the
order "would be likely to lead to continuation or recurrence" of the dumping and injury.  If
requested by the domestic industry, Commerce and the ITC are required to conduct a "sunset"
review of an order every five years to determine whether it should continue in effect.   <p>

<h4>The Cement Industry's Experience</h4>
The experience of the U.S. cement industry indicates that the antidumping law can be an
effective remedy for unfairly priced imports.  U.S. consumption of cement increased
substantially during the 1983-1989 economic expansion as construction boomed.  U.S. cement
producers, however, were prevented from benefitting from this growing demand by a surge in
low-priced cement imports during the same period.  The volume of imports grew 500 percent
from 1982 to 1987, as the imports' share of the U.S. market increased from less than 5 percent to
nearly 20 percent.  Delivered import prices declined by 24 percent between 1981 and 1988, from
$45 to $34 per ton.  Import prices were at their lowest in 1987-1988, when import penetration of
the U.S. market was at its highest.  <p>

Rapidly increasing imports depressed domestic prices, took market share from domestic
producers, forced plants to close, and prevented the domestic industry from modernizing or from
capitalizing on expansion opportunities in growing regional markets.  Even though U.S. cement
demand increased 40 percent from 1980 to 1990, U.S. production capacity declined 10 percent,
and the number of U.S. plants decreased from 142 to 109.  The industry's problems with
low-priced imports were especially acute in the southern tier of U.S. states, where the market
was heavily affected by imports from Mexico, Japan, and Venezuela.  <p>

Beginning in 1989, southern tier cement producers successfully prosecuted antidumping
petitions against imports from Mexico and Japan.  Commerce found dumping margins of 58
percent for imports from Mexico and 64 percent for imports from Japan.  A third case against
imports from Venezuela was suspended--after Commerce's preliminary determination of a 49
percent margin on Venezuelan imports--on the basis of an agreement by Venezuelan exporters to
price their exports to the United States above quarterly benchmarks established by Commerce. 
As a result, imports from Mexico, Japan, and Venezuela declined 85 percent from 1989 to 1994,
allowing cement prices and domestic producers' returns on investment to increase substantially. 
The industry's recovery was tied directly to its successful antidumping petitions.<p>

<h4>Evaluation Of A Potential Case</h4>
As the cement industry's experience demonstrates, the antidumping law can be an effective
countermeasure to injurious and unfairly priced imports.  Because of this potential, domestic
producers competing with low priced imports should consider whether it would be advantageous
to file a petition.  The likelihood of success differs from case to case, and the decision to proceed
should be based on a careful analysis of the potential benefits and costs.  Generally speaking,
petitions are more likely to succeed where imports from certain countries are gaining U.S.
market share due to their lower pricing.  Factors to be considered include (1) the volume of
imports and whether imports are increasing; (2) the imports' market share and whether the
imports' market share is increasing; (3) the scope of the industry and the products on which a
case would be based; (4) industry trends during the last three calendar years in consumption,
production, capacity utilization, employment, market share, pricing, sales, and profitability; and
(5) evidence that prices are higher in the foreign country than in the United States.  The outcome
of a petition is often dependent on the most advantageous definition of the product and the U.S.
industry and the most advantageous timing for filing the petition.  <p>

U.S. importers and foreign producers should also undertake a careful analysis of their potential
liability for dumping duties.  A review similar to that undertaken by a petitioner prior to filing a
petition would be particularly well advised if imports are increasing or if domestic producers
have complained about import competition.  This review would enable a company either to
revise its pricing or importing practices or to develop useful information and arguments for
defending against a potential petition.<p>
<p>
<p>
