<head>
<title>Country of Origin Marking</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<p>
<h1>Country of Origin Marking: When is a Product "Made in the USA?"</h1>
<h2>Stephen A. Jones</a></h2>
<H6>This article originally appeared in the November 1995 issue of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by permission.</H6>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
Imagine you are a manufacturer or seller of athletic footwear assembled in the United States
from imported components.  Do you need to disclose the foreign origin of the shoes' components
to the consumer?  Because the shoes are assembled in the United States, can you label and
advertise the shoes as "Made in the U.S.A.?"<p>

Competitiveness in the international marketplace often demands that manufacturers source
components from one or more different countries in order to achieve the lowest possible cost. 
Given the prevalence of multiple-country sourcing and processing, determining the country of
origin of a product, and the corresponding marking and labeling requirements, is increasingly
difficult.  The U.S. Customs Service requires all products of foreign origin to be marked with the
country of origin.  The Federal Trade Commission specifies when a seller may identify its
products as "Made in the U.S.A."  Due to the increasing complexity of international commerce,
both Customs and the FTC are currently modifying their rules in this area.  The new rules that
emerge from these review proceedings will affect the marking and labeling requirements for
many products sold in the United States.<p>

<h4>The Customs Marking Requirements</h4>
Section 304 of the Tariff Act of 1930 requires that every imported article of foreign origin be
marked legibly, conspicuously, and permanently so as to indicate the article's country of origin to
the ultimate purchaser in the United States.  The law has two purposes.  First, it enables the
ultimate purchaser in the United States to buy, or refuse to buy, a product based on its country of
origin.  Second, determining country of origin is necessary for Customs to administer the tariff
laws, which provide different tariff rates for products depending on their origin.  <p>

The "country of origin" is generally the article's country of manufacture, production, or growth.  
Further production or the addition of material in a second country will render the second country
the country of origin if the further production results in a "substantial transformation" of the
article.  Customs defines substantial transformation as "production which results in a new and
different article, with a new name, character, and use."  The country of origin is therefore the
country in which the last substantial transformation took place.<p>

In determining whether the combining of parts and materials constitutes a substantial
transformation, Customs considers the extent of the operations performed and whether the parts
lose their identity and become integral parts of the new article.  Minimal or simple assembly
operations would generally not result in a substantial transformation.  If there is no substantial
transformation, each part must be individually marked to indicate its country of origin prior to
sale to the ultimate purchaser.<p>

The ultimate purchaser is generally considered the last person to receive the merchandise in the
United States in the form in which it was imported.  If the imported merchandise is intended to
be further processed or manufactured in the United States, a determination must be made as to
who the ultimate purchaser will be.  A U.S. manufacturer that buys foreign merchandise will be
considered the ultimate purchaser if the manufacturer processes the imported merchandise such
that it undergoes a substantial transformation in the United States.  If that occurs, the product is
"Made in the U.S.A." for purposes of Customs law and the U.S. manufacturer need not mark the
product it sells to the ultimate consumer.  If the U.S. manufacturer does not substantially
transform the merchandise, however, the manufacturer's customer will be the ultimate purchaser,
and the manufacturer must mark the product with the foreign country of origin.<p>

Under current law, Customs administers the substantial transformation rule on a case-by-case
basis, which often involves subjective judgments as to what constitutes a "new and different"
product, or whether certain processing steps have resulted in a product with a "new name,
character, and use."  These standards are difficult to apply and have created uncertainty and
unpredictability within Customs and the international trade community, especially in situations
involving assembly of components from multiple countries.  Notwithstanding the large number
of administrative and judicial determinations, little guidance exists on the effect of certain types
of processing on the determination of origin.<p>

In our example involving athletic footwear, Customs would require each of the components to be
marked with its country of origin, unless the components were substantially transformed in the
United States.  Customs would analyze whether the assembly operations in the United States
resulted in a new and different product, with a new name, character, and use.  If there were a
substantial transformation in the United States, that is, if the products were "Made in the U.S.A."
under Customs law, Customs would require no marking whatsoever.  <p>

On January 3, 1994, in conjunction with the publication of standards for determining origin
under the North American Free Trade Agreement ("NAFTA"), Customs published two important
notices.  First, Customs notified the public that for determinations of origin within the NAFTA,
substantial transformation would be based on whether there was a change in the tariff
classification of the article.  Second, Customs stated that it was considering extending the
"change in tariff classification" test to all situations in which Customs must determine the
country of origin of a product.  <p>

Under the "change in tariff classification" test, an article would be considered to be substantially
transformed if further processing changed the article's tariff classification.  The change in
classification necessary would, in most cases, involve a change in the first four digits of the
product's classification number under the Harmonized Tariff System.  The location of the
operation resulting in the change of tariff classification would be the article's country of origin. 
The new rule is designed to provide more certainty and uniformity to the substantial
transformation test.<p>

Since January 3, 1994, Customs has revised its proposal twice and continues to review
comments submitted by interested parties.  The effective date of the new regulations will be 90
days after notice of the new regulations is published in the Federal Register.<p>

U.S. manufacturers must analyze whether products assembled in the United States are
substantially transformed in the United States to determine whether the product must be marked
with the foreign country of origin.  The "change in tariff classification" test should provide
additional predictability and certainty to this determination.  Determining the origin and marking
requirements for products comprised of components from various countries, however, will likely
remain an extremely difficult task.<p>

<h4>Federal Trade Commission Requirements</h4>
In the interest of protecting the consuming public, the FTC has repeatedly determined that it is
an unfair or deceptive act within the meaning of section 5 of the Federal Trade Commission Act
to sell a product of foreign origin without disclosing its country of origin.  The rule is based on
the presumption that a substantial portion of the consuming public may have a preference for
products manufactured in the United States, and the absence of any mark or label would mislead
consumers into thinking that a product was of domestic origin.<p>

According to FTC practice, if a product manufactured in the United States contains an imported
component, the seller of the product must disclose the origin of the foreign component if it
retains its essential character despite incorporation into a product.  If assembly of the finished
product caused the foreign component to "lose its identity," however, disclosure of the foreign
origin of the component would not be required.  This standard is essentially the same as the
current Customs law of substantial transformation, discussed above.<p>

The FTC also regulates the circumstances in which a domestic seller may state that a product is
"Made in the U.S.A."  The FTC's standard for an unqualified "Made in the U.S.A." claim is that
"all or virtually all" of the parts and labor used to manufacture the product must be of domestic
origin.  The FTC's standard is therefore different than Customs', which requires merely
substantial transformation in the United States for a product to be considered domestic in origin. 
The FTC's standard is based on evidence demonstrating that "Made in the U.S.A." claims are
highly important to consumers and that consumers interpret such claims to mean that all or
virtually all of both parts and labor are American.  The purpose of the standard is to protect
consumers from deceptive claims and to deny companies that misuse the term "Made in the
U.S.A." an unfair competitive advantage.<p>

In recent cases involving two manufacturers of athletic footwear, the FTC applied the standard
described above and ruled that the companies could not state that their products were "Made in
the U.S.A."  Since significant portions of the parts and labor of the companies' products were
foreign-origin, the FTC's position was that it would be deceptive to describe the products as
"Made in the U.S.A."  The FTC reiterated its position that "all or virtually all" of the parts and
labor used to manufacture the products must be of domestic origin for a product fairly to be
described as "Made in the U.S.A."<p>

The FTC subsequently received 150 comments from consumers, industry, and trade associations
objecting to the "all or virtually all" standard.  Many of the comments stated that, given the
globalization of commerce, the "all or virtually all" standard is unrealistic and unduly restricts
use of the "Made in the U.S.A." claim.  In response to the criticism, the FTC has decided to
convene a public workshop in early 1996 to explore the best ways to balance protection of the
consumer with the reality of today's global economy.<p>

<h4>Conclusion</h4>
With respect to whether a product is "Made in the U.S.A.," Customs and the FTC use different
tests.  Under Customs law, a product that is substantially transformed in the United States is
"Made in the U.S.A.," despite significant previous processing abroad or the use of foreign
components .  Conversely, under FTC law, a product is not "Made in the U.S.A." unless all or
virtually all of the parts and labor are domestic origin.  It is therefore possible that a product
could be "Made in the U.S.A." under Customs law, but not under FTC law.  Since Customs law
is primarily concerned with accurate determinations of foreign origin, the FTC has primacy over
the use of "Made in the U.S.A." claims.<p>

Pending Customs and FTC proceedings highlight the need for accurate country of origin marking
and labeling.  With regard to "Made in the U.S.A." claims, current Customs and FTC practice are
not consistent and may add to the uncertainty faced by U.S. manufacturers and sellers.  Parties
wishing to make "Made in the U.S.A." claims in connection with products to be sold in the
United States should participate in the FTC's public workshop in February 1996 and make their
views known to the agency.  In addition, parties should become generally familiar with the law
and practice in this area and be prepared to revise their practices if necessary to conform to new
Customs and FTC policies.<p>

