<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The Family and Medical Leave Act: 
Supervisor Liability and Other Recent Developments</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>The Family and Medical Leave Act: 
Supervisor Liability and Other Recent Developments</H1><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
One of the most significant recent issues regarding the Family and Medical Leave Act ("FMLA") is the extent to which supervisors can be subject to individual liability for decisions regarding FMLA leave. An Illinois district court recently ruled that supervisors who exercise sufficient control over an employee’s terms and conditions of employment may be held individually liable for FMLA violations. <EM>Freemon v. Foley</EM>, 1995 W.L. 669607 (N.D. Ill.). However, more recently, a Tennessee district court reached the opposite conclusion. <EM>Frizzell v. Southwest Motor Freight, Inc.</EM>, 1995 W.L. 713459 (E.D. Tenn.).<P>
In the Illinois case, a hospital employee was terminated when she failed to provide medical verification for her entire absence to care for her sons with chicken pox. Following her termination, the employee sued the hospital, the human resources vice-president, and her immediate and department supervisors under the FMLA. The court, relying on cases under the Fair Labor Standards Act, which has an identical definition of "employer," ruled that a supervisor can be liable for FMLA violations when the supervisor possesses control over the violation. Because each individual sued was capable of impeding or denying the employee’s FMLA leave, the Court denied their motion for summary judgment. <P>
In the Tennessee case, the former employee, who allegedly became pregnant by her supervisor, sued her employer and supervisor under the Tennessee Human Rights Act ("THRA"), FMLA and Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. The court relied on its earlier decsion that supervisors are not employers for purposes of the THRA to conclude that a similar result should apply for purposes of Title VII and the FMLA. <P>
The Illinois decision is consistent with the Department of Labor regulations interpreting the FMLA. However, the Tennessee case shows courts do not always follow the regulations. <P>
In a case more favorable to employers, another Illinois court ruled that an employee who had previously been granted a reduced work schedule under the FMLA failed to show that her subsequent discharge for excessive absenteeism amounted to discrimination under FMLA. <EM>McCown v. UOP, Inc.</EM>, 1995 W.L. 519818 (N.D. Ill.). The employee was granted a reduced work schedule under the FMLA in order to be home with her recently molested daughter. In a memorandum regarding her absences, her supervisor stated that it was "doubly important" for her to be at work when scheduled because she was already on a reduced schedule under the FMLA. The employee later alleged she was terminated because of her reduced schedule in violation of the FMLA and provided her supervisor’s memorandum as evidence of his discriminatory intent. The court ruled that the memorandum alone was insufficient evidence of discriminatory intent to defeat the employer’s motion for summary judgment, stating that the "FMLA is not a shield to protect employees from legitimate disciplinary action by their employers if their performance is lacking in some manner unrelated to their FMLA leave." <P>
In one of the first Department of Labor ("DOL") actions filed against an employer under the FMLA, the DOL charged a Texas employer with firing an employee for taking leave to care for his hospitalized pregnant wife. <EM>Reich v. Associated Milk Products, Inc.</EM>, D.C. N.Texas, No. 2-94-CV-218-J (2/10/95). The DOL asked for back pay, benefits and other equitable relief. After acknowledging in writing that it recognized the FMLA and that it would not knowingly or intentionally violate the FMLA, the employer settled the lawsuit for $10,000. <P>
The DOL’s first case actually litigated under the FMLA was won by the employer. A Michigan court ruled that a pregnant employee who was discharged for excessive absenteeism after contracting chicken pox was not entitled to reinstatement because she did not inform her company that she was taking leave under the FMLA. <EM>Reich v. Midwest Plastic Eng’g, Inc</EM>., 1995 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 8772; dismissed, 1995 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 12130. The court stated that the FMLA regulations require that "at a minimum, an employee must inform her employer of her condition with sufficient detail to make it evident that the requested leave is protected as FMLA-qualifying leave." The employee did not meet the minimum notification requirements because she failed to tell her employer that she was under a doctor’s care or that she had been hospitalized. Moreover, the court found that she failed to update her employer as to her status and her intent to return to work as required by the employer’s policy, stating that "[t]his alone gave [the employer] a ground to terminate [her] employment." <P>
As the cases above demonstrate, employer and employee rights and responsibilities under the FMLA will be shaped by the courts. These cases also underscore the importance of awareness of FMLA requirements at all management and supervisory levels. <P>
<P>
<center><HR><p>
