<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Participant Contribution Regulations </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>Participant Contribution Regulations </H1><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
Recently, the Department of Labor ("DOL") issued proposed regulations shortening the period within which employers must pay participant contributions to an employee benefit plan trust or to an insurance company. <P>
The current regulations provide that participant contributions to an employee benefit plan generally must be paid into a trust or to an insurance company as soon as they can reasonably be segregated from the employer’s general assets, but no later than 90 days from the date the employer receives or withholds the contributions. <P>
According to the DOL, the revision is necessary because many employers are abusing the current regulations by treating the 90-day maximum as a "safe harbor," allowing a 90-day delay in transmitting participant contributions to the trust or insurance company. Further, the DOL believes the 90-day maximum is too long. <P>
Under the proposed regulations, employers would be required to transmit participant contributions to a trust or insurance company for the plan within the same time period within which the employer is required to make deposits for federal income and employment taxes. For many employers, the proposed regulations would require transmitting participant contributions to the plan trust or insurance company by the next banking day after the employer withholds or receives the contributions.<P>
The proposed regulations apply to participant contributions under medical, dental, life insurance and other welfare plans as well as to 401(k) plans and other retirement plans. Surprisingly, the proposed regulations do not appear to affect the DOL’s 1992 position that participant contributions deducted on a pre-tax basis under a § 125 cafeteria plan are not required to be held in trust. <P>
Employers should contact us if they want more information on the proposed regulations and how they could affect their plans.
<P>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center></BODY>
