<HEAD>
<TITLE> Eleventh Circuit Extends Constitutional Protection to a Woman’s Plan to Marry Another Woman</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<H1>Eleventh Circuit Extends Constitutional Protection to a Woman’s Plan to Marry Another Woman</H1><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
In a decision potentially affecting the employment policies of public employers throughout the country, the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta rules that "strict scrutiny" must be applied to a woman’s First Amendment claims that the Attorney General of Georgia reneged on a job offer in the Law Department of the State of Georgia because of her plans to marry another woman in a religious ceremony recognized by a branch of Judaism. <EM>Shahar v. Bowers, </EM>70 F.3d 1218 (11th Cir. 1995). The Attorney General is expected to seek review by the Supreme Court of this decision which has been hailed as a significant victory by gay and lesbian rights groups. <P>
In July 1991, the Attorney General withdrew an offer of employment as an attorney in the State’s Law Department previously made to Robin Shahar after learning that Ms. Shahar intended to marry another woman. Ms. Shahar sued the Attorney General under 42 U.S.C. § 1983 alleging that his actions violated her rights of intimate and expressive association, freedom of religion, equal protection, and substantive due process. The district court granted summary judgment in favor of the Attorney General on all claims. On appeal, the Eleventh Circuit affirmed summary judgment for the Attorney General on all claims except the claims of interference with the rights of intimate association and expressive association. <P>
The couple were married in South Carolina on July 28, 1991 by a Rabbi performing a traditional Jewish marriage ceremony. Ms. Shahar did not assert that the religious ceremony constituted a valid Georgia civil marriage. Her marriage is apparently recognized by the Reconstructionist Branch of Judaism (of which she and her partner are adherents) and she claimed the ceremony conferred on her and her partner a religious-based "married" status apart from and independent of the civil marriage provided by Georgia law. <P>
The Eleventh Circuit held that the intimate relationship between Ms. Shahar and her partner, although not involving marriage in a civil, legal sense, is nonetheless an intimate relationship entitled to constitutional protection because it was "intimate and highly personal" as well as "inextricably entwined with Shahar’s exercise of her religious beliefs." The Court was careful to note that it was not holding that an association based solely on the sexual orientation of a same sex couple was an intimate association meriting constitutional protection. <P>
After finding the relationship constitutionally protected, the Court went on to apply the standard of strict scrutiny to the claim. Under that standard, the act of the Attorney General in firing Ms. Shahar after learning of her relationship must be deemed to violate her First Amendment rights of intimate association unless the Attorney General could show that his actions were narrowly tailored to serve a compelling governmental interest. The majority remanded to the district court for a determination on this issue. Finding with little analysis that strict scrutiny should apply, the Eleventh Circuit also remanded the expressive association claim.<P>
Although the ultimate outcome is as yet unknown, the case represents a major victory for individuals involved in same sex relationships. It is the first decision of which we are aware that applies the strict scrutiny standard to the government’s actions with respect to homosexual relationships. Nongovernmental employers should be unaffected by the <EM>Shahar </EM>decision.
<P>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center></BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT06-B35-23</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B022-209</DOCOLDNO>
