<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>How to Keep the Other Shoe from Dropping</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><P>
<h1>How to Keep the Other Shoe from Dropping: The Interrelationship of Civil RICO and Criminal Proceedings</h1>
<p>
<a href="/htm/thompson.htm"><H2>Larry D. Thompson</H2></a>
<H6>Reprinted with permission from the <EM>Georgia State Bar Journal</EM>, Vol. 30, No.4</H6>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
<h4>THE DILEMMA:  TO PARTICIPATE IN DISCOVERY OR NOT?</h4>
"[R]acketeering activity," as expressly defined by the federal RICO statute,1 encompasses
numerous specific criminal offenses.  There are four categories of "predicate acts" set forth under
RICO, the commission of which may trigger civil liability:  crimes of violence (murder,
kidnapping, arson, robbery, extortion and obstruction of justice); crimes involving illicit goods
and services (gambling, pornography, narcotics, counterfeiting, theft and trafficking in restricted
goods); crimes involving breach of fiduciary obligations and labor contracts (restrictions on
payments and loans to labor organizations); and crimes of commercial fraud (embezzlement,
securities fraud, mail fraud and wire fraud).2<p>

The great majority of civil RICO cases are brought by plaintiffs alleging violations of the
"commercial fraud provisions," with mail and wire fraud being the most frequently used.3 
Although most civil RICO cases are essentially business disputes, some cases, given the nature
of the predicate act allegations, involve sensitive matters that could give rise to potential criminal
liability for one or more of the parties or representatives of parties.  RICO's predicate acts
involve criminal statutes that are subject to expansive interpretations by some federal
prosecutors and investigative agencies.4  Counsel representing a party or witness involved in
activity within the scope of these statutes therefore should never take the possibility or fact of a
criminal investigation lightly.<p>

Moreover, counsel representing a party or witness in a civil RICO case also needs to be aware of
certain additional issues that may unwittingly involve him or her in a criminal case along with
the client.  For example, the federal witness tampering statute prohibits, among other things,
engaging in misleading conduct with the intent to influence, delay, or prevent the testimony of
any person "in<i> an official proceeding</i>,"5 which can be a civil or administrative matter. 
"Misleading conduct" is not defined, and some commentators have suggested that it may apply
even to routine witness preparation.6 Federal law also prohibits perjury in discovery devices
such as depositions, affidavits or written testimony,7 as well as the subornation or procurement
of perjury.8  The author is aware that some federal judges are referring perjury concerns arising
out of depositions to the Department of Justice for possible criminal prosecution.9<p>

For all of the above reasons, a party or witness in a civil RICO case with concerns about
potential criminal liability needs to be sensitive to the fact that testimony, and even in some
instances the production of documents, may be held to constitute a waiver of the Fifth
Amendment privilege against self-incrimination.10  In <i>United States v. Kordel</i>,11 the United
States Supreme Court held that the Fifth Amendment privilege clearly can be waived where a
party did not invoke it in civil proceedings.12  The specter of losing the Fifth Amendment
privilege is a very strong argument for invoking it, but by doing so a party runs the risk of having
an adverse inference drawn against him by the trier of fact in the civil proceeding.  Thus, in
Baxter v. Palmigiano,13 the Supreme Court held that an adverse inference was not an
impermissible penalty for the exercise of a constitutional right and noted that an adverse
inference was but one of many factors used by the fact-finder in determining whether to assess a
penalty.14<p>

A lawyer who represents a party in a civil RICO case concerned with potential criminal liability
has three primary alternatives:  (1) file a motion to stay the RICO proceedings; (2) file a motion
for a protective order; and (3) advise the client to assert the Fifth Amendment privilege.  The
remainder of this article addresses each of these possible options.<p>
<p>
<h4>STAY OF CIVIL RICO PROCEEDINGS</h4>
The authority for a stay may be found in three sources.  First, "'[t]he power to stay proceedings is
incidental to the power inherent in every court to control the disposition of the causes on its
docket with economy of time and effort for itself, for counsel, and for litigants.'"15  Second, the
All Writs Act empowers the federal courts to issue "all writs necessary or appropriate in aid of
their respective jurisdictions."16  Finally, the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure provide that: 
"In all cases not provided for by rule, the district judges and magistrates may regulate their
practice in any manner not inconsistent with these rules or those of the district in which they
act."17  <p>

The burden of persuasion is on the party seeking the stay,18 and, according to some courts, such
a party "'must make out a clear case of hardship or inequity in being compelled to proceed.'"19 
Although a primary consideration is the extent to which a defendant's Fifth Amendment rights
are implicated,20 the most commonly considered additional factors are those listed by the court
in <i>Golden Quality Ice Cream Co. v. Deerfield Specialty Papers, Inc</i>.21:<p>

<blockquote>	(1) the interest of the plaintiffs in proceeding expeditiously with [the] litigation or
any particular aspect of it, and the potential prejudice to plaintiffs of a delay; (2)
the burden which any particular aspect of the proceedings may impose on the
defendants; (3) the convenience of the court in the management of its cases, and the
efficient use of judicial resources; (4) the interests of persons not parties to the civil
litigation; and (5) the interest of the public in the pending civil and criminal
litigation.22  
</blockquote>
Because "[o]ther factors a court should consider will vary according to the case itself,"23
reported cases also have taken account of the similarity between the civil and criminal
proceedings24 and the extent to which the invocation of the Fifth Amendment privilege would
essentially gut a civil defense.25<p>

	The impossibility of predicting accurately the appropriate length of a stay, particularly in cases
in which the defendant has not yet been indicted, has led some courts to dismiss outright
defendants' motions.26  In<i> Roe v. Operation Rescue</i>,27  for example, the court denied a stay in
part because "there is no way of knowing how long it will be before criminal proceedings (if
any) against the defendants conclude and the applicable statutes of limitation expire."28  The
Supreme Court, however, has indicated that some type of stay may be available and even
appropriate during the pendency of a criminal investigation.29  This approach is supported by
two leading commentators on the grounds that an indictment/no indictment distinction seems
overly formalistic, particularly in cases where indictment is a near certainty or where there is a
very active criminal investigation.30 <p>

	In a recent and important case, <i>In Re Grand Jury Proceedings</i>,31 the Eleventh Circuit has
suggested that a stay of civil proceedings is appropriate for civil litigants facing criminal
investigation and concerned about losing their Fifth Amendment rights.32  In this era of
increasing concern over crowded court dockets, civil RICO litigants should cite this case for the
proposition that a witness' Fifth Amendment rights clearly outweigh the inconvenience of
delaying civil proceedings.<p>

<p>

<h4>PROTECTIVE ORDERS</h4>
	If a civil RICO case involving sensitive matters must proceed, a party then should try to limit
information that can be obtained through discovery or, in the event information is produced,
keep the information confidential or sealed.  The concept of protecting information or limiting
access is directly authorized by Rule 26(c) of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure.33  Although
a protective order in a civil RICO case can be attacked, such an order also can serve to protect
the legitimate interests of a party subject to potential criminal liability.<p>

	In <i>Martindell v. International Tel. &amp; Tel. Corp</i>.,34 for example, depositions were taken pursuant
to a stipulation of confidentiality between the parties and a protective order entered by the court. 
On the basis of the protective order, the district court subsequently denied a government motion
to obtain access to the deposition transcripts for the purpose of a criminal investigation.35  The
Second Circuit affirmed, holding that defendants had testified in reliance on the court's order and
finding that the district court's order appropriately balanced the competing interests of the private
litigants and the public.36 <p>

	The Eleventh Circuit, however, in <i>In Re Grand Jury Proceedings</i>,37  recently rejected the
Second Circuit's <i>Martindell</i> test, and held that a Rule 26(c) protective order does shield relevant
information from a subsequent grand jury investigation.38  In this case, a federal grand jury
issued a subpoena <i>duces tecum</i> for the court reporter's notes of a deposition that had been taken
only after the district court had issued a protective order sealing it.  The district court quashed
the subpoena, noting that the deponent had relied on the protective order and waived his Fifth
Amendment right to remain silent.39  The court of appeals reversed, noting that a district court
does not have the authority under Rule 26(c) or any other provision to grant, in effect, "use
immunity" to civil witnesses.40 <p>

<p>

<h4>AVOIDING SANCTIONS OR ADVERSE INFERENCES RESULTING
FROM THE EXERCISE OF THE FIFTH AMENDMENT PRIVILEGE</h4>
	In addition to moving for a stay of civil proceedings and securing a protective order, a lawyer
who represents a party in a civil RICO case concerned with potential criminal liability may
advise his or her client to assert the Fifth Amendment privilege.  Obviously, however, such an
exercise may lead to an adverse inference or even sanctions against the client and, for that
reason, a lawyer faced with these possibilities should consider taking steps to preclude them
from coming to reality.<p>

<p>

<h5>Use of a Stay to Preclude Sanctions</h5>
	As in other types of cases, a court in a civil RICO case has the discretion to impose sanctions
upon a party invoking the Fifth Amendment privilege.  In addition to the other possible
advantages of a stay in proceedings discussed above, however, moving for a stay may preclude
the imposition of sanctions for such a strategy.<p>

	In <i>Wehling v. Columbia Broadcasting System</i>,41 for example, the plaintiffs, owners of
proprietary and trade schools in Texas, instituted an action alleging defamation as a result of a
news story broadcast over television on the CBS Evening News.  The broadcast contained
statements to the effect that the plaintiffs had defrauded their students, as well as the federal
government, through abuse of federal student loan and grant programs.  When CBS sought
pre-trial discovery concerning the details of the operation of the school, one owner invoked his
Fifth Amendment privilege.  The court ordered the plaintiff to answer the questions posed to him
or, in the alternative, have the lawsuit dismissed under the discretionary authority accorded the
courts under Rule 37 of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure for failure to comply with an order
of discovery.42 <p>

	The plaintiff moved for a protective order requesting a stay of discovery until the threat of
criminal liability had passed.  Plaintiff previously had appeared five times before a federal grand
jury investigating federally insured student loan programs, and in each instance asserted his Fifth
Amendment privilege against self-incrimination.  At the time of deposition, plaintiff's counsel
had stated that plaintiff was still a target of the investigation.  The district court denied the
motion, restated the order and, upon the plaintiff's continued assertion of the privilege, dismissed
the action with prejudice.43 <p>

	The former Fifth Circuit reversed the decision and ordered the district court to enter a protective
order staying discovery for a period of three years, the time within which plaintiff could still be
prosecuted criminally under the applicable statute of limitations.44  In support of its action, the
circuit court stated that it could find no provision in the federal rules authorizing sanctions on a
party resisting discovery by asserting a valid claim of privilege.45  Moreover, the circuit court
could find no valid distinction between a defendant who was sued while under threat of criminal
prosecution, and a plaintiff who is required to bring a lawsuit while also under the threat of
criminal prosecution.46  Because Rule 26 limits the scope of discovery to those matters "not
privileged," the circuit court reasoned that CBS had no valid right to the information protected
by the Fifth Amendment, and, therefore, the plaintiff did not violate the discovery rules in
exercising his privilege.  Balancing the defendant's discovery rights against the plaintiff's
constitutional privilege, the court determined that the sanction of dismissal was simply too
severe.47 <p>

	The Eleventh Circuit recently cited <i>Wehling</i> approvingly in In Re Grand Jury Proceedings,48 in
which the target of a grand jury investigation was deposed in related civil litigation only after
entry of a Rule 26(c) protective order in that litigation.  In reversing the district court's quashing
of a subpoena of the deposition transcript, the Eleventh Circuit held that the protective order did
not shield the transcript.49  In the process, however, it relied upon <i>Wehling</i> to suggest that a stay
of the civil proceeding could protect a litigant's Fifth Amendment rights.50 <p>

<p>

<h5>Avoiding Adverse Inferences</h5>
	A party's decision to exercise its Fifth Amendment right not to testify carries with it the risk of
an adverse inference.  One approach to resisting such an inference being drawn is through Rule
403 of the Federal Rules of Evidence, which provides:<p>

<blockquote>	Although relevant, evidence may be excluded if its probative value is substantially
outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice, confusion of the issues, or
misleading the jury, or by consideration of undue delay, waste of time, or needless
presentation of cumulative evidence.
</blockquote>
This rule was successfully invoked in <i>Farace v. Independent Fire Insurance Co</i>.,51 in which the
plaintiff insurance claimant previously had exercised his Fifth Amendment privilege in a
criminal arson investigation.  In excluding the evidence of the plaintiff's previous refusal to
testify, the court recognized that the prejudicial effect of the plaintiff's having exercised the
privilege outweighed the probative value of that evidence and justified exclusion by the trial
court.52 <p>

	Another approach to avoiding an adverse inference is the suggestion of possible prosecutorial
abuse.  In SEC v. Musella,53 the court noted, in dicta, that it would be reluctant to impose a
penalty on a party who has been indicted for invoking the privilege against self-incrimination
"given the invitation to prosecutorial abuse this might entail."54  As this observation suggests,
the specter of the government cooperating with one side in a civil RICO proceeding and
suggesting whom to depose is very troubling to many, including most judges.<p>

	Although an adverse inference against a party or witness in a civil RICO proceeding is a serious
matter, a witness can refuse to testify on Fifth Amendment grounds and an adverse inference
may not carry the day for the opposite party.  Obviously, in many cases, there are good and
persuasive arguments that can be used to defeat an adverse inference.  Nevertheless, the dilemma
of a party in a sensitive civil RICO case faced with critical considerations of potential criminal
liability is to avoid drawing an adverse inference while still preserving the Fifth Amendment
privilege.55 <p>

<p>

<h4>	ENDNOTES</h4>
<p>
<SMALL><ol>
  <li>	Pub. L. No. 91-452, tit. IX, 84 Stat. 941 (1970) (codified as amended at 18 U.S.C. 1861-68
(1988) &amp; Supp. IV 1992)).</li>
  <li>	<i>See </i>18 U.S.C. 1961(1) (Supp. IV 1992).</li>
  <li>	<i>See Sedima S.P.R.L. v. Imrex Co., </i>473 U.S. 479, 501 (1985) (Marshall, J., dissenting)
(identifying mail and wire fraud as "single most significant reason" for the expansive use of civil
RICO); see also Mark Headley, Comment, "<i>Sedima v. Imres: </i>Civil Immunity for Unprosecuted
RICO Violators?," 85 Colum. L. Rev. 419, 421 (1985) ("Virtually any modern commercial fraud
involves use of the wires or mails and thus arguably constitutes a violation of section 1962(c).").</li>
  <li>	Expansive interpretations are encouraged by the statute.  <i>See</i> The Organized Crime Control of
1970, Pub. L. No. 91-452, 904(a), 84 Stat. 947 (1970) ("The provisions of this title shall be
liberally construed to effectuate its remedial purposes.").</li>
  <li>	18 U.S.C. 1512 (1988) (emphasis added).</li>
  <li>	<i>See e.g.</i>, William H. Jeffress, Jr., "The New Federal Witness Tampering Statute," 22 <i>Am. Crim.
L. Rev.</i> 1 (1984).</li>
  <li>	18 U.S.C. 1621 (1988).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i>. 1622.</li>
  <li>	This article's primary focus on the use of civil discovery materials and testimony in subsequent
criminal proceedings should not obscure the fact that, although relatively few civil RICO claims
lead to criminal investigations, civil RICO cases frequently follow indictments or even highly
publicized criminal investigations.  As in the antitrust and securities areas, the treble damage and
attorneys' fees remedy provided by 18 U.S.C. 1964(c) are powerful lures to a potential civil
RICO plaintiff.  <i>See</i> <i>Sutliff, Inc. v. Donovan Cos</i>., 727 F.2d 648, 652 (7th Cir. 1984) ("The
statute is construed on the model of a treasure hunt.").</li>
  <li>	The Fifth Amendment provides that "no person shall be . . . compelled in any criminal case to be
a witness against himself . . ."  U.S. Const. amend V.  This privilege against self-incrimination
"protects against any disclosures that the witness reasonably believes could be used in a criminal
prosecution [against him or her] or could lead to other evidence that might be so used."  <i>Kastigar
v. United States,</i> 406 U.S. 441, 444-45 (1972).</li>
  <li>	397 U.S. 1 (1970).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 9-10.</li>
  <li>	425 U.S. 308 (1976).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 316-20.</li>
  <li>	<i>Cadillac Ins. Co. v. American Nat'l Bank</i>, 1992 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 2815, at *21 (N.D. Ill. March
10, 1992) (quoting <i>Landis v. North Am. Co</i>., 299 U.S. 248, 254-55 (1936) (Cardozo, J.)).  <i>See</i>
<i>also United States v. Simon</i>, 373 F.2d 649, 652 (2d Cir.), <i>vacated</i>, 389 U.S. 425 (1967).</li>
  <li>	28 U.S.C. 1651(a) (1988).</li>
  <li>	Fed. R. Crim. P. 57.</li>
  <li><i>	United States v. Amrep Corp., </i>405 F. Supp. 1053, 1056 (S.D.N.Y. 1976), <i>aff'd</i> 535 F.2d 1240 (2d
Cir. 1976).</li>
  <li><i>	Roe v. Operation Rescue, </i>123 F.R.D. 508, 509 (E.D. Pa. 1988) (quoting <i>Landis v. North Am.
Co., </i>299 U.S. 248, 255 (1936) (Cardozo, J.)).</li>
  <li>	<i>Federal Sav. and Loan Ins. Corp. v. Molinaro</i>, 889 F.2d 899, 902 (9th Cir. 1989).</li>
  <li>	87 F.R.D. 53, 56 (E.D. Pa. 1980).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i></li>
  <li>	<i>Molinaro</i>, 889 F.2d at 902-03.</li>
  <li>	<i>Brumfield v. Shelton</i>, 727 F. Supp. 282, 284 (E.D. La. 1989).</li>
  <li>	<i>Dienstag v. Bronsen</i>, 49 F.R.D. 327, 329 (S.D.N.Y. 1970) (inconvenience of delaying civil
proceedings until completion of criminal trial was outweighed by defendant's right to protection
against self-incrimination).  <i>See</i> <i>generally</i> Jed S. Rakoff and Howard W. Goldstein, RICO Civil
and Criminal Law and Strategy 11.01 et seq. (1993 ed.).</li>
  <li>	<i>See</i> <i>Fidelity Bankers Life Ins. Co. v. Wedco, Inc</i>., 586 F. Supp. 1123, 1125-1126 (D. Nev. 1984)
(denying stay in part because the parties "cannot control the timing of any criminal
proceedings").</li>
  <li>	123 F.R.D. 508 (E.D. Pa. 1988).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 509.</li>
  <li>	<i>Kordel</i>, 397 U.S. at 10 ("mere act of volunteering the information sought . . . was potentially
incriminatory.").</li>
  <li>	Rakoff and Golstein, <i>supra</i> note 25, 11.03[3], at 11-16 through 11-17.</li>
  <li>	995 F.2d 1013 (11th Cir. 1993).</li>
  <li>	<i>See</i> <i>Id</i> at 1018 n.11 ("[A] civil trial court may stay discovery until the grand jury investigation is
completed.").</li>
  <li>	Rule 26(c) provides, in relevant part, that:</li>
  <li>	Upon motion by a party or by the person from whom discovery is sought, accompanied by a
certification that the movant has in good faith conferred or attempted to confer with other
affected parties in an effort to resolve the dispute without court action, and for good cause
shown, the court in which the action is pending or alternatively, on matters relating to a
deposition, the court in the district where the deposition is to be taken may make any order
which justice requires to protect a party or person from annoyance, embarrassment, oppression,
or undue burden or expense, including one or more of the following:  (1) that the discovery not
be had; (2) that the discovery may be had only on specified terms and conditions, including a
designation of the time or place; (3) that the discovery may be had only by a method of
discovery other than that selected by the party <i>See</i>king discovery; (4) that certain matters not be
inquired into, or that the scope of the discovery be limited to certain matters; (5) that discovery
be conducted with no one present except persons designated by the court; (6) that a deposition
after being sealed be opened only by order of the court; (7) that a trade secret or other
confidential research, development, or commercial information not be disclosed or be disclosed
only in a designated way; (8) that the parties simultaneously file specified documents or
information enclosed in sealed envelopes to be opened as directed by the court.</li>
  <li>	594 F.2d 291 (2d Cir. 1979).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 292-93.</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 296.</li>
  <li>	995 F.2d 1013 (11th Cir. 1993).</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 1018 n. 11.</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 1018.</li>
  <li>	For a similar ruling in the Fourth Circuit, <i>See</i> <i>In Re Grand Jury Subpoena</i>, 836 F.2d 1468 (4th
Cir.), <i>cert denied</i>, 487 U.S. 1240 (1988).</li>
  <li>	608 F.2d 1084 (5th Cir. 1979), <i>reh'q denied</i>, 611 F.2d 1026 (5th Cir. 1980).  This case was
decided prior to September 30, 1981 and, under <i>Bonner v. City of Prichard</i>, 661 F.2d 1206, 1209
(11th Cir. 1981), is binding precedent on the Eleventh Circuit.</li>
  <li>	608 F.2d at 1086.</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i></li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 1088-89.</li>
  <li>	<i>Id</i> at 1087.</li>
