<head>
<title>A ROAD MAP FOR EMPLOYMENT TAX AUDITS
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">
<CENTER><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<h1>A Road Map for Employment Tax Audits
</h1>
<p>
<h2>James B. Sowell</h2>
<H6>Copyright &copy; 1996 by James B. Sowell.</H6>
<HR><p>
</CENTER>
<H4>I.	Introduction</H4>
	In recent years, the Internal Revenue Service (the "Service") has greatly increased its enforcement efforts with regard to employment tax matters.  Since establishing the Employment Tax Examination Program in 1988, the Service has assessed more than $670 million in penalties and back taxes and has forced businesses to reclassify over 430,000 independent contractors as employees.  Compliance efforts have focused primarily on businesses with assets of $3 million or less.  The Service claims that these smaller businesses are most likely to misclassify the status of workers.  However, the painful and unfair by-product of this policy is that most businesses undergoing employment tax audits do not have the financial resources necessary to overcome a reclassification and assessment by the Service.  As a result, aggressive Service agents often use strong arm tactics in an effort to raise revenues while ignoring facts that indicate independent contractor status and failing to inform unwary taxpayers of relief provisions that are available in the event of reclassification.<P>
	At the National Office level, the Service is aware of the grave concerns that small business owners have regarding IRS enforcement efforts to reclassify their workers and is taking actions to address these concerns.  The Service recently has announced two test programs for resolution of employment tax issues.  In addition, the Service has announced that all examining agents handling worker classification issues will receive additional training and has released a proposed draft of the training materials (the "Training Guide") for comments from the private sector.  <P>
	While commentators and industry representatives generally are encouraged by the Service's efforts to level the playing field in the employment tax arena, it is certain that handling an employment tax audit will remain a difficult task.  As with many factual determinations, the investigation into the work relationship often will involve asking innumerable questions and reviewing countless documents.  The determination of a worker's status turns on many factual nuances, so one must be acutely aware of all facts surrounding the applicable work relationships. <P>
	It is equally important to understand the legal issues that can arise in the audit and the administrative routes that are available to settle the audit.  This article is intended to serve as a guide to these various issues.  The article begins by discussing the different tax and reporting requirements that follow under the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended (the "Code"), from the classification of a worker as an employee or an independent contractor.  It follows with a discussion of the factors and provisions that control in determining whether a worker is classified as an employee or an independent contractor.  The article then sets out the various parties who can be held liable for employment taxes, some of whom generally are not thought of as an "employer" in the traditional sense of the word.  Next, this article discusses numerous employment tax relief provisions that are available where workers are reclassified.  The article follows with a discussion of penalties and interest that may be applicable where a worker is reclassified and indicates situations where such penalties and interest may be reduced or avoided.  This article then discusses the application of the statute of limitations to an employment tax case and finally concludes with a discussion of the new programs available for resolution of employment tax audits.  
<P>
<H4>II.	Ramifications of Worker Reclassification</H4>
<P>
	Numerous ramifications can follow where workers are reclassified as employees.  The obligations imposed on a company under the Code are very different depending upon how workers are classified.  The Code essentially imposes no obligation on the company that uses an independent contractor, except that the company must file a Form 1099 reporting amounts paid to the independent contractor in the taxable year where the amount of such payments exceeds $600.  By contrast, a company must withhold income and social security (FICA) taxes on wages paid to employees.  In addition, an employer is required to match the amount of FICA taxes withheld and also must pay Federal unemployment taxes (FUTA) on wages, subject to credits for tax payments made into state unemployment funds.  Where workers are reclassified as employees, the company may be liable for all FICA, FUTA, and income withholding taxes owed with respect to such workers for all open years, plus applicable penalties and interest.  <P>
	While liability for employment taxes generally will be the most significant concern in an employment tax audit, there are other potentially disastrous ramifications that can follow from the classification of workers as employees.  First, a company must take all employees into consideration in determining whether a qualified retirement plan is nondiscriminatory.  If the nondiscrimination rules are violated, the employer's plan will become disqualified, and the Service could disallow any deductions taken with respect to contributions made on behalf of participants who are not vested with respect to such amounts.  Furthermore, amounts contributed to a plan on behalf of individuals who are vested with respect to such amounts could be imputed as income to these individuals in the year they became vested.  The worker who previously thought that he or she was an independent contractor also may forfeit the ability to establish and maintain a Keough Plan.<P>
	In addition to the disqualification of retirement plans, key employees and/or highly compensated individuals could be forced to include in income (1) all amounts attributable to the cost of group term life insurance, (2) a portion of amounts received under accident and health plans, and (3) amounts received as no-additional-cost service fringe benefits and qualified employee discounts where such benefits are provided on a discriminatory basis.  Finally, workers who are reclassified as employees will be limited by the 2% floor in deducting business expenses incurred with respect to their employment.

<H4>III.	Classification.
</H4>	There are numerous ways for a worker to be classified either as an employee or independent contractor.  The tax ramifications that follow from the reclassification of a worker can vary depending on which provision is used.  This section details the various provisions that govern the determination of a worker's status.  <P>
	<STRONG>A.	Common Law Employee.</STRONG><P>
	In an employment tax audit, the Service is most likely to assert that workers are employees under the common law rules.  The Treasury Regulations generally provide that an employer-employee relationship exists if the person for whom an individual performs services has the right to control and direct the individual with respect to both "the result to be accomplished by the work" and "the details and means by which that result is accomplished."  In other words, if the "employee is subject to the will and control of the employer not only as to what shall be done but how it shall be done," a common law employment relationship exists for federal employment tax purposes.<P>
	The Service has published a list of 20 factors on which it relies to characterize a worker's status.  The 20 factors are:<P>
<OL>
<LI>	Whether a worker is required to comply with other persons' instructions about when, where, and how he is to work.
<LI>	Whether a worker is required to be trained.
<LI>	Whether a worker's services are integrated into business operations so that the success or continuation of the business depends to an appreciable degree on the performance of such services.
<LI>	Whether the services must be rendered personally.   
<LI>		Whether the persons for whom the services are performed hire, supervise, and pay assistants.
<LI>		Whether the services are performed as part of a continuing relationship between the worker and the person for whom the services are performed.
<LI>	Whether the worker has set hours during which he must work. 
<LI>	Whether the worker is required to work substantially full-time. 
<LI>	Whether the work must be performed on the employer's premises.
<LI>Whether the order or sequence of the services the worker is to perform are set by the person for whom the services are performed.
<LI>Whether the worker is required to submit regular oral or written reports.
<LI>Whether the worker is paid by the hour, week or month, or whether he is paid by the job or on a straight commission basis.
<LI>Whether the worker's business expenses are paid by the person for whom he performs the services.
<LI>Whether the worker is furnished with tools and materials.
<LI>Whether the worker has a significant investment in facilities used in the performance of his services.  
<LI>Whether the worker can realize a profit or suffer a loss from his services, greater than the profit or loss ordinarily realized by employees.
<LI>Whether the worker performs services for multiple unrelated parties at the same time.
<LI>Whether the worker makes his services available to the general public.
<LI>Whether the person for whom the services are performed has the right to discharge the worker.
<LI>Whether the worker has the right to terminate his relationship with the person for whom the services are performed at any time without incurring liability.

</OL>

	As one might imagine, the application of these 20 factors is very subjective.  Some factors are given more weight than others, depending upon the occupation at issue.  As the taxpayer's representative, it will be important to understand the nature of the taxpayer's industry and to be aware of any authority that might exist applying the factors to workers in that industry. 
<P>	In the recently released draft of the Training Guide which will be used in training IRS examiners on worker classification issues, the Service emphasizes that there is no "magic number" of relevant factors and that the 20-factor test does not embody the legal control test used for determining worker status.  These "factors merely point to facts to be used in evaluating the extent of the right to direct and control."
	<P>In the Training Guide, the Service segregates some of the 20 factors into different categories that relate to the type of control for which the factors are relevant.  First, the Training Guide addresses "behavioral control" and indicates that factors 1 and 2 should be analyzed to determine whether there is a right to direct or control how the worker performs the specific task for which he or she is hired.  Second, the Training Guide discusses "financial control" and indicates that factors 12, 13, 15, 16, and 18 should be considered in determining whether there is a right to direct or control how the business aspects of the worker's activities are conducted.  Third, the Training Guide states that the examining agent should analyze the "relationship of the parties" and should evaluate factors 6, 19, and 20 as well as considering employee benefits and the intent of the parties as evidenced by the written contracts in determining how the parties perceive their relationship.  Finally, the Training Guide indicates that factors 6 through 9 generally should be accorded lesser significance.
	<P>The Training Guide correctly states that control is a matter of degree and that even in the clearest case where a worker is an independent contractor, the worker will be constrained in some way.  In an obvious effort to curb the zeal of overaggressive agents, the Training Guide also makes the following statement:
     <P>It is important to remember that the results can be either that the worker is an employee or an independent contractor.  A case which results in a 'no change' does not indicate there is a problem with the examination process.  In fact, if numerous cases selected for audit result in 'no change,' there may be a problem with the process for selection of returns for audit, not with the examination results.
<P>
	<STRONG>B.	Statutory Employees.</STRONG><P>
	The Code provides that individuals holding certain positions or engaging in certain occupations will be considered employees for FICA tax purposes regardless of their status under the common law rules.  These "statutory employees" are:
<OL>
<LI>	an officer of a corporation;
<LI>	an agent or commissioned driver who delivers produce, meat, or laundry;
<LI>	a full-time life insurance salesman;
<LI>	a person who works at home under the direction of the party that supplies the materials and supplies for the work;
<LI>	a traveling salesman; or
<LI>	a common law employee.

</OL>

	With the exception of full-time life insurance salesmen and home workers, these persons are considered employees for FUTA tax purposes as well.  
<P>	The Treasury Regulations provide certain exceptions with respect to these various classifications.  For instance, an individual will not be classified as an employee merely by falling within one of the occupational groups set forth above unless (i) the individual's contract for services contemplates that substantially all the services to which the contract relates with respect to the designated occupation will be performed personally by such individual, (ii) the individual does not have a substantial investment in the facilities used to perform the services, and (iii) the services are part of a continuing relationship with the person for whom the services are provided and are not in the nature of a single transaction.  It is important to note that where workers are classified as statutory employees but not common law employees, the employer will not be liable for federal income withholding taxes.
	<P><STRONG>C.	Code § 3508 Statutory Non-Employees
</STRONG><P>	Code § 3508(a) provides that "qualified real estate agents" and "direct sellers" are treated as non-employees for purposes of all taxes imposed under the Code.  A "qualified real estate agent" must be a licensed real estate agent.  A "direct seller" must be engaged in the trade or business of selling (or soliciting the sale of) consumer products in the home or a place other than a permanent retail establishment.  
<P>	A direct seller need not necessarily sell consumer products, but may recruit, train, counsel, or otherwise motivate individuals who sell such products.  The proposed regulations provide that "consumer products" include only tangible personal property which is distributed in commerce and which is normally used for personal, family, or household purposes.  However, the requirement that a direct seller must be limited to selling tangible personal property finds no support in the statute, and two courts have held that the term "consumer product" should be construed to include tangible consumer products as well as intangible consumer services.  Based upon a statement in the Training Guide, it appears that the Service intends to follow the result reached in these two cases, "pending finalization of the regulations and further consideration of the issue in that context."
	<P>The compensation paid to both qualified real estate agents and direct sellers must be directly related to sales or other output rather than the number of hours worked.  This requirement will be satisfied if at least 90% of the total remuneration received by the individual is determined on such basis. 
	<P>Finally, both qualified real estate agents and direct sellers must perform services pursuant to contracts which provide that they will not be treated as employees for Federal tax purposes.  According to the proposed regulations, a contract stating that an individual will not be treated as an employee will satisfy the written contract requirement only if it specifically states that such treatment is for "Federal tax purposes." 
	<P>It is conceivable that a worker could be classified as both a statutory employee under Code § 3121(d) and a statutory non-employee under Code § 3508.  For example, this could arise where a full-time life insurance salesman calls on customers in their homes or offices.  In this situation, it appears that Code § 3121(d) will override Code § 3508 so the worker will be treated as an employee for FICA, and in some situations FUTA, tax purposes, but will remain a non-employee (i.e., independent contractor) for purposes of federal income tax withholding. 
<P>
     <H4>IV.	Employers and Other Liable Parties</H4>
	People generally think of the person for whom a worker provides services as being the only party that is liable for employment taxes.  However, this is not always the case.  This section outlines the various parties that can be held liable for such taxes.  
	<P><STRONG>A.	Employers.</STRONG>
	<P>The "employer" is primarily liable for employment taxes.  The term "employer" generally means the person for whom an individual performs or performed services as an employee.  However, Code § 3401(d) provides that if the person for whom the individual performs services does not control the payment of wages, the term "employer" means the person having control of the payment of such wages.  While Code § 3401(d) technically applies only for purposes of federal income withholding taxes, this definition of employer has been judicially expanded to include FICA and FUTA taxes as well.  
	<P>"Payor liability" under Code § 3401(d) has become particularly significant in recent years, given the increased scrutiny by the Service of industries such as nurse registries and referral agencies where the service recipient and payor are not the same party.  Companies involved in these and other industries that "lease" workers to other parties often do not exert sufficient control to cause the workers on their payroll to be classified as their common law employees.  However, where the "lessee" exercises sufficient control to cause the worker to be treated as its common law employee, the "lessor" may be treated as that worker's employer by virtue of its "control" over payment of the worker's wages.  
	<P>There is little guidance regarding the meaning of "control" for purposes of Code § 3401(d).  However, to the extent that a party exercises or has the right to exercise control over who gets paid, the amount paid, and when payments are made, such party likely will be treated as an employer for federal employment tax purposes.  The Service and at least one court have gone even further, holding that regardless of who fixes the amount or terms of the payment, the party who actually pays the wages will be treated as the employer under Code § 3401(d).   
	<P>Because the payor's liability for employment taxes derives from the worker's status as a common law employee of the service recipient, it appears that where the service recipient would be exempt from paying some or all of the employment taxes if it were the payor, the actual payor will be exempt as well.  In addition, where "payor liability" applies under Code § 3401(d), only the payor is liable for employment taxes; the lessee of the worker will not be secondarily liable.
     	<P><STRONG>B.	Code § 3505 Liability for Third-Parties Paying or Providing for Wages
</STRONG><P>
	Code § 3505 imposes liability for employment taxes on certain third parties who are not employers but who pay or provide for wages.  It is easier to appreciate the situations in which a party will be held liable under Code § 3505 if one first understands why the provision was added to the Code.  Prior to enactment, third parties engaged in "net payroll financing," whereby they advanced funds to troubled employers (usually subcontractors in the construction industry) in an amount sufficient to cover the net wages due to employees without paying the government the withholding taxes that were due on those wages.  The government usually could not collect such taxes because the employer was insolvent, and the third party did not "control" the payment of wages and thus was not an "employer" responsible for withholding and paying employment taxes under Code § 3401(d).
	<P>Congress addressed this problem by imposing liability in two distinct situations.  First, where a lender, surety, or other person pays wages directly to an employee or group of employees of another, such party is liable for an amount equal to the taxes that the employer is required to deduct and withhold, but not the employer's portion of the employment taxes.  Second, if a lender, surety, or other person supplies funds to an employer for the specific purpose of paying employee wages, that person can be held liable for withholding taxes if the indirect payment was made with actual notice or knowledge that the employer did not intend or would not be able to make timely payment or deposit of amounts required to be withheld from wages.  In the latter situation, the third party's liability (including liability for pre-judgment interest) cannot exceed 25% of the amount supplied to the employer for the payment of wages.  In both cases, amounts paid by the third party are credited against the liability of the employer.  Accordingly, there can be no double recovery even though Code § 3505 imposes liability in the form of a penalty rather than a tax.
<P><STRONG>C.  100% Penalty for Responsible Persons Under Code § 6672</STRONG><P>
Any person who is required to collect, truthfully account for, and pay over withheld taxes, and who willfully fails to do so is liable for a penalty equal to the tax not collected, or not accounted for and paid over.  This penalty is commonly referred to as the "100% penalty" since it imposes on responsible persons a penalty equal to 100% of the employment taxes that should have been withheld and paid over. 
<P>	For purposes of Code § 6672, a "person" is an officer or employee of a corporation or a member or employee of a partnership who is "under a duty" to collect, truthfully account for, and pay over withheld taxes.  This definition is not all inclusive, however, and other persons such as directors, prospective purchasers, creditors, accountants, and bankers also have been held liable.
	<P>The determination of whether an individual is a responsible person is dependent on the facts and circumstances of the particular case.  Courts generally inquire as to whether the potential responsible persons had authority over the allocation of corporate funds.  In determining whether such authority existed, courts have looked at factors such as the entity's governing documents, the person's position within and financial interest in the company, the individual's authority to hire and fire employees, his or her authority to execute corporate checks or prepare corporate tax returns, the ability to borrow money, and the authority to make corporate financial decisions.  Generally, the mere ability to write checks and pay taxes on behalf of a company is not enough to make an individual a responsible person.  In order to be liable under Code § 6672, a person must also have discretion over which creditors are paid and when. 
	<P>To impose liability under Code § 6672, the Service also must show that the responsible person's failure to withhold was "willful."  However, the standard for showing willfulness is low.  Willfulness will be present where withheld employment taxes are "knowingly and intentionally" used to pay other expenses.  Under this standard, it will be very difficult for a responsible person who was aware or should have been aware that payroll taxes were delinquent to show that he or she did not act willfully.  
	<P>While it seems inappropriate to assess the Code § 6672 penalty against a responsible person when such amounts are still collectible from the employer, the Service is under no obligation to pursue the employer before imposing the 100% penalty.  Moreover, if someone is a responsible person, that person may be required to pay an amount equal to the entire tax due, even though there may be other responsible persons who also could pay a portion of the tax. 
	<P>In the past, the Service has been very aggressive in asserting that individuals were responsible persons.  However, in 1993, the Service revised its policy with respect to identifying responsible persons and indicates that it now will focus its collection efforts on those persons truly responsible under the law for collecting and paying over employment taxes.  According to the revised statement, responsibility should be determined based upon a person's status, duty, and authority.  Persons who perform ministerial acts without exercising independent judgment will not be subject to the 100% penalty.  In addition, the Service generally will not impose the 100% penalty on responsible persons where the Service has entered into an installment agreement or bankruptcy payment plan with the company for payment of the taxes as long as the company adheres to the plan.
	<P>Code §§ 3505 and 6672 both impose liability in the form of a penalty rather than imputing liability for the underlying tax.  Accordingly, it is possible that the Service could attempt to collect the full amount of the tax due twice; once from the lender under Code § 3505 and once from the responsible person under Code § 6672.  In Security Pacific Business Credit, Inc. v. U.S., the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals allowed the Service to collect the amount of the underlying tax from a responsible person under Code § 6672 and to collect pre-judgment interest (which was not available under Code § 6672) from a lender under Code § 3505(b).  There, the Service did not obtain a windfall since it merely collected the taxes and interest that it was owed.  It is doubtful that the Service would attempt to treat Code § 3505 or 6672 as a real penalty rather than a means for collecting the tax owed since courts probably would impose a heavy burden of proof upon the Service in establishing entitlement to a true penalty.  
<P>
     <H4>V.	Relief Provisions</H4>
		A determination that a company's workers are employees does not necessarily mean that liability for employment taxes will be imposed.  There are a number of relief provisions that can limit or eliminate an employer's liability for unpaid employment taxes.  These provisions are discussed below.  
<P><STRONG>A.	Section 530 Statutory Relief
</STRONG><P>		If the examining agent determines that a class of workers should be reclassified as employees, the first and foremost weapon for use in combatting any deficiency is section 530 of the Revenue Act of 1978 ("Section 530").  Section 530 is an "off-Code" provision that was enacted in 1978 to combat what Congress perceived to be abusive practices by the Service in connection with employment tax audits.  Congress saw the need for legislative guidance in this area and felt it necessary to provide "interim" relief until Congress could complete its study of the employment tax area.  Initially, Section 530 was to expire on December31, 1979.  However, this provision was extended indefinitely by the Tax Equity and Fairness Reform Act of 1982.
		<P>Section 530 provides that an employer is relieved from federal employment tax liability where the employer can demonstrate (i)that it has consistently treated similarly situated workers as independent contractors since 1977, (ii)that it filed all federal tax returns, including information returns, since 1978 on a consistent basis with the workers being treated as independent contractors, and (iii)that it had a reasonable basis for treating the workers as independent contractors.  Relief under Section 530 will continue on a prospective basis as long as the employer continues to satisfy the reporting consistency rule even after it is determined that such workers are properly classified as employees.  
		<P>Section 530 can apply to both common law and statutory employees.  This section terminates an employer's liability for employment taxes as well as related interest and penalties but does not change the status of a worker from an employee to an independent contractor.  Accordingly, Section 530 does not affect the employee's liability with respect to his or her share of employment taxes due.  In addition, Section 530 only applies with respect to employment tax determinations and does not affect liability for income taxes that can arise from plan disqualifications and other such actions.  
		<P>While the Service traditionally has shown a strong bias against applying Section 530, it is clear that the Service cannot ignore the existence of this provision in conducting an audit.  In assessing liability against the Service for a taxpayer's costs and attorney's fees under Code §7430, a court recently defined the relative burdens of the Service and the taxpayer as follows:  <P>
[T]he most logical interpretation of section 530 is that Congress intended taxpayers and the IRS to work together to establish reasonableness.  This joint responsibility can be allocated most appropriately by requiring the taxpayer to come forward with an explanation and enough evidence to establish prima facie grounds for a finding of reasonableness.  However, as reflected in the statute, this threshold burden is relatively low and can be met with any reasonable showing.  Once the taxpayer has made this prima facie showing, the burden then shifts to the IRS to verify or refute the taxpayer's explanation.

<P>
	<P>	According to the Training Guide, it is not even necessary for the taxpayer to claim relief under Section 530 for this section to apply.  This appears to signal a shift in the Service's willingness to consider Section 530.  Pursuant to the IRS mission, an examining agent "must explore the applicability of section 530 even if the taxpayer does not raise the issue." 
		<P>In order to qualify for relief under Section 530, the taxpayer must satisfy a number of requirements.  These requirements are discussed in detail below.  
	<P>	<STRONG>1.	Consistent Treatment of Similarly Situated Workers</STRONG>
		<P>If an employer is to qualify for relief under Section 530, the employer must demonstrate that it has treated workers holding substantially similar positions as independent contractors for any period beginning after December 31, 1977.  While this requirement seems relatively simple, a closer analysis reveals a number of thorny issues.  
		<P>	a.	 What is "For Any Period"?  
		<P>Although Section 530 provides that the taxpayer must not have treated similarly situated workers as employees for any period beginning after December31, 1977, where an employer treated its workers as independent contractors but subsequently reclassified such workers as employees, relief will not be denied for any periods prior to the period in which such individuals were treated as employees.  For example, if a company treated a class of its workers as independent contractors for all periods prior to 1996 but began treating some of these workers as employees in that year, Section 530 relief could be available with respect to all similarly situated workers for taxable years prior to 1996, but would not be available for any such workers thereafter.  <P>
			b.	 What is "Treated"?  <P>
		For purposes of determining the "treatment" of workers, the statute does not focus on the day-to-day treatment of the worker, but instead looks specifically to the treatment for employment tax purposes.  Revenue Procedure 85-18 sets forth specific guidelines for determining whether a taxpayer "treated" an individual as an employee within the meaning of Section 530.  First, the revenue procedure states that the withholding of income or FICA taxes from an individual's wages will constitute "treatment" of the individual as an employee, regardless of whether the tax is paid over to the government.  Second, except in the limited circumstances discussed below, the filing of an employment tax return for a period with respect to an individual is "treatment" of the individual as an employee for that period, regardless of whether tax was withheld from the individual. 
		<P>One exception where the filing of an employment tax return will not constitute "treatment" of an individual as an employee applies where the Service prepares a return for a taxpayer under the authority granted by Code §6020(b).  The signing of an audit Form 2504 also will not constitute "treatment" under Section 530.  <P>
		The more important exception where a taxpayer will not be considered to have treated a worker as an employee by virtue of filing an employment tax return and paying the underlying tax involves the filing of a delinquent or amended employment tax return for a particular period as a result of Service compliance procedures.  If this exception did not exist, a taxpayer would be unable to dispute an employment tax determination in court without destroying its qualification under Section 530.  A taxpayer cannot file for relief in the Tax Court for employment tax disputes and thus, in order to get into federal district court or the Claims Court, the taxpayer must pay the deficiency and sue for a refund.  If the filing of an amended return and payment of taxes for a period under audit constituted "treatment" for purposes of Section 530, the taxpayer would be caught in a catch-22 because it would be deemed to have "treated" the worker as an employee by fulfilling the requirements to challenge the assessment in court and would forego relief under Section 530 for periods subsequent to the filing.<P>  
		The revenue procedure provides that collection or examination activities constitute compliance procedures.  However, where the Service sends a notice merely advising the taxpayer that no return has been filed and requests information from the taxpayer, such action is not a compliance procedure.  As long as the taxpayer only withholds employment taxes or files employment tax returns pursuant to compliance procedures for the period under audit, it will not be deemed to have "treated" the workers as employees.  But where employment taxes are paid or returns are filed for periods following those under audit, such action will constitute "treatment" of the workers as employees for those periods.<P>
			c.	What are "Substantially Similar Positions"?  <P>
		In order to satisfy the first requirement of Section 530, all workers in "substantially similar positions" must have been treated as independent contractors.  The determination of whether workers are similarly situated is important in another context under Section 530 as well.  In relying on a prior audit for purposes of obtaining relief under Section 530, the taxpayer must show that the workers covered by the audit held positions that are substantially similar to the current workers.  Although the incentives vary depending upon the context of the determination, the analysis should be the same under both scenarios.<P>
		The determination of whether workers are similarly situated is dependent on all the facts and circumstances.  According to the Training Guide, "the day-to-day services that workers provide and the method by which they perform those services" as well as the similarity of job functions are important factors in determining whether workers hold substantially similar positions.  <P>
		The Service will disregard certain factors in analyzing the similarity of workers' positions.  The Service believes that "[d]ifferences in the positions held by the respective individuals that result from the treatment of one individual as an employee and the other" as an independent contractor should be disregarded in making this determination.  For example, the fact that an employee participates in the taxpayer's qualified pension plan or health plan and an independent contractor does not will not be considered as support for disparate treatment of the workers.  <P>
		There is not a great deal of case law authority discussing when workers will be treated as holding substantially similar positions.  In Lambert's Nursery and Landscaping, Inc. v. U.S., the Fifth Circuit focused on the structure of the relationship between the service recipient and the worker rather than the type of work performed in determining whether the workers' positions were substantially similar.  The court affirmed the decision of the magistrate who found that the taxpayer could rely on a prior audit in which landscape workers were treated as independent contractors for purposes of gaining Section 530 relief with respect to janitors, since landscape workers and janitors were "substantially similar" in their relationship to the taxpayer.  In making this determination, the court looked at whether the workers were treated similarly "in terms of control, supervision, pay, and demands."  <P>
		More recently, in Crowd Management & Services, Inc. v. U.S., the court analyzed a situation where the relevant workers were engaged in the same line of work as workers who previously had been classified as employees.  In attempting to show that the change in the workers' status to independent contractor was justified and that these workers were not in a substantially similar position to those workers previously classified as employees, the taxpayer introduced evidence that the workers classified as independent contractors had more autonomy in performing their jobs than the prior employees.  While seemingly agreeing that a substantial decrease in the workers' level of autonomy could cause workers to be treated as not holding "substantially similar positions" to others workers in the same line of business, this court rejected the taxpayer's argument because it found that while these workers did exercise more autonomy, they, in fact, were still subject to the same degree of control as the prior employees.  <P>
		Although the courts in Lambert's Nursery and Crowd Management did not consider the workers' line of business to be determinative of whether the workers had substantially similar positions, the Service seems to give a significant amount of weight to this factor.  In fact, in determining whether a taxpayer can qualify for the prior audit safe harbor, the Service takes the position that a corporation cannot rely on a prior audit where it subsequently begins conducting a new line of business, apparently because the workers engaged in the new business cannot hold positions that are substantially similar to those workers who were engaged in the old business.  In taking this position, the Service acknowledges that the Fifth Circuit held against it on this issue in Lambert's Nursery.  <P>
		<STRONG>2.	Reporting Requirements</STRONG><P>
		In order to qualify for relief under Section 530, the taxpayer must have timely filed all federal tax returns, including information returns, for all periods beginning after December 31, 1978 consistently treating the workers as independent contractors.  Treas. Reg. §1.6041-1(a) requires, with certain exceptions, that information returns for compensation aggregating $600 or more paid to another person by one who is engaged in a trade or business must be made on Forms 1096 (Annual Summary and Transmittal of U.S. Information Returns) and 1099 (Information Return).  No information return need have been filed with respect to workers who received less than $600 from the taxpayer during the year.  In addition, a taxpayer that mistakenly, but in good faith, files the wrong type of Form 1099 will not forfeit eligibility under Section 530. <P>
		It appears that the filing requirement must be satisfied for all periods after 1978 or such shorter period as the taxpayer has been in business and using workers occupying positions similar to those workers involved in the audit.  Merely filing the appropriate returns for the periods under examination will not be sufficient.  <P>
		<STRONG>3.	Reasonable Basis</STRONG><P>
		Finally, a taxpayer must show that it had a reasonable basis for treating the applicable workers as independent contractors to qualify for relief under Section 530.  This requirement can be met by satisfying any one of three safe harbors or by showing that the taxpayer had an "other reasonable basis" for classifying its workers as independent contractors.  The legislative history states that the reasonable basis requirement is to be construed liberally in favor of taxpayers, and the Training Guide repeats this command. <P>
			a.	Safe Harbors
			<P>	(1)	Judicial Precedent<P>
		The first safe harbor provides that a reasonable basis will exist where the employer can show that there is judicial precedent or published rulings, or a private letter ruling or determination letter issued with respect to the employer, supporting its position that the worker was an independent contractor.  The Internal Revenue Manual provides that in order to rely on judicial precedent or a revenue ruling, the taxpayer must document (particularly by the cases or arguments) how the issues in the precedents relied upon parallel the treatment of the taxpayer's similarly situated workers.  A taxpayer cannot rely on a precedent where additional substantial evidence of an employer-employee relationship exists.  However, given Congress' command in the legislative history that "reasonable basis" should be construed liberally in favor of the taxpayer, it should not be necessary to show identity of facts to rely on established precedent.  <P>
		Court cases provide little guidance as to the similarity of facts that must be shown.  The Service recognizes that the precedent relied on need not relate to the taxpayer's business or industry, and in one ruling, the Service allowed a taxpayer to rely on precedent with facts that were "generally similar" (i.e., the similarities outweighed the differences) to those present in the taxpayer's situation.  In more recent rulings, however, the Service has taken a stricter approach, seemingly requiring a near identity of facts before a taxpayer may rely on this safe harbor.  <P>
		One troubling point with this safe harbor should be acknowledged.  The statute provides that "the taxpayer's treatment of such individual for such period was in reasonable reliance" on judicial precedent, etc.  Based on this language, the Service takes the position that a taxpayer cannot rely on precedent decided after the years that are at issue in the audit (or presumably any years under audit that are prior to the court decision).  However, even if the Service's interpretation of this safe harbor is correct, a taxpayer still should be granted relief under Section 530 since a subsequent court decision rendered on similar facts shows that the taxpayer had an "other reasonable basis" beyond the safe harbor for classifying its workers as independent contractors.  <P>
		With regard to private letter rulings and determination letters, it is clear that a taxpayer cannot meet the safe harbor unless the taxpayer was the subject of the ruling or determination letter relied upon.  However, although private rulings issued to other parties and information letters will not qualify a taxpayer for relief under the "precedent" safe harbor, they also may provide the taxpayer with an "other reasonable basis" for its classification of the workers.  <P>
			(2)	Prior Audit<P>
		The second safe harbor under Section 530 provides that an employer can rely on a prior audit by the Service that did not result in the assessment of employment taxes, even if the prior audit was not an employment tax audit.  An "audit" must involve an official I.R.S. examination of the taxpayer's books; a compliance interview will not suffice.  In addition, audits conducted by agencies other than the Service will not qualify a taxpayer for relief under this safe harbor.  The audit of another party engaged in the same industry will not bring a taxpayer within the prior audit safe harbor, although such an audit may provide the taxpayer with an "other reasonable basis" for treating its workers as independent contractors.  <P>
		There appears to be no limitation as to when the audit may have occurred, although prior audits may be relied on only for avoiding deficiencies for taxable years beginning after December 31, 1977.  While taxpayers may rely on audits that were closed well before the period under examination, the statute requires that the workers who were the subject of the prior audit must hold positions that are substantially similar to the current workers, so it is important that the circumstances of the work relationship not have changed since the time of the prior audit.  <P>
		In order to qualify for the safe harbor, the prior audit must relate to the business of the taxpayer that hired the workers who are potentially subject to reclassification.  A business may rely on the audit of its predecessor in treating its workers as independent contractors.  However, an audit of the worker or of the individual that owns the corporation operating the business will not suffice.  In addition, where a common parent of an affiliated group is audited, the Service takes the position in its Training Guide that the subsidiary will not be entitled to relief unless it is examined in connection with the parent.  <P>
		As with the judicial precedent safe harbor, the Service will require taxpayers to show actual reliance upon the prior audit in deciding to treat workers as independent contractors.  However, the Training Guide states that in order to show such reliance, the taxpayer need only show that the class of workers currently under consideration were treated as independent contractors during the period covered by the prior audit. <P>
		According to the Training Guide, the taxpayer has the burden of showing that a prior audit took place.  The taxpayer can meet this burden by furnishing a copy of correspondence connected with an IRS audit.  In addition, if the taxpayer informs the examining agent that an audit was conducted in a particular year, the taxpayer will be deemed to have satisfied its burden if the Service can verify through existing records that the audit did occur.  <P>
			(3)	Industry Practice<P>
		Under the third safe harbor, an employer can rely on a long-standing recognized practice of a significant segment of the industry in which the services were performed of treating similarly situated workers as independent contractors.  There are several questions that must be answered in determining whether a taxpayer qualifies for this safe harbor.  <P>
		First, one must determine what constitutes a "recognized practice."  The most significant question here is what is the relevant area for determining whether the practice is recognized.  The Service initially argued that the practice of treating workers as independent contractors in the relevant industry must be recognized nationwide.  However, it now is generally accepted that the relevant area for evaluating the taxpayer's industry consists of the geographic region where businesses compete for the same customers and provide the same or similar services as the taxpayer.  Accordingly, the determination as to whether taxpayer's treatment of the workers constitutes a "recognized practice" ordinarily will be made by reference to the geographic area where the taxpayer conducts its business.  <P>
		It also is necessary to ascertain the "industry" in which the taxpayer is engaged.  There often are a number of segments that make up a broad industry.  The Service states in its Training Guide that the same standard used in determining the relevant geographical market (i.e., competitors for the same customers) should apply in determining the appropriate industry.  While this position is not illogical, the one court that has addressed this issue has taken a narrower view.  In addition to looking for those who competed for the same customers, the court looked for other parties who operated and were structured similar to the taxpayer in defining the relevant industry.  <P>
		The numerical standard for determining what constitutes a "significant segment" of the industry is far from clear.  An official at the Service has stated that this requirement would probably be satisfied where 80 percent of the businesses in the relevant industry treated their workers as independent contractors, and the Service has argued in one case that a "significant segment of the industry" means more than 50 percent of the members of the industry.  One court has indicated that an amount well below 75 percent could represent a "significant segment of the industry," while another has stated that a "significant segment" is less than a majority of the firms in an industry.  Still another court has stated, in dicta, that 39 percent of the relevant businesses would represent a "significant segment" of the industry.  
		<P>Finally, after a taxpayer has shown that the treatment of workers as independent contractors represents a "recognized practice in a significant segment of the industry," it is still necessary to prove that this practice has been "long-standing."  The Service has stated that there is no fixed time period that represents a "long-standing" industry practice.  The Training Guide indicates that satisfaction of the long-standing practice requirement is most clear where the industry has treated workers as independent contractors since 1978, when Section 530 was enacted, although it recognizes that taxpayers may use the industry practice safe harbor if it began business after 1978.  One court has held that seven years was sufficient to constitute a "long-standing" practice, while another has held that 10 years would qualify.  There is little other precedent or published guidance giving content to this requirement, and one certainly can argue that a shorter time period should be sufficient.
		<P>As with the other safe harbors, the Service requires that the taxpayer must actually have relied on the industry practice in determining to treat its workers as independent contractors.  According to the Training Guide, the taxpayer must show both how and when it knew of the industry practice.  If the taxpayer did not know of the industry practice at the time it began treating its workers as independent contractors, the Service believes that the industry practice safe harbor is not available.  Even if this is so, the fact that a significant number of businesses in the taxpayer's industry treat their workers as independent contractors could provide the taxpayer with an argument that it has an "other reasonable basis" outside the safe harbor for treating its workers as independent contractors. 
		<P>b.	Other Reasonable Basis
		<P>A taxpayer still may satisfy the "reasonable basis" requirement of Section 530 without satisfying any of the three safe harbors.  The legislative history states that Section 530 "grants relief if a taxpayer had any reasonable basis for treating workers as other than employees."  As mentioned above, Congress also has stated that the reasonable basis requirement is to be construed liberally in favor of taxpayers.  The Service has paid lip-service to this mandate.  However, in reality the Service's construction of this term has been anything but liberal.
		<P>The case law authority, while generally following a liberal construction, has failed to develop a consistent analysis or standard for determining whether a taxpayer has an "other reasonable basis" for treating its workers as independent contractors.  Existing authority can be divided into three categories, based upon the burden of proof imposed and the type of evidence that the courts considered.
		<P>The first line of cases analyze whether a taxpayer has a reasonable basis for treating its workers as non-employees by reference to the common law factors, but reduce the taxpayer's burden of proof in making this determination.  Ordinarily, the taxpayer must show by a preponderance of the evidence that its workers are independent contractors in order to avoid liability in an employment tax case.  However, in order to prevail under Section 530, this line of cases holds that the taxpayer need only show that it had a "reasonable basis" for treating its workers as independent contractors and need not show by a preponderance of the evidence that they are in fact independent contractors.
		<P>In determining whether the taxpayer has an "other reasonable basis," this line of cases analyze the same types of evidence that would be considered in an ordinary employment tax case where Section 530 did not apply.  These courts have not inquired into evidence affecting the subjective beliefs of the taxpayer, but merely looked at the facts surrounding the workers' relationships with the taxpayer to determine if it was objectively reasonable to treat such workers as independent contractors.  Only one of these courts specifically held that a taxpayer is precluded from showing a reasonable basis outside the safe harbors by any method other than by reference to the common law factors.  Presumably, the other courts would be willing to consider additional evidence indicating that the taxpayer had some other reasonable basis for classifying its workers as independent contractors.  
		<P>The Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals recently called the validity of this line of cases into question in Boles Trucking, Inc. v. U.S..  In this case, the court held that it was reversible error for the lower court to instruct jurors that the taxpayer "need only show that the existence of a reasonable basis is just as likely true than not."  According to the court, "reasonable basis is what must be proved by the taxpayer -- it is not an expression regarding the level of proof or quantum of evidence."  Taxpayers still have to show by a preponderance of the evidence that they had a reasonable basis for classifying their workers as independent contractors.
		<P>The Eighth Circuit's analysis in Boles Trucking is not necessarily inconsistent with the authorities discussed above.  It is quite conceivable that a taxpayer could review the relevant worker classification authority and come to the reasonable conclusion that its workers are independent contractors although a court applying the preponderance of the evidence standard might hold that the workers are employees.  In other words, the burden of proof in showing that the workers were independent contractors is lowered because the determination is made by reference to a reasonable basis standard.  However, the burden of showing that the taxpayer's belief was objectively reasonable is still a preponderance of the evidence.  The jury instructions in Boles Trucking merely required the taxpayer to show that it more likely than not had a reasonable basis for treating its workers as independent contractors.  The real question should be "can the taxpayer show by a preponderance of the evidence that its belief regarding the classification of its workers was reasonable?".  The authorities that allow a finding of reasonable basis under the common law factors are consistent with this standard.  
		<P>The second line of authority utilizes a more subjective analysis in determining whether the taxpayer had an "other reasonable basis."  Under these cases, the taxpayer need not show that it has a reasonable basis under the traditional common law factors.  Instead, the taxpayer need only show that it took reasonable steps to determine the proper classification of its workers.  Here, courts are more willing to hear evidence that could affect the taxpayer's beliefs, not just evidence relating to the actual relationships with the workers.  Some cases have indicated that taxpayers may rely on the advice of attorneys and accountants in treating their workers as independent contractors.  Determinations by state agencies also may constitute a reasonable basis for treating workers as independent contractors for federal income taxes, although not all courts agree on this point.  
		<P>While this line of cases considers third party advice in determining whether the taxpayer had an "other reasonable basis," the taxpayer must show not just that it believed the advice rendered, but also that it was reasonable to rely on such advice.  Based upon statements contained in the Training Guide, the Service appears to agree with this analysis.  Under this line of reasoning, taxpayers should be prepared to show that they disclosed all relevant information to their counsel or the applicable agency and, in the case of counsel, that such party was knowledgeable with respect to employment tax matters.  
		<P>In addition to relying on advice of counsel and state agency determinations, one court has implied that a taxpayer may rely on the audit of another taxpayer involved in the same industry.  Also, while taxpayers may not rely on private letter rulings issued to third parties, they may use such rulings to show that the Service had repeatedly taken the position that similarly situated workers are non-employees.  Although these rulings may not prove that it was reasonable under the common law factors to treat workers as independent contractors, the fact that the Service consistently took this position in the form of private letter rulings and that the taxpayer was aware of the Service's position may be sufficient to show that it was reasonable for the taxpayer to believe that its workers were not employees, thus giving it an "other reasonable basis" for purposes of Section 530.
		<P>Finally, some courts not only consider evidence extraneous to the work relationship, but also lower the taxpayer's burden further, requiring only that the taxpayer exercise "good faith" in determining that its workers are independent contractors.  Under this line of analysis, the reasonableness of the taxpayer's actions will be measured in light of the taxpayer's own knowledge and experience.  Presumably, the inquiry required of an unsophisticated sole proprietor would be lower than the inquiry required by a large corporation that has greater awareness with respect to such matters.  
		<P>Numerous courts have paid lip-service to the "good faith" standard, but few courts have applied the standard in a way that would allow the taxpayer to blindly rely on the advice of others.  However, one case does seem to have gone this far.  In Queensgate Dental Family Practice, Inc. v. U.S., the taxpayer's sole inquiry was to the Pennsylvania Dental Board, which informed the taxpayer that it was illegal under state law for a non-licensed business corporation to enter into an employer/employee relationship with a licensed dentist.  Although the taxpayer provided the agency with no information regarding the details surrounding its relationship with the workers, the court held that Section 530 relief was appropriate based upon the taxpayer's "good faith inquiry" into the treatment of its members.
		<P>It appears that a taxpayer will proceed at some peril where it attempts to rely solely on a good faith determination that its workers are non-employees.  While the legislative history provides for a liberal construction of the reasonable basis standard, there is no clear justification for lowering the burden of proof so far as to require only a good faith inquiry.  However, it also seems inappropriate to limit taxpayers to a common law analysis in showing an "other reasonable basis."  First, the legislative history indicates that a taxpayer should be granted relief where it had any reasonable basis for treating its workers as other than employees.  Second, two of the three safe harbors (i.e., prior audit and industry practice) do not involve a common law analysis but relate to other facts that would cause a taxpayer to believe that its workers should be classified as independent contractors.  Accordingly, a taxpayer should be considered to have a reasonable basis for treating its workers as non-employees where a reasonable taxpayer would believe that its workers are independent contractors, whether determined under a common law analysis or otherwise.<P>
		<STRONG>4.	Application of Section 530 With Respect to Code §3401(d) "Payor Employers" and Other Third Parties<P>
</STRONG>
		While the application of Section 530 is fairly straightforward with respect to traditional employers, many complexities arise where this section is invoked on behalf of Code §3401(d) "payor employers" or other parties who are potentially liable for the penalties imposed under Code §3505 or 6672.  There is very little authority addressing these issues, so one generally is left to argue for the logical result.  <P>
			a.	Section 530 and Code §3401(d) "Payor Employers"
<P>
		The Service has ruled privately that Section 530 can apply with respect to Code §3401(d) "payor employers."  However, some field agents apparently have taken the position that such an employer cannot invoke Section 530.  The rationale is as follows:  Revenue Procedure 85-18 provides that Section 530 relief applies to taxes imposed under Code §§3101, 3102, 3111, 3301, 3402, and 3403.  Because the revenue procedure does not mention Code §3401, those parties who are subject to tax as "payors" under Code §3401(d) are not entitled to Section 530 relief.
	<P>	The position taken by these field agents is unjustified.  Revenue Procedure 85-18 refers only to those statutory provisions that impose an employment tax or withholding obligation on the taxpayer.  Code §3401(d) does not impose a tax; it merely determines who is an employer and thus who is subject to the tax and withholding obligations that are imposed under the provisions set forth in Revenue Procedure 85-18.  Accordingly, despite the contention of these misguided field agents, Code §3401(d) "payor employers" should be eligible for relief under Section 530 where they can meet the requirements of the statute.
		<P>It is unclear how the reasonable basis requirement of Section 530 should be applied with respect to "payor employers."  Presumably, the taxpayer must show that it had a reasonable basis for not treating the workers as its common law employees.  This should not be difficult since, if the Service is attempting to impose liability under the "payor" portion of Code §3401(d), the taxpayer obviously did not exercise extensive controls over the workers.  However, the inquiry probably does not end there.  It is likely that the taxpayer also must show that it had a reasonable basis for not treating the workers as its deemed employees under Code §3401(d).  
		<P>If the taxpayer has undergone a prior audit where it was not determined that the workers were employees or if it is the practice of third party payors in the taxpayer's industry to treat similarly situated workers as independent contractors, the taxpayer should satisfy the reasonable basis requirement regardless of how the relationship is analyzed.  In addition, the taxpayer should satisfy this requirement where it had a reasonable basis for concluding that it did not "control" the payment of wages to the employees.  However, if none of these arguments are available to the taxpayer, there presumably must be some analysis of the relationship between the service recipient and the deemed employee to determine if the "payor employer" satisfies the reasonable basis requirement.  
		<P>If there is judicial precedent or published rulings that would justify the service recipient in treating the workers as independent contractors were it the payor of such workers, that certainly should be enough to protect the Code §3401(d) "payor employer."  Advice that the workers are not employees of the taxpayer from a professional who is experienced in employment tax matters and is fully apprised of the facts surrounding the relationship also should be sufficient to show an "other reasonable basis."  But what happens if the taxpayer understood the underlying facts of the relationship between the workers and service recipient to be such that they would indicate that the workers were independent contractors when, actually, the facts were different and more indicative of an employment relationship?  Should the analysis be with respect to the facts as they actually existed or with respect to the taxpayer's perception of the facts?  Given the Congressional mandate that Section 530's reasonable basis requirement should be liberally construed, it seems that as long as the taxpayer was reasonable in its belief of the facts underlying the relationship, it should be the taxpayer's perception of the facts that control in determining whether the taxpayer had a reasonable basis for concluding that the workers were not its employees.
			<P>b.	Section 530 Relief Where Liability is Imposed Under Code §3505 or 6672
<P>
		Where a taxpayer can satisfy the requirements of Section 530, it is entitled to relief from liability for employment taxes.  Because neither Code §3505 or 6672 impose an employment tax, but instead impose liability in the form of a penalty equal to the employment taxes owed, the question arises as to whether a taxpayer who is subject to liability under either of these provisions can claim relief under Section 530.  
	<P>	Revenue Procedure 85-18 apparently answers this question affirmatively.  The revenue procedure provides that <P>
If a taxpayer is relieved from liability under section 530(a)(1) of the Act, liability for interest or penalties attributable to that liability is forgiven automatically.  The relief from interest and penalties applies whether charged directly against the taxpayer or personally against a corporate taxpayer's officers.
<P>
The language highlighted at the end of this quote clearly is made with reference to the 100 percent penalty imposed under Code §6672.  There is no valid basis for distinguishing the penalty imposed under Code §6672 from the one levied under Code §3505, given that both derive from the employment tax liability of the underlying employer.  Thus, parties who may be subject to liability under Code §3505 should be entitled to relief under Section 530 as well.<P>
		Based upon the language in Revenue Procedure 85-18, it appears that relief from liability under Code §§3505 and 6672 is derivative from qualification of the underlying employer for Section 530 relief.	 Accordingly, the various inquiries to be applied in determining qualification under Section 530 will be made by reference to the underlying employer and not the party from whom the Service is trying to collect.  This is logical:  Because the parties against whom liability is being imposed are not actually "employers," the questions of whether they treated the workers as non-employees or had a reasonable basis for doing so are not really appropriate.  However, the fact that the taxpayer's fate under Section 530 lies in the hands of another party (i.e., the underlying employer) can cause some significant problems.  Namely, the taxpayer, particularly one who is potentially subject to liability under Code §3505, may not have access to records and other information with respect to the underlying employer which are necessary to show that relief under Section 530 is available.  For instance, without the cooperation of the underlying employer, how can the taxpayer show that the employer filed all applicable returns with respect to the workers, that the workers were always treated as independent contractors, or that the employer was previously subject to an audit where the workers were not determined to be employees?  It is these logistical questions, rather than legal questions, that often will cause the greatest anguish in trying to gain Section 530 relief for parties who otherwise will be subject to liability under Code §3505 or 6672.  
		<P>A recent case, Crowd Management Services, Inc. v. U.S., indicates that a responsible person need not go so far as satisfying Section 530 to avoid liability under Code §6672.  In that case, the corporation failed to satisfy Section 530 because it previously had treated similarly situated workers as employees.  Nonetheless, the court found that because the responsible person had a "reasonable basis" for believing that the workers were independent contractors and that no withholding was required, the Service could not show that he "willfully" failed to withhold taxes.  Accordingly, Code §6672 did not apply.  <P>
		<P><STRONG>5.	Whipsawing the Government Under Section 530</STRONG><P>
		As discussed above, Section 530 relief should be available on both a retroactive and prospective basis.  Therefore, even if the agent determines that the workers are employees, where Section 530 applies, the taxpayer will not be liable for past employment taxes and will not be required to pay employment taxes with respect to the workers on a going-forward basis.  In addition, because Section 530 does not recharacterize the workers as independent contractors, where the workers have considered themselves to be independent contractors and have paid the self-employment tax attributable to their wages, they will be entitled to a refund of the amount of self-employment tax paid.  The refund will be reduced by the worker's share of FICA tax imposed under Code §3101, but even after this offset, the worker will receive back approximately half of the self-employment tax paid.  In addition, since the worker will be classified as an employee on a going forward basis, in the future it will be required to pay only its share of the FICA tax and will no longer be subject to the self-employment tax.  Accordingly, it often will be to the government's advantage to find that the taxpayer's workers are not employees where the taxpayer otherwise would be entitled to relief under Section 530.  <P>
		This point is strategic and could convince an I.R.S. agent to determine that workers are actually independent contractors rather than finding that they are employees.  This could be important if the taxpayer is concerned that the scope of the audit could expand to consider the qualification of its retirement plans or other issues on which an employment determination could have an impact.  This also could be important if Section 530 is eventually amended and the taxpayer's prospective protection is terminated (which is a very real possibility).<P>
	<STRONG>B.	Partial Relief from FICA and Income Tax Withholding Under Code §3509
</STRONG><P>
		<STRONG>1.	In General</STRONG>
<P>
		Code §3509 provides some relief where an employer fails to deduct and withhold income tax and the employee's share of FICA tax with respect to any employee "by reason of treating such an employee as not being an employee."  Code §3509 provides for two levels of relief.  The degree of relief that a taxpayer is entitled to under Code §3509 essentially is dependent on whether the taxpayer has satisfied certain filing requirements or has shown that its failure to satisfy these requirements was reasonable.  
	<P>	Code §3509 does not provide for relief with respect to FUTA taxes imposed under Code §3301 or the employer's share of FICA taxes imposed under Code §3111.  It applies only to "trust fund" or withholding taxes.  Where the taxpayer can show that it did not intentionally disregard the requirement to deduct and withhold tax from the employee's wages and that it met the reporting requirements applicable under Code §§6041(a), 6041A, and 6051, the employer's liability for income tax withholding will be limited to 1.5 percent of the wages paid to such employee, and the employer's liability for the employee's share of FICA taxes will equal 20 percent of the amount that otherwise would be imposed without the application of Code §3509.  The reporting requirements are determined as if the taxpayer had treated the worker as not being an employee and generally will be satisfied where the employer has timely filed Form 1099 with respect to the worker and has timely filed Form 1096 including the worker for the applicable period.  Where the worker misclassification was not due to intentional disregard, but the taxpayer failed to satisfy the reporting requirements and such failure was not due to reasonable cause, the taxpayer's liability will double so that it becomes liable for income tax withholding in an amount equal to three percent of wages paid and 40 percent of the employee's share of FICA taxes that otherwise would have been due.  Code §3509 will not apply where the taxpayer's liability for employment taxes is due to intentional disregard of the requirement to deduct and withhold such taxes.  
		<P>The benefits afforded by Code §3509 are not available in certain circumstances even where the taxpayer's failure to pay employment taxes was not due to intentional disregard of the applicable rules.  Code §3509 will not apply with respect to any wages where the taxpayer deducted and withheld income tax from such wages but failed to deduct and withhold the employee's share of FICA taxes.  A taxpayer also will not be eligible for protection under Code §3509 with respect to wages paid to statutory employees described in Code §3121(d)(3).  For purposes of this determination, if an individual would be treated as an employee under Code §3121(d)(3) but for the fact that he or she is an employee under Code §3121(d)(1) or (2), the individual will be treated as an employee under Code §3121(d)(3) so that Code §3509 will not apply.
		<P>A taxpayer will not be excused from the payment of penalties, additions to tax, or additional amounts otherwise applicable when Code §3509 applies.  However, the amount of such penalties or other additions will be calculated as if the amount of tax determined under Code §3509 were the amount that the taxpayer was required to deduct, withhold, and pay over.
		<P>Where Code §3509 applies, a taxpayer is not entitled to recover from the employee for taxes ultimately collected from the taxpayer.  While income tax and FICA withholding reported and paid over by the taxpayer with respect to the applicable employees will be credited against the employer's liability under Code §3509, the taxpayer cannot take advantage of Code §§3402 and 6521 to credit taxes paid by the employee against its Code §3509 liability.   In addition, the Service takes the position that Code §3509 is mandatory and a taxpayer cannot voluntarily elect out of its application even where crediting employee-paid taxes under Code §§3402 and 6521 would produce a better result.  This can make Code §3509 disadvantageous to taxpayers employing compliant workers who paid their taxes.  However, because the information taxpayers must collect in order to take advantage of Code §§3402 and 6521 often will not be available, Code §3509 generally will provide a better result.  
		<P><STRONG>2.	Code §3509 Relief Where Liability is Imposed Under Code §3505 or 6672</STRONG><P>

		Because Code §3509 only applies to reduce an "employer's liability" with respect to "taxes" imposed under chapter24 (income tax withholding) and subchapterA of chapter21 (employee FICA withholding) of the Code, there is some question as to whether relief should be available to parties who incur liability under Code §3505 or 6672.  Payors under Code §§3505 and 6672 are not treated as "employers" but are merely liable as third parties.  Accordingly, reducing the liability of such payors does not reduce the "employer's liability" for taxes.  Likewise, under both sections, the payor is not considered to actually pay the "taxes" referred to in Code §3509; instead, in the case of §3505, the party pays a penalty equal to the "taxes ... required to be deducted and withheld" and, in the case of Code §6672, a penalty equal to the "tax evaded, or not collected, or not accounted for and paid over."  
		<P>In spite of these technical problems, one can argue that because the liability imposed under Code §§3505 and 6672 derives from the income tax withholding and employee FICA withholding obligations imposed on the employer, these parties should be entitled to take advantage of Code §3509 where the underlying taxpayer qualifies for such relief.  The Service has already accepted this reasoning with respect to parties that are subject to liability under Code §6672 in the context of Section 530 even though this section only provides for relief from liability for "employment taxes."  There does not seem to be any rational basis for applying a different analysis in the context of Code §3509.  
		<P>As is the case with third parties seeking relief under Section 530, there may be practical barriers to such parties qualifying for relief under Code §3509.  First, it may be difficult to prove that the taxpayer did not intentionally disregard the requirement to deduct and withhold the tax.  Second, a third party also will have difficulty showing that the employer fulfilled the applicable reporting requirements.  Code §6672 responsible parties often were officers of the employer and thus may have access to this information.  However, Code §3505 lenders, sureties, and other persons generally are unrelated to the employer.  Accordingly, in many instances, these parties will be unable to gain access to information necessary to prove that these requirements have been fulfilled.  
	<P><STRONG>C.	Credit for Employee-Paid Taxes</STRONG><P>
		Code §3402(d) provides that where an employer fails to deduct and withhold income tax, but such tax is subsequently paid by the worker or some other party, the tax shall not be collected from the employer.  In order to claim such relief, the employer must show that the underlying tax, in fact, has been paid.  While this section relieves employers from liability for the underlying tax, it does not relieve employers for any penalties or other additions attributable to such tax.  <P>
		Code §6521 provides somewhat comparable relief with respect to FICA and self-employment taxes.  Under Code §6521(a), employer's liability for failure to deduct and withhold the employee's share of FICA taxes will be reduced by the amount of self-employment tax paid by the employee where certain conditions are satisfied.  Specifically, an amount must have been erroneously treated as self-employment income, the correction must require an assessment against the employer and a refund of self-employment tax to the employee, and the correction of the error must be allowed as to the employer's liability for FICA tax but prevented as to the employee's refund of self-employment tax by any rule of law.  This provision generally will apply only when the statute of limitations remains open with respect to the employer but is closed with respect to the employee, thus preventing the employee from filing a claim for refund.  <P>
		<P>Like Code §3509, these provisions do not affect the employer's liability for its share of FICA or FUTA taxes.  In addition, as stated above, where Code §3509 applies, the employer may not take advantage of the relief provided under Code §3402(d) or 6521.  
<H4>VI.	Penalties and Interest
</H4>		The Service may assess interest and a variety of penalties in connection with employment tax deficiencies.  However, as is the case with the deficiencies themselves, a number of relief provisions are available that can limit or even eliminate a taxpayer's liability with respect to such amounts.  
<P><STRONG>A.	Penalty for Failure to Deposit Taxes
</STRONG>		<P>An employer is required to deposit with the Government depositary the employee's share of FICA tax, the employer's share of FICA tax, and income taxes withheld from an employee's wages.  Code §6656 provides that where a person fails to deposit such taxes by the prescribed date, a penalty equal to the applicable percentage of the amount of the underpayment shall be imposed.  The applicable percentage equals two percent where the failure is not for more than five days, five percent where the failure is for more than five days but not more than 15 days, and ten percent if the failure is for more than 15 days.  <P>
		The penalty for failure to deposit taxes will not apply where the taxpayer can show that "such failure is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect."  Likewise, where the taxpayer treats its workers as independent contractors rather than employees and thus fails to withhold income tax and the employee's share of FICA taxes, the penalty under Code §6656 will apply only with respect to the employer's share of FICA taxes and not with respect to the other taxes which the taxpayer failed to pay over because it did not actually withhold such taxes.  <P>
<STRONG>B.	Penalty for Failure to File Appropriate Returns
</STRONG><P>		An employer is required to file Forms 940 (FUTA) and 941 (social security and income tax withholding) quarterly with respect to wages paid during such quarter.  Where such forms are not filed, Code §6651(a)(1) imposes a penalty equal to five percent of the amount of tax required to be shown on the return, provided that the form is not more than one month overdue.  For each additional month, the penalty increases by an additional five percent up to a maximum of 25 percent.  The penalty is greater where fraud is involved.  <P>
		If the failure to file Forms 940 and 941 is due to reasonable cause and not due to willful neglect, no penalty will be imposed.  In addition, many taxpayers will have filed Forms 940 and 941 with respect to workers that it properly classified as employees.  The mere fact that additional workers reclassified as employees were not included on the return should not cause the penalty to apply.  This failure to file penalty is not invoked by the mere underreporting of tax due.  
<P><STRONG>C.	Interest
</STRONG><P>		Under the general rule, interest will accrue with respect to employment tax deficiencies at the statutory underpayment rate from the last date prescribed for the payment of such tax.  However, if the taxpayer can negotiate an acceptable settlement for the amount of tax due, payment of interest can be avoided.  Where a taxpayer pays the proposed deficiency prior to receipt from the Service of a notice and demand for payment, there will be no assessment of interest.  Even if the potential interest is significant but a settlement cannot be achieved, it may be worth paying the full amount of the proposed deficiency prior to receipt of such a notice and demand and then suing for a refund.
	<P>	There are certain situations where the Service will not allow an interest free adjustment even though the tax is paid before receipt of a notice and demand for payment.  Specifically, such an adjustment will be denied where the taxpayer's returns were audited for prior years and additional tax was found to be due with respect to the same issue involved in the current audit.  Also, where a taxpayer has been informed by the Service of its status as an employer and knowingly underreports its employment tax liability in subsequent years, the interest free adjustment will not be allowed.
<P>
<H4>VII.	Statute of Limitations
</H4>		One last legal issue that must be considered in handling an employment tax audit is the statute of limitations.  In general, employment taxes must be assessed within three years after the taxpayer filed its return for the applicable period.  Where a return covering FICA tax and income tax withholding (i.e., Form 941) for any period ending with or within a calendar year is filed before April15 of the succeeding calendar year, the return will be deemed filed on April15 of such succeeding calendar year.  
		<P>One court has held that the filing of a Form 1099 for a worker will not start the statute of limitations for taxes due with respect to that worker where it is determined that the worker should have been classified as an employee.  The court based its holding on the conclusion that the Form 1099 would not allow an IRS agent to determine the amount of tax due since it did not indicate that the worker/recipient was an employee.  From a policy perspective, this holding is questionable since it effectively eliminates the statute of limitations for employment taxes where a company uses only independent contractors in its operations.  In reality, however, few companies have zero employees.  Assuming that a company files Forms 940 and 941 with respect to the workers it classifies as employees, the statute of limitations should be triggered for all employment taxes attributable to the period covered by the returns, regardless of whether the workers subject to reclassification were included in the returns.
<P>
<H4>VIII.	The Service's New Settlement Programs</H4>
		At the 1995 White House Conference on Small Business and at a number of town meetings with small business owners sponsored by the Service, the participants identified worker classification as one of their primary concerns.  In an effort to ease the taxpayers' burden in resolving employment tax audits, the Service has developed two test programs.  These programs are discussed below.
	<P><STRONG>A.	The Classification Settlement Program</STRONG><P>
		The Classification Settlement Program ("CSP") establishes an optional settlement program that is designed to allow resolution of worker classification cases as early in the administrative process as possible and to ensure that Section 530 is properly and consistently applied.  The CSP will allow examining agents to offer businesses a worker classification settlement using a standard closing agreement.<P>
		Under the CSP, the examiner must develop the various issues relevant to the audit, which will include gathering facts to determine whether improper classification has occurred, whether Section 530 is available, and whether the taxpayer is eligible for a CSP offer.  The agent then must consult with the examination group manager, who will confirm or deny the taxpayer's eligibility for a CSP settlement off.  If the offer is made and the taxpayer chooses to accept it, the parties will sign a CSP closing agreement based on a standard closing agreement provided by the National Office.<P>
		Taxpayers may qualify for a series of graduated settlement offers under the CSP depending upon the facts of their case.  If the taxpayer has filed the appropriate returns with respect to the workers as required by Section 530 ("reporting consistency"), but either has not treated similarly situated workers as independent contractors ("substantive consistency") or clearly cannot satisfy the reasonable basis requirement under Section 530, the offer will be a full employment tax assessment for one taxable year computed using Code §3509, if applicable.  If the taxpayer satisfies the reporting consistency requirement and has a colorable argument that it meets the substantive consistency requirement and the reasonable basis test, the offer will be an assessment of 25 percent of the withholding and FICA tax liability for the audit year, again computed using Code §3509, if applicable, along with 100 percent of the FUTA tax liability.  In accepting either settlement, the taxpayer must agree to reclassify its workers prospectively.<P>
		If a taxpayer clearly meets the reporting and substantive consistency requirements and satisfies the reasonable test under Section 530, all of the requirements of Section 530 will be met.  Under this scenario, no assessment will be made and the taxpayer may continue treating its workers as independent contractors.  However, if the taxpayer wishes to begin treating its workers as employees, the taxpayer will not give up its claim to Section 530 relief for prior years.<P>
		If a taxpayer fails to satisfy the reporting consistency requirement, it will not be eligible to participate in the CSP.  A taxpayer may qualify for more than one CSP offer if multiple classes of workers are at issue.  <P>
		Participation in the CSP is entirely voluntary, and a taxpayer may accept a CSP settlement offer at any time during the examination process.  In declining such a CSP offer, the taxpayer will not waive any of its rights to a conventional administrative appeal with the Service or any of its rights to judicial review.<P>
		The CSP is being implemented on a two-year basis, beginning on March 5, 1996, and the future of the program beyond the two-year period will depend on its success during that time.  The CSP will be available to any taxpayer with an open case in either IRS Examination or Appeals on March 5, 1996 or who has a case initiated during the two-year period thereafter.  <P>
	<STRONG>B.	Early Referral to Appeals
	</STRONG><P>	In Revenue Procedure 96-9, the Service set forth a process through which a taxpayer could request referral to Appeals of any developed, unagreed issue (subject to certain exceptions) that is under the jurisdiction of the District Director arising from an examination.  The Revenue Procedure was developed in an effort to resolve cases more expeditiously by having Examination and Appeals work simultaneously.  The Service has now published an announcement applying the provisions of the Revenue Procedure 96-9 to employment tax issues on a one-year test basis.
		<P>According to the announcement, issues considered appropriate for early referral include those that if resolved can reasonably be expected to result in quicker resolution of the entire case and that both the taxpayer and the District Director agree should be referred to Appeals early.  Examples of employment tax issues considered appropriate for early referral include worker classification issues such as whether a worker is a common law or statutory employee or a statutory non-employee, whether Section530 or Code §3509 applies, and whether the taxpayer qualifies for an interest-free adjustment under Code §6205, as well as other issues such as whether certain payments are excepted from the definition of "wages" and whether certain services are excepted from the definition of "employment."  
		<P>A taxpayer may request early referral by submitting such a request in writing to the case manager.  The announcement states that a "case manager" includes Compliance, Examination, Collection, and EP/EO group managers.
		<P>Once the issue is approved for transfer to Appeals, the procedure is similar to the procedure that follows when a proposed notice of deficiency is issued (i.e., a "thirty-day letter").  The District Director will prepare and send to the taxpayer an employment tax report for each approved early referral issue which identifies the amount of employment taxes in dispute, describes the issues, and describes the District Director's position.  The taxpayer must then respond in writing to the Director's report in a manner similar to that which would be provided in an Appeals protest.  The taxpayer's response must be submitted to the case manager within 30 days of the date of the District Director's report, but the 30-day requirement may be extended with the case manager's consent.  After the taxpayer has filed its response, the early referral file is sent to Appeals and the issues are handled essentially according to Appeals' normal operating procedures.  If an agreement is not reached at Appeals with respect to an issue, Appeals will close the early referral file and return jurisdiction to Examination.  Appeals will not reconsider an early referral issue if the entire case is later referred to Appeals, unless the circumstances relating to the early referral issue have changed substantially.  
<P>
<H4>IX.	Conclusion
</H4>		Conducting an employment tax audit traditionally has been a very frustrating and difficult task, but given the Service's apparent new-found attitude in the context of worker classification issues, there is hope that undertaking such an audit may become a more manageable endeavor.  Only time will tell whether the Service's programs will have a significant effect on the examining agents in the field.   
<P>		Even anticipating the Service's more lenient approach, the factual and legal issues involved in an employment tax audit are numerous and complex so representing a taxpayer will continue to require substantial knowledge and preparation.  This article has attempted to set forth a guide to the various issues that can arise in an employment tax audit and the manner in which such issues should be resolved.  By anticipating the arguments that the government will present and realizing the weapons that are available to combat such arguments, the chances of obtaining a favorable result should be greatly increased.
<center><HR><p>
