<HEAD>
<TITLE>THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS ACT OF 1996: MAKING THE TRANSITION TO A MORE
COMPETITIVE TELEPHONE INDUSTRY </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS ACT OF 1996: Making the Transition to
a More Competitive Telephone Industry</H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="http:/htm/coen.htm">Timothy F. Coen</A></H2>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the November 1996 issue
of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by
permission.</H6>
<HR>
<P>The passage of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 (the &quot;Act&quot;)
radically alters the rules governing the U.S. telephone industry.  As described
recently by the Federal Communications Commission (&quot;FCC&quot;), two of the
principal goals established by the telephony provisions of the Act are:  (1)
opening the local exchange and exchange access markets to competitive entry, and
(2) promoting increased competition in telecommunications markets that are
already open to competition, including the long distance services market.</P>
<H3>OPENING LOCAL TELEPHONE MARKETS TO COMPETITION</H3>
<P>The principal method employed by the Act to accomplish the goal of
increasing local competition is the wholesale elimination of artificial legal
and regulatory barriers to entry as a matter of preemptive federal law.  In
particular, under Section 253 of the Act, Congress eliminates nearly a century
of local telephone monopolies by sweepingly prohibiting &quot;all state or local
statutes, regulations or other legal requirements that may prohibit or have the
effect of prohibiting the ability of any entity to provide any interstate or
intrastate telecommunications service.&quot;  The states retain authority to
impose competitively-neutral rules to ensure universal and quality local service
within their jurisdictions, but the FCC is given ultimate authority to preempt
state or local rules to the extent they are inconsistent with the terms of
Section 253 of the Act.</P>
<P>In order to successfully make the transition to a more competitive
telecommunications marketplace, however, Congress had to do more than tear down
existing statutory and regulatory entry barriers.  It also had to address
defacto entry barriers created by the existence of historical monopolies and it
had to create a new industry structure for the provision of competitive local
telephone service.  Congress addressed these issues by imposing specific legal
duties on new and incumbent providers and by conditioning incumbent providers'
access to new markets on the opening of their existing markets to competition.
</P>
<P>Under Section 251 of the Act, for example, Congress imposes on all
telecommunications carriers a new legal duty to interconnect with each others'
networks.  This overarching legal duty is intended to replace the previous
monopoly driven industry structure and to create a new duty of common carriage
among carriers, rather than just to end-users, which did not exist prior to the
Act.  </P>
<P>To address technical and operational barriers, the Act also places new legal
duties on all local telephone companies (a &quot;LEC&quot;), whether incumbent
providers or new entrants.  LECs are required to permit others to resell their
services and to provide certain other network features, such as number
portability (the ability of customers to retain, at the same location, their
existing phone number if they change carriers) and dialing parity (the ability
of customers to automatically route their calls to their presubscribed local or
long distance provider without having to dial an access code).  LECs must also
grant competing providers access to their rights of way and must enter into
reciprocal compensation arrangements with other carriers for the transport and
termination of telecommunications traffic. </P>
<P>Lastly, Congress placed a third set of specific additional duties solely on
companies providing local phone service as of the date the Act passed (known as
&quot;incumbent local exchange companies&quot; or &quot;ILECs&quot;).  The Act
requires ILECs to negotiate in good faith the terms of their interconnection
agreements and to provide interconnection to competing providers on just,
reasonable and nondiscriminatory terms at &quot;any technically feasible point&quot;
in their network.  The quality of interconnection provided must be equal to that
which the ILEC provides itself and its affiliates.  In addition, ILECs must (1)
unbundle their networks so that other competing carriers can buy on a &quot;cost-plus&quot;
basis only those facilities they need to provide service to their customers, and
(2) offer their retail telecommunications services to competing service
providers at &quot;wholesale rates&quot; for resale.</P>
<H3>INCREASING COMPETITION IN THE LONG DISTANCE MARKET</H3>
<P>The Act also seeks to enhance competition in the already competitive long
distance industry by authorizing the entry of the Regional Bell Operating
Companies (&quot;RBOCs&quot;) into a market from which they have been prohibited
since the breakup of the Bell System in 1983.</P>
<P>The Act permits the RBOCs to engage in &quot;incidental&quot; long distance
service and in long distance service for calls originating outside their local
service territories immediately.  However, the Act conditions the RBOCs
provision of so-called &quot;in region long distance service&quot; (i.e.  long
distance service for calls originating in their local service territory where
they currently have a strong customer base) on the opening of their local
telephone markets to competition.  Thus, under Section 271 of the Act, an RBOC
will be allowed to provide in-region long distance service only when it faces
facilities-based competition (as opposed to resale competition) in its local
telephone market in a particular state, and has otherwise met a 14 point &quot;competitive
checklist&quot; set out in the Act.  Once an RBOC has met these conditions, it
must then apply to the FCC on a state by state basis for a finding that the
RBOC's entry into the in-region long distance business in that state meets the
statutory test and is in the public interest.</P>
<H3>NEW OPPORTUNITIES AND NEW CHALLENGES</H3>
<P>Under the Act, increased competition is intended to supplant regulation in
all segments of the telephony marketplace.  Congress has outlined a new industry
structure and has supplied a roadmap for the development of competitive entry
into the local and long distance telephone markets.  Proponents of the Act
expect competition to create new economic opportunities and to bring new
packages of services, lower prices and increased innovation to residential and
business consumers.  Certainly, the transition to a more competitive telephone
industry will present tremendous opportunities and tremendous challenges to the
U.S. telephony industry.  </P>
<P>Businesses in particular will have access to new markets and to a dizzying
array of new services and service providers.  Rather than relying on regulators
and &quot;one size fits all&quot; tariffs to determine what services will be
available and at what cost, businesses will have the opportunity to obtain
customized service packages and, in some cases, to negotiate their own deals
with their telecommunications provider.  Additional cost savings and better
service will be available to large users by aggregating their local and long
distance traffic to obtain greater volume discounts and requiring end to end
service guarantees from their service provider.  These new opportunities will
challenge business users and their advisors to understand the marketplace, the
communications needs of their business and their service provider's capabilities
better than they have ever had to in the past.</P>
<P>Perhaps the ultimate challenge of the new industry structure created by
Congress in the Act will be to maintain the quality, affordability and universal
access of the previous system and to make it better by lowering cost and
increasing innovation through the introduction of efficient competition into the
marketplace.  </P>
<HR>
