<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Regulation of Internet Content and Communications</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">Regulation of Internet Content and Communications</H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">Bradley A. Slutsky</H2>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the November 1996 issue
of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by
permission.</H6>
<HR>
<P>The number of users connected to the Internet doubles approximately every
year.  By one estimate as many as 40 million users currently are connected to
the Internet.  As Internet use has expanded, state and federal governments have
taken notice and have attempted to regulate this new medium.  Recent decisions
reviewing the constitutionality of the Communications Decency Act of 1996, 47
U.S.C. &#167; 223(a)-(h) (the &quot;CDA&quot;), indicate that regulations in
this area may be difficult to enforce.</P>
<P>The CDA was signed into law as part of the Telecommunications Act of 1996
and was designed to limit the exposure of children to sexually explicit
materials available &quot;on-line.&quot;  The day the CDA became law, two
separate lawsuits were filed to test its constitutionality.  Both cases held
that because the CDA restricts speech based on content, its constitutionality is
judged under a &quot;strict scrutiny&quot; standard: it &quot;will only be
upheld if it is justified by a compelling government interest and if it is
narrowly tailored to effectuate that interest.&quot;  <I>American Civil
Liberties Union v. Reno</I>, 929 F. Supp. 824, 851 (E.D. Pa. 1996).  See also
<I>Shea v. Reno</I>, 930 F. Supp. 916, 939 (S.D.N.Y. 1996).</P>
<P>In analyzing whether the CDA met the strict scrutiny test, the reviewing
courts first heard extensive testimony and argument regarding the nature of the
Internet and the state of its technology.  This was necessary because &quot;differential
treatment of the mass media has become established First Amendment doctrine. ...
 This medium-specific approach to mass communication examines the underlying
technology of the communication to find the proper fit between First Amendment
values and competing interests.&quot;  <I>ACLU v. Reno, </I>929 F. Supp. at
873.</P>
<P>With respect to the nature of the Internet, the court in <I>ACLU v. Reno</I>
found that &quot;[i]t is no exaggeration to conclude that the content on the
Internet is as diverse as human thought. ...  Such diversity of content on the
Internet is possible because the Internet provides an easy and inexpensive way
for a speaker to reach a large audience, potentially of millions. ...  The
Internet is therefore a unique and wholly new medium of communication.&quot; 
Id. at 842, 843, 844.  See also <I>Shea v. Reno</I>, 930 F. Supp. at 929-30.</P>
<P>In assessing whether, given the current state of Internet technology, the
CDA is sufficiently &quot;narrowly tailored,&quot; the courts concluded that &quot;content
providers using most forms of Internet communication have no way of transmitting
indecent content with certainty that it will not reach a minor.&quot;   Id. at
941.  See also <I>ACLU v. Reno</I>, 929 F. Supp. at 845.  The courts found that
the inability of the technology to limit minors' access to allegedly indecent
material impermissibly chilled otherwise protected speech, and rendered the CDA
overbroad--&quot;[b]ecause adults would lack means of engaging in
constitutionally protected indecent communications over the Internet without
fear of criminal liability, the statute would unquestionably be
unconstitutional.&quot;  <I>Shea v. Reno</I>, 930 F. Supp. at 942.  See also
<I>ACLU v. Reno</I>, 929 F. Supp. at 854.</P>
<P>The trend toward regulation of Internet content and communications may
therefore be in for a rough road.  &quot;As the most participatory form of mass
speech yet developed, the Internet deserves the highest protection from
governmental intrusion.&quot;  <I>ACLU v. Reno</I>, 929 F. Supp. at 883. 
Because the current state of technology makes it difficult if not impossible for
many content providers to selectively deliver content over the Internet to
identifiable users, Internet regulations will be suspect unless access
limitations imposed on content providers are feasible given the state of
technology at the time the regulations are enacted.  As Internet technology
advances, however, the government's ability to regulate communications over the
Internet may concomitantly increase.</P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG
