<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS DEVELOPMENT FUND: A New Source of Funding for
Small Businesses</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">THE TELECOMMUNICATIONS DEVELOPMENT FUND: A New Source of
Funding for Small Businesses</H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">Lisa Williams Greene</H2>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the November 1996 issue
of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by
permission.</H6>
<HR>
<P>For many small businesses, the main barrier to competition and growth in the
telecommunications industry is lack of access to capital. In one of the
provisions of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 (the &quot;Act&quot;), Congress
has created a new source of funding to encourage the entry of small businesses
into the telecommunications industry.</P>
<P>Section 707 of the Act adds a new section 714 to the Communications Act of
1934 which establishes the Telecommunications Development Fund (&quot;TDF&quot;).
 The purpose of the TDF is threefold: (1) to promote access to capital for small
businesses in order to enhance competition in the telecommunications industry,
(2) to stimulate new technology development and promote employment and training,
and (3) to support universal service and promote delivery of telecommunications
services to underserved rural and urban areas.  </P>
<P>The TDF will be capitalized, in part, from the interest that accrues on the
deposits made by bidders in the Federal Communications Commission (&quot;FCC&quot;)
spectrum auctions.  Within forty-five (45) days of an auction's conclusion, the
interest accrued from the deposits of bidders will be placed into the TDF.  The
provision requiring auction bidders' upfront payments to be placed into an
interest-bearing account is one of the more innovative approaches to raising
capital ever taken by Congress and the FCC.  The TDF is also authorized to
receive capital from funds appropriated to the FCC for advances to the TDF,
contributions and donations, and any repayment of, or payment made with respect
to, loans, equity, or other credit extensions made from the TDF.  The TDF has
over $7 million in interest from auctions in it today, but it is expected to
grow larger from future auctions and contributions or donations.   </P>
<P>All funds deposited with the TDF will be used solely for making loans,
investments, and other extensions of credit to eligible small businesses,
providing financial advice to eligible small businesses, and other
administrative purposes.  A small business is eligible to apply for a loan or
other credit extension from the TDF if it is engaged in the &quot;telecommunications
industry&quot; and its annual revenue is $50 million or less on average over the
past three (3) years prior to submitting its application.  Under the Act, the
term &quot;telecommunications industry&quot; is defined broadly to include
communications businesses using regulated or unregulated facilities or services
and includes broadcasting, telecommunications, cable, computer, data
transmission, software, programming, advanced messaging, and electronics
businesses.   </P>
<P>Section 714 provides that loans and other credit extensions to eligible
small businesses will be based on the following criteria: (1) the analysis of
the business plan of the eligible small business, (2) the reasonable
availability of collateral to secure the loan or credit extension, (3) the
extent to which the loan or credit extension promotes the purposes of the TDF,
and (4) other lending policies as defined by the TDF Board of Directors. </P>
<P>For further information concerning the status of the TDF, contact the FCC's
Office of Communications Business Opportunities at 202-418-0990 or see the FCC's
web site at <A HREF="http://www.fcc.gov">http://www.fcc.gov</A>.</P>
<HR>
