<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>States Remain at the Forefront of the Telecommunications Revolution</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></H2>
<HR>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">States Remain at the Forefront of the Telecommunications
Revolution </H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="http:/htm/sibley.htm">Horace H. Sibley</A></H2>
<H6 ALIGN="CENTER">This article originally appeared in the November 1996 issue
of <EM>Legal Trends Advisory for Corporate Leaders</EM>. Reproduced by
permission.</H6>
<HR>
<P>With this year's passage of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 and the
recent attempt by the Federal Communications Commission (&quot;FCC&quot;) to
establish nationwide rules for pricing and interconnection of competitive local
telephone service, a great deal of attention has been focused on
telecommunications activity at the federal level.  However, prior to the latest
federal action a number of states had already passed legislation to authorize
local competition and many were in the process of implementing competition in
their local markets.  Indeed, the states have been the catalysts for many of the
changes now occurring at the federal level.  </P>
<P>Local service has traditionally been primarily the province of state
regulators, and the Telecommunications Act of 1996 continues to carve out a
major role for states to manage the transition to competition within their
jurisdictions.  State regulators are given, among other things, the role of
overseeing the implementation of  interconnection agreements between the local
phone company and new competitors, and the states must approve the pricing of
services for resale and the cost to competitive providers of unbundled services
that they need to obtain from the local phone company.</P>
<P>Universal service issues - what it is, who will get it and how it will be
paid for - are also critical to the states.  The Telecommunications Act of 1996
established a Federal-State Joint Board to explore these issues from a federal
perspective.  The Joint Board's recommendations were recently issued to the FCC
on November 7th and must be acted on by the FCC by May 8, 1997.  Access charges
currently paid by long distance companies to local companies, which currently
provide a tremendous contribution to support universal service at the local
level, are also slated for revision by the FCC in a proceeding scheduled to be
completed by mid-1997.  States will have to be deeply engaged in these federal
processes to protect state interests and will have to create their own
intrastate mechanisms to assure the continued availability of universal service
within their respective jurisdictions.  </P>
<P>The states will also have to find new and creative ways to manage the
development of the telecommunications industry in their state in the new
post-regulatory competitive era.  In Georgia, one effort that has already been
undertaken is the development of a three-sector partnership of the state's
research universities, the business community and state government to foster
economic development in the area of advanced telecommunications.  As part of
this effort, and to provide a base for future growth in the state's
telecommunications industry, the Georgia Center for Advanced Telecommunications
Technology (&quot;GCATT&quot;) was established.  GCATT's overall mission is to
provide a focal point to help shape and support the emergence of an advanced
telecommunications industry in the state.  To accomplish this goal, GCATT has
five specific missions, several of which are in direct support of universal
service goals:</P>
<P>(1) to further economic development in the state through the growth of an
advanced telecommunications industry;</P>
<P>(2) to advance the quality and cost effectiveness of education, health care,
and human services through the use of advanced telecommunications; </P>
<P>(3) to conduct basic research in technologies that underlie the advanced
telecommunications industry; </P>
<P>(4) to further the development of enlightened public policies to resolve the
ethical and regulatory issues that surround advanced telecommunications; and</P>
<P>(5) to conduct applied, industrial research and to develop applications in
support of the advanced telecommunications industry.  </P>
<P>There are many advantages that the states will enjoy as a result of the
introduction of competition into the local telephone markets.  However, there is
also no doubt that any dislocations resulting from the transition from a
monopoly to a competitive environment will fall most heavily on the local
economy, businesses, and ratepayers.  As a result, states will have to remain at
the forefront of the telecommunications revolution and find new and innovative
ways to channel the benefits of competition in a positive direction for the
states.  </P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG
