<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Living On Earth: Who Are We?</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 1.0">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=480 LEFT=8 RIGHT=538>
   <!-- Date: Wednesday, October 25, 1995  4:21 PM -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P><BODY><IMG SRC="../images/newlogo.gif" WIDTH=472 HEIGHT=121
BORDER=0 ALIGN=bottom><BR>

</P>

<P>This year marks Living On Earth's fifth anniversary. Every week
over <A HREF="stations/stations.html">250 National Public Radio stations</A>
broadcast Living On Earth's news, features, interviews and commentary
on a broad range of ecological issues.</P>

<H3>Cast and Crew</H3>

<P><A HREF="curwoodbio.html">Steve Curwood,</A> Host / Executive
Producer</P>

<P>Chris Ballman, Senior Producer<BR>

Dan Grossman, Editor<BR>

George Homsy, Coordinating Producer<BR>

Liz Lempert, Assistant Producer<BR>

Julia Madeson, Assistant to Executive Producer<BR>

Kim Motylewski, Associate Producer<BR>

Jan Nunley, Development Director/News Roundup Host<BR>

Peter Shaw, Bookkeeper<BR>

Susan Shepherd, Assistant Producer<BR>

Deborah Stavro, Marketing Director<BR>

Peter Thomson, Senior Correspondent<BR>

Constantine von Hoffman, Newscast Producer<BR>

</P>

<P>Michael Giammusso and Jason Kral - Editorial Assistants</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>Living On Earth is produced in cooperation with
<B><A HREF="http://web.bu.edu/COM/html/wbur.html">WBUR-FM in
Boston</A></B> and
<B><A HREF="http://www.harvard.edu/~PS.html/~ims/">Harvard
University</A></B></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H3>Recent Awards</H3>

<DL>
   <DT><B>June 1996</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth is again honored by the New York Festivals as
   an outstanding environmental series.
   
   <DT><B>March 1996</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth wins a bronze Cindy Award for Bob Carty's
   report, "Who Owns Life? Patenting Human Genes"
   
   <DT><B>February 1996</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth receives two Silver Reel Awards from the
   National Federation of Community Broadcasters. "The Wolf and the
   Soul of the West" by reporter Sandy Tolan is honored with the
   silver in the national documentary category. A report by Joe
   Richman, "Paper Chase: The Black Market in Newsprint," receives
   the silver award in the national news and public affairs category.
   
   <DT><B>July 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth wins a 1995 Edward R. Murrow Award from the
   Radio and Television News Directors Association for "Who Owns
   Life? Patenting Human Genes", a report by Bob Carty on genetic
   piracy."
   
   <DT><B>June 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth is honored by the New York Festivals as an
   outstanding environmental series.
</DL>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H3>Major Support For Living On Earth is provided by:</H3>

<P>National Science Foundation<BR>

W. Alton Jones Foundation<BR>

Ford Foundation<BR>

William and Flora Hewlett Foundation<BR>

W.K. Kellogg Foundation</P>

<H3>Additional Support comes from:</H3>

<P>Joyce Foundation<BR>

Geraldine R. Dodge Foundation<BR>

Great Lakes Protection Fund<BR>

George Gund Foundation<BR>

Town Creek Foundation<BR>

Turner Foundation<BR>

Stonyfield Farm Yogurt<BR>

</P>

<P>and from <A HREF="http://www.npr.org">National Public Radio</A>
</P>

<H3>Living On Earth Highlights 1991 - 1996</H3>

<DL>
   <DT><B>October 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth launches its one hour edition.
   
   <DT><B>September 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth joins forces with the Great Lakes Radio
   Consortium to enhance its coverage of environmental stories from
   the Midwest.
   
   <DT><B>June 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth presents a month-long series, "How Will We
   Eat?," from five countries examining shrinking agricultural
   resources and increasing populations.
   
   <DT><B>April 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth teams up with Soundprint and Homelands
   Productions to produce a five-part series, "Earth Day +25: A
   Checkup on the Planet"
   
   <DT><B>April 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth kicks off a year-long series profiling 25
   Influential Americans in the Environment.
   
   <DT><B>January 1995</B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth opens its Midwest Bureau at WCPN in Cleveland.
   Reporter Robin Finesmith anchors midwestern coverage of
   environmental stories.
   
   <DT><B>October 1994 </B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth launches environmental science series. A
   three-year grant to Living On Earth from the National Science
   Foundation will fund a major commitment by Living On Earth to
   reporting in four major areas: environmental toxicology,
   biodiversity, atmospheric change and agricultural science.
   
   <DT><B>July 1994 </B>
   
   <DD>Living On Earth is the first national broadcaster to produce
   two ground breaking documentaries examining scientific evidence
   linking synthetic chemicals, known as endocrine disruptors, to
   immune and reproductive abnormalities in animals and humans.
</DL>

