<HEAD>
   <TITLE>This Week on Living On Earth</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=73 BOTTOM=482 LEFT=27 RIGHT=557>
<!-- Date: Wednesday, October 25, 1995  4:21 PM -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P><IMG SRC="../images/newlogo.gif" WIDTH=426 HEIGHT=117
ALIGN=bottom></P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Tune into Living On Earth on </FONT><FONT
SIZE="+1"><A HREF="stations/stations.html">your local public radio
station</A></FONT><FONT SIZE="+1"> the week of January 10 to January
16 and hear the following stories:</FONT><BR>

</P>

<P><B>NATIONAL LAND SWAPS<BR>

</B>In the past year, President Clinton has been behind some high
profile land deals. While they're not Arkansas real estate
developments, these land deals have nevertheless been controversial.
Jyl Hoyt of member station WBSX in Boise, Idaho explains how these
national land swaps work, who they benefit, and why some people
vigorously oppose them. <B> </B></P>

<P><B>PREDATOR-FRIENDLY WOOL<BR>

</B>Ever since sheep were imported and raised in this country, the
tension between ranchers against native coyotes and wolves has been
high. Producer Bob Reha reports on a recent compromise whereby some
man, lamb, and canine are living in greater harmony.<B> </B></P>

<P><B>BITTER COLD<BR>

</B>Commentator Susan Carol Hauser remarks on how even people who
love the winter have difficulty abiding negative double digit weather
for long.</P>

<P><B>SECOND HALF HOUR</B></P>

<P><B>The Living On Earth Almanac<BR>

</B>Facts about... things that shorten life expectency.</P>

<P><B>ANTARCTICA SERIES: PART 3 &emdash; GLOBAL WARMING  AND THE
POLAR ICE SHELVES?</B>  <BR>

Terry FitzPatrick reports on the  latest research into what is
causing large masses of ice to break off  the world's frozen
continent.  If uncontrolled global warming is in  fact the cause,
predictions forecast a significantly more watery  world.  Encore
broadcast. </P>

<P><B>ANTARCTICA UPDATE<BR>

</B>Steve Curwood talks with the reporter  of the Antarctica series,
Terry FitzPatrick, about his experiences  there and what got left out
of the 4 part series. </P>

<P><B>ENVIRO SCHOOL BOOM</B><BR>

Schools in Grand Rapids, Michigan  are promoting environmental
education in many innovative ways.  Wendy Nelson  of the Great Lakes
Radio Consortium reports on this  current boomin green cirriculum. 
</P>

<P>
