<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT06-B35-46</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA034-000693-B042-245</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.loe.org:80/html/susag/susag.html 207.60.134.31 19970110231328 text/html 5302
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Friday, 10-Jan-97 23:22:14 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 20-Dec-96 16:07:28 GMT
Content-length: 5113
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!--This file created 12/19/96 3:29 PM by Claris Home Page version 2.0-->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Living On Earth: Election '96</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=45 BOTTOM=461 LEFT=24 RIGHT=556>
<!-- Date: Wednesday, October 25, 1995  4:21 PM -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P><IMG SRC="../../images/ag-header.gif" WIDTH=481 HEIGHT=126
X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom><BR>

<BR>

</P>

<H2>Sustainable Agriculture<TABLE BORDER=5 WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=140
align=RIGHT hspace=3 vspace=2>
   <TR>
      <TD VALIGN=top>
         <H4 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#000000">Sustainable Ag
         Links</FONT></H4>
         
         <P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.mother.com/agaccess">Ag
         Access</A></P>
         
         <P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.cityfarmer.org">City
         Farmer</A></P>
         
         <P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.onenw.org/cbd/">Conservation
         Based Development</A></P>
         
         <P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="http://www.ewg.org">Environmental
         Working Group</A></P>
         
         <P ALIGN=CENTER>&nbsp;
      </TD></TR>
</TABLE></H2>

<P><B><A HREF="grocery.html">NATURAL FOODS GAIN GROUND</A></B><BR>

Natural foods supermarkets with huge aisles of organic produce and
nutritional guarantees are sprouting up all over.  Living On Earth
producer Kim Motylewski went to the openings of two grand scale new
markets to see who these new ventures will be benefitting.  Chances
are, competition will be driving some prices down, and consumers wil
be faring better along with farmers and merchandisers.  </P>

<P><B><A HREF="grain.html">ORGANIC GRAIN</A></B><BR>

Not all organic products are in demand, according to Fred
Kirschenmann, president of Farm Verified Organic, Inc.  Mr.
Kirshenmann, who serves on the National Organic Standards Board, says
crop rotation for soil health is another important component in the
organics movement.</P>

<P><B><A HREF="saxon.html">SUSTAINABLE DAIRY FARMING</A></B><BR>

Steve Curwood visits a family farm near the shores of Lake Michigan
to report on a sustainable alternative to traditional dairy farming.
"Rotational Grazing" combines old-fashioned grazing practices with
modern technology to reduce production costs, improve soil quality,
prevent manure runoff and attract wildlife back to the farm.</P>

<P><B><A HREF="almond.html">ALMOND BROTHERS</A></B><BR>

Matt Binder reports from the Great Central Valley of California about
two brothers who farm almonds, side by side, in the tiny town of
Hilmar. One brother cultivates his nuts the way most almond farmers
do, with synthetic chemical fertilizers, insecticides, fungicides and
herbicides. Just across the road his brother farms organically. And
as you can imagine, they have some spirited debates.</P>

<P><B><A HREF="amish.html">AMISH</A></B><BR>

Many see America's tightly-knit Amish communities as odd throwbacks
to the days of the horse and buggy. But Amish beliefs don't reject
progress so much as they call for the sustainable use of God's gifts
of creation.</P>

<P><B><A HREF="caretaker1.html">COMMUNITY-SUPPORTED
AGRICULTURE</A></B><BR>

Steve Curwood talks with the owners of Caretaker Farm in
Williamstown, MA, a community-supported agriculture enterprise that
links traditional organic, local food production and an
unconventional approach to marketing.</P>

<P><B><A HREF="../../Liz/Web%20stuff%20for%20Liz/caretaker3.html">PICK
YOUR OWN PESTO</A></B><BR>

Steve Curwood returns to the Caretaker Farm in Western Massachusetts
for the fall harvest season. The Anderson family have paid shares in
the farm, and Curwood is invited back to their kitchen to sample some
homemade pesto they're preparing for the winter ahead.</P>

<P><B><A HREF="caretaker4.html">COMMUNITY-SUPPORTED FARMS</A></B><BR>

Caretaker Farm in Williamstown, Massachusetts finishes out the year.
</P>

<P><B><A HREF="cuba.html">ORGANIC FOOD REVOLUTION IN CUBA</A></B><BR>

Following the collapse of the Soviet Union four years ago, Cuba's
supply of fertilizers and pesticides was cut back 80 percent, its
fuel supply cut in half. Now, there is an urgent need for the country
to feed its people, but there is no money to buy farm chemicals or
oil. So Cubans have turned to organic farming on a national scale.
It's a high risk gamble that uses plows and oxen instead of tractors
and turbines and biological pest controls instead of chemical
pesticides. Reporter Bruce Gellerman traveled to Cuba to find out
what farmers have learned and what lessons the experiment holds for
sustainable growers around the world.<B> </B></P>

<P><BR>

</P>

<P>
<HR>
<B>Comments? Suggestions? Living on Earth wants to hear from you!
</B> Email us at <A HREF="../feedback.html">loe@npr.org</A>, or call
our listener line (1-800-218-9988). Our mailing address is P.O. Box
380639, Cambridge, MA 02238-0639.
<HR>
</P>

