<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Living On Earth's Steve Curwood</TITLE>

<!-- Date: Wednesday, October 25, 1995  4:21 PM -->

</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<BODY>
<IMG  SRC="../images/steve.gif" width=464  height=60>
<P>
<H2>Tracking the Planet's Most Important Story</H2>

<IMG SRC="../images/Small_Steve.gif" width=212 height=165 align=left hspace=9 vspace=5>
The creator, executive producer, and host of National Public Radio's 
environmental journal of the air, "Living On Earth" rocks in his office chair, now leaning forward, now stretching back, juggling urgent phone calls, putting out production brush fires. His brainchild is almost five years old now, featured on more than 260 NPR stations across the country and in 400 countries worldwide as part of the Armed Forces Radio Network. Steve Curwood is an immensely proud papa. And "Living On Earth" is a pretty demanding child.
<P>
"Early on, somebody told me, 'Steve, you know what? You'll get six months into this and you'll be dying on Earth. How are you going to do more than twenty programs on the environment?'" Curwood chuckles. "Now we have more stories than we can use."  And that's despite the fact the show recently doubled its available airtime to an hour. 
<P>
The show blends two important streams of his life: a love of the natural world, and a driving desire to write and report. The first Curwood traces to his boyhood on a farm in southern New Hampshire, where the family moved from Boston after his father's death when Curwood was two. His mother, then a graduate student in social psychology and junior faculty member at Harvard, instilled in Curwood a fascination with nature. There wasn't a lot of money, and "when we moved to the country, for Christmas presents she'd get glass jars, go into the woods, and get a little bit of moss or berry, and make terrariums for friends as presents. She'd literally go around handing out pieces of the earth." 
<P>
When Steve was five, his mother took a tenure - track position at Antioch College in Yellow Springs, Ohio.  Steve's Quaker family attended the Yellow Springs Friends Meeting, where Steve learned that "it was really important to be involved with the community, with the tribe, really," he recalls. Much later, Steve learned to appreciate his own tribal heritage: his maternal great-grandmother was a member of the Cherokee Nation and his mother's generation had tribal rights. Curiously, the family didn't embrace that indigenous heritage, says Curwood, although "my ethnic background is varied, a lot of African people, a lot of Irish, and then this Native American ancestor." He speculates that his mother's, and his own intense interest in the outdoors may stem from this link.
<P>
Another love was born during those days in Yellow Springs, and "love brought me into it," Steve laughs. A crush on the local correspondent for the 4-H club led him to accept the position of scribe for his Boy Scout troop. "I could get out of school to deliver my copy to the local paper, and spend a little time seeing if I could catch her eye,  well, why not?" But what turned his head was something quite different. He watched as the copy editor finished his changes and walked back to the typesetter. "And this big old Linotype machine started setting this story, my story," he recalls, with some of the same awe. "And then the thing came out in the paper, and I was completely hooked. I have no idea what happened to the girl, but newspapers? That was it."
<P>
In 1965, Curwood entered Harvard, and spent his summers as an engineer for the Boston news/talk radio station, WEEI-AM. The second summer at WEEI, riots broke out in Boston's Roxbury section.  Curwood was at the right place at the right time. "They didn't have anybody they could send out to the riots. So they gave me a microphone, a tape recorder, a hard hat and a news cruiser," recalls Curwood. "Can you imagine driving into a riot zone in a big old station wagon with 'WEEI' on the side and a revolving light on top? This was a serious riot. The crowd kinda rolled by and I stuck the microphone out and I got the hell out of there!" But the news bug that bit him years ago was back.
<P>
Steve took an internship at the "Bay State Banner", the "Boston Globe's" weekly newspaper for the African-American community, where he went from reporter to managing editor in short order. "I suppose some would say 'how could this be an authentic voice for the black community with the white folks downtown paying the tab?'," says Curwood. "But I got opportunities I never would have had at a white operation" , such as covering the 1972 Democratic Convention for the Banner. And it put Curwood, who, although born in Roxbury, says he "never really grew up in black America," right in the heart of Boston's black ghetto.
<P>
His mentors downtown noticed him, and in 1973 he joined the Globe's Spotlight investigative team to cover Boston's desegregation battles. "The school suit filed in 1970 had boiled over by that time," he says, "so I was in the thick of a very sad, hard time for the city." In his view, both blacks and working-class whites were the victims of a cynical racial shell game , played by affluent whites in the suburbs, whose children didn't have to be bused, and by members of the city's School Committee who profited financially from the turmoil. "The School Committee was usually obstructionist about everything to do with desegregation, until a Federal judge told them they had to do it," Curwood recalls. "Then one day the actual school busing contract came up, the 'instrument of social death,' as they called it. And they approved it without so much as a cough or a sniffle." The clerk, who Curwood could usually count on to tell him what was happening, "wouldn't tell me what time it was that day. Turns out there was a bid-rigging scheme going on, and eventually some of the members wound up in jail." Curwood shakes his head. "It's one thing for people to stand up for a position they truly believe in, even if it's horrible and wrong, but to learn that these people were so deeply cynical that they were manipulating the voters with race-baiting just to line their own pockets . . ." His voice trails off. "I'd had enough of the school system before long."
<P>
Steve's work earned him a share of a Pulitzer Prize for the Globe's coverage of Boston's desegregation crisis. The paper's owners wanted him in management, but Curwood said no. Not long after, he was recruited by Boston's public television station, WGBH, to report for their new "10 O'Clock News." He also narrated some episodes of Nova and worked on the station's minority show "Say Brother." Then the offer came to produce for "The Advocates", hosted by Michael Dukakis.
<P>
"The premise of 'The Advocates' was that you had an idea that you put on trial," he explains. "It had to be a real idea that somebody could take action on, like the Equal Rights Amendment. Each side had an advocate, a lawyer, arguing for it, who would call witnesses. It was a totally eye-opening experience, a great show , and it ran out of money." Curwood later tried to produce a radio version of the show, and hasn't given up the idea yet.
<P>
But his immediate problem was being out of a job. "Somebody told me they were hiring at National Public Radio," he says, and shortly thereafter the Curwoods moved to Washington. Steve worked as a Capitol Hill reporter, and covered the State Department and the White House too. But he'd heard rumors the network was starting a morning version of the popular evening flagship show "All Things Considered." "So I went down there with the idea of trying to get the anchor job. They hired some guy named Bob Edwards instead," he says wryly. NPR put him to work anchoring the weekend version of "All Things Considered" with Liane Hansen and others, following Noah Adams' departure. "I had a ball," he says. "But my family didn't like it that my weekends were Mondays and Tuesdays."
<P>
The Globe welcomed him back, this time as a business reporter, a columnist, and eventually back on the education beat , this time, the state's public higher education system, which had become "a cesspool." Curwood's investigation of questionable campaign contributions by some of Massachusetts' state college administrators led to the downfall of at least two college presidents. Another investigation, this one of a case in which a woman abducted and hid her child from the husband she alleged had sexually abused the child, led Curwood to write a still-unpublished manuscript , and to want out of daily journalism.
<P>
"I came to the end of that process wanting to do deeper journalism," he says. "My kid James said, 'Dad, you've got to do something about the environment!' Well, I thought, who's going to buy a book by Steve Curwood about global warming , what's my expertise on that? But James was right. So I said to my book agent, 'I think I could do a very limited radio series to publicize the book.' Well," he smiles, "the book isn't done." He wrote up a proposal for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting in the fall of 1989. "They said 'No way. This will never work.' But I was really bitten by then, so I went to some local businesses and came up with enough dough to make four pilots for Earth Day." By that time, Curwood had engaged the attention of some of "Living on Earth's" future staffers: coordinating producer George Homsy and marketing director Deborah Stavro.
<P>
"The shows that we had for that Earth Day [1990] were pretty awful," he observes. "They were interesting , we did a debate on the new light-water nuclear reactors, we talked to Jesse Jackson about the environmental justice movement. But the production values were fairly weak. Still," he says, "there was a spark there. By the next year, I had raised enough to go on a weekly basis and get a hundred stations to carry it." Sadly, Curwood's mother died just six months before the show actually premiered.
<P>
Even the grammatical form of the name had significance. "I used the gerund 'Living,'" says Curwood, "instead of 'Life on Earth' or something like 'Earth Times' to signify that it is today , it's what each of us is doing, it's not static." Basing the format on the highly-successful "All Things Considered" let the show range from serious reports, analysis and commentary to light-hearted features.
<P>
"I always believed that when we got into it, the stories would start presenting themselves," says Curwood. "That vision was clear from day one. I was scared, though. When the Persian Gulf War came along right before we first went on, I thought, will people care about the environment in the middle of a war? And then the Gulf War became an environmental story. The next year the Soviet Union imploded, and I thought, surely this will bump us off the map. But in fact part of the USSR's unraveling related to its horrible environmental problems."
<P>
The show has changed from those early days, Curwood says. "I think we're doing better, more mature reporting," he observes. "We're looking more at the process of people dealing with environmental change, and we're doing less of the 'here's something really horrible' stories. We still do major investigations, but we're doing a better job of putting them in a context. "I really want us to be the 'program of record' on environmental change. I think the broader community of people who are concerned about that change probably aren't aware of what we're doing, and I hope we'll begin tapping that audience. My mission here is to be sure that "Living On Earth" is a place where people really do hear something that provokes them to think, and to act.
<P>
"There's a story about John Woolman, who was a Friend in America's colonial days. Woolman would show up at Meetings all over the Eastern Seaboard, arguing against slavery; it was very disturbing for the Friends. One time he showed up for a Meeting and no one else was there. He sat down, and when the spirit moved him he stood up and talked just as if it were a full house. As he was leaving, he heard a noise, and looked around to find a man who had been hiding in the foyer the whole time. 'Thee has convinced me,' the man told Woolman." Curwood smiles. "So he never knew who he was talking to and what effect it would have. But the seed of change had been planted. And you never know, when you do a story, what seed you may have planted."

 <P>
<HR>
<B>Comments? Suggestions? Living on Earth wants to hear from you! </B>
Email us at <A HREF="feedback.html">loe@npr.org</A>, or call our listener line (1-800-218-9988). Our mailing address is P.O. Box 380639, Cambridge, MA 02238-0639.
<HR>
