<P><IMG SRC="../../images/story.gif" WIDTH=464 HEIGHT=61
ALIGN=bottom></P>

<H2>Oil Spill Threatens Japan Coast</H2>

<P>Air Date: Week of January 10, 1997</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="-1">Copyright 1996 by World Media Foundation. No
portion of this transcript may be copied, sold, or transmitted
without the written authority of World Media Foundation.</FONT><BR>

</P>

<P>An oil spill from a Russian tanker may ruin one of Japan's richest
marine  environments. A spokesman for Japan's fisheries disaster task
force says the spill will spoil the area's seaweed crop for years and
hurt birds that roost in the area. Earlier this month a tanker
carrying 19,000 tons of heavy fuel oil, broke in two and started
leaking oil in the Sea of Japan. So far more than 60 miles of
coastline have been fouled by the spills, one of the worst ever to
hit Japan. In 1995, more than 150,000 tons of fish, shellfish, crab,
shrimp, squid and other marine produce were harvested in the
now-threatened area.</P>

<P>
<HR>
<B>Comments? Suggestions? Living on Earth wants to hear from you!
</B> Email us at <A HREF="../feedback.html">loe@npr.org</A>, or call
our listener line (1-800-218-9988). Our mailing address is P.O. Box
380639, Cambridge, MA 02238-0639.
<HR>
</P>

