<P><IMG SRC="../../images/story.gif" WIDTH=464 HEIGHT=61
ALIGN=bottom></P>

<H2>Pesticides Linked to Alligator Sex Defects</H2>

<P>Air Date: Week of January 10, 1997</P>

<P><FONT SIZE="-1">Copyright 1996 by World Media Foundation. No
portion of this transcript may be copied, sold, or transmitted
without the written authority of World Media Foundation.</FONT><BR>

</P>

<P>There is more evidence linking pesticides to health problems in
Florida alligators. Researchers studying the declining alligator
population in Florida's Lake Apopka say that  residual DDT and a
pesticide called dicofol are responsible for abnormalities in the
alligator's reproductive system. DDT was banned in the United States
for most uses more than 20 years ago. Dicofol is used to kill mites. 
The study was published  in the journal Environmental Health
Perspectives. </P>

<P>
