<H2>Green Gardening Spot Resource List</H2>

<P>The following books and magazines were mentioned in Living on
Earth's ongoing series on organic gardening with special
correspondent, Evelyn Tully Costa. <TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=1
CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=464 HEIGHT=1>
   <TR>
      <TD align=LEFT>
         <P><B><IMG SRC="../../images/wreath.gif" WIDTH=90 HEIGHT=119
         X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=middle></B>
      </TD><TD COLSPAN=4>
         <P><B>The Ultimate Wreath Book</B>, by Ellen Spector
         Platt<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>Rodale, 1995</P>
         
         <P>This book suggests hundreds of wreaths to make from
         natural materials.</P>
         
         <P>(Additional resource for
         <A HREF="wreath.html">Wreaths</A> segment, air date December
         1996)
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD COLSPAN=5>
         <P><B>The Natural Christmas</B>, by Tom Pritchard and Billy
         Jarecki. <B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>Clarkson Potter, 1996.</P>
         
         <P>This book has several holiday craft ideas including
         wreaths, candles, and garlands.</P>
         
         <P>(Mentioned in <A HREF="wreath.html">Wreaths</A> segment,
         air date December 1996)
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD COLSPAN=4>
         <P><B>Bulbs for Indoors,Year-Round, Windowsill Splendor</B>,
         by<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>Hays and Marinelli, Brooklyn Botantical Garden,
         1996.<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>A guide to growing bulbous plants ranging from
         tree bulbs to tubers.Includes tips on forcing bulbs indoors,
         and a list of the best bulbs for indoor
         gardens.<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"> </FONT></B>To contact
         Brooklyn Botanical, call 718-622-4433, or check out the
         <A HREF="http://www.bbg.org">Brooklyn Botanical web
         site</A>.</P>
         
         <P>(Mentioned in <A HREF="bulbs.html">Bulbs</A> segment, air
         date November 1996)
      </TD><TD>
         <P><IMG SRC="../../images/bulbs.gif" WIDTH=90 HEIGHT=134
         X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight BORDER=1
         ALIGN=middle>
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD width=94>
         <P><IMG SRC="../../images/preserving.gif" WIDTH=90
         HEIGHT=112 BORDER=1 ALIGN=middle>
      </TD><TD COLSPAN=4>
         <P><B><FONT COLOR="#000000">Preserving Summer's
         Bounty</FONT></B><FONT COLOR="#000000">, by Susan McClure,
         ed., Rodale Books, 1995</FONT><B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>Describes various methods of preserving fruits
         and vegetables, including freezing, canning, and drying, and
         discusses which works best for which fruits and
         vegetables.<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B><FONT COLOR="#000000">(Mentioned in
         </FONT><FONT COLOR="#000000"><A HREF="bounty.html">Harvest
         Home</A></FONT><FONT COLOR="#000000"> segment, air date
         October 1996)</FONT>
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD COLSPAN=4>
         <P><B>The New Seed-Starters Handbook</B> by Nancy Bubel,
         <B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>Rodale Press, 1988.<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>This book will walk you through the growing
         process, from starting seeds indoors, moving plants
         outdoors, to saving seeds for the
         future.<B><FONT COLOR="#000000"><BR>
         
         </FONT></B>(Additional resource for
         <A HREF="seeds.html">Saving Seeds</A> segment, air date
         September 1996)
      </TD><TD>
