<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Supporting efforts to minimize the harm associated with alcohol, tobacco and 
other drug use</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="/newlogo.gif" WIDTH=372 HEIGHT=167 ALT="CCSA-CCLAT">
<H1><A NAME = support></A>Federal 
support slipping</H1>
During the 1980s, public concern over health, social and economic problems related to substance abuse 
was very strong, and governments in the US and Canada responded by funding countermeasures such as 
the US War on Drugs and Canada's Drug Strategy (CDS).  Since that time, attention to these vital issues 
has gradually slipped away, and governments now spend less and less on prevention and treatment of drug 
abuse and alcoholism. In late 1995, Health Canada decided to substantially reduce its participation in the CDS, 
which the department had launched with great fanfare in 1987, and renewed in 1992. The abandonment 
of the CDS a year earlier than anticipated comes at a time when drug use among North American high 
school students is inching upwards for the first time in 10 years, and the trend toward fewer alcohol-
related road fatalities appears to be about to reverse itself.<P>
If the Canadian government's faltering commitment to reducing the devastation caused by alcohol and 
other drugs is of concern to you, why not speak up?  Send a message to the federal cabinet ministers 
responsible for Canada's Drug Strategy:<P>
<B>The Right Honorable Jean Chretien</B><BR>
Prime Minister<BR>
Room 309-S, Centre Block<BR>
House of Commons<BR>
Ottawa, ON  K1A 0A6<BR>
(613) 992-4211<P>
