<H1><A NAME = 
provincial></A>Provincial agencies 
disappearing</H1>
Cutbacks have had a disastrous impact on provincial and territorial efforts to treat and prevent substance 
abuse problems. During the past couple of years, several provinces have dismantled independently run 
government agencies established in the 1960s and '70s to focus special attention on drug and alcohol 
issues. Now, as part of the overall health care delivery system in these jurisdictions, prevention, education 
and treatment no longer receive the attention they once did, and a wealth of expertise is being lost. Even 
in provinces where independent agencies such as the Alberta Alcohol and Drug Abuse Commission and 
the Addiction Research Foundation of Ontario continue to exist, cuts to funding have seriously 
compromised the effectiveness of substance abuse programs.<P>
If you are concerned about the ongoing disintegration of what once was a strong and useful network of 
Canadian substance abuse experts and resources, contact any or all of the following provincial/territorial 
ministers:<P>
<H3>Alberta</H3>
