<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Canada's Drug Strategy</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<IMG SRC="/cds.gif" WIDTH=450 HEIGHT=150>
<H1>Canada's Drug Strategy</H1>
<HR>
The objective of Canada's Drug Strategy (CDS) is to reduce the social, economic, physical and 
psychological harm to individuals, families and communities caused by the use and abuse of alcohol and 
other drugs.  The Strategy is a national initiative for which the Minister of Health Canada has lead 
responsibility.  It is an integrated, multi-departmental, and multi-sectoral strategy involving seven federal 
program departments:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Health Canada
<LI>Canadian Heritage
<LI>Justice Canada
<LI>Revenue Canada, Customs
<LI>Ministry of the Solicitor General
<UL>
<LI>Solicitor General Secretariat
<LI>Royal Canadian Mounted Police
<LI>Correction Services Canada
</UL>
<LI>Human Resources Development
<LI>Foreign Affairs and International Trade
</UL>
The Strategy was originally initiated in 1987 for a five-year period with an allocation of $210 million.  
The Strategy was renewed in 1992 for a second five-year term with an allocation of $270 million.  Also 
included in Phase II was the National Driving While Impaired Strategy.<P>
Fundamental to the Strategy are principles of collaboration and partnership and as such inlcudes the 
participation of provincial and territorial governments, law enforcement agencies and organizations, 
community groups, NGO's, business, labour and professional associations.  The Strategy is characterized 
by a balanced approach which includes elements of enforcement and control as well as prevention, 
treatment and rehabilitation.<P>
