<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Economic costs of substance abuse</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/dollars.gif" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=111 VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALT="Economic costs">
<CENTER><H1>Studying the economic costs<BR>of 
substance abuse -<BR>
Process development</H1></CENTER><BR CLEAR=left><HR>
<H4>What is the cost of substance abuse to society?</H4>
<H4>What proportion is realistically avoidable?</H4>
<H4>Where should we invest to avoid these costs?</H4>
<H4>What is our return on investment?</H4>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/bluefade.gif" WIDTH=595 HEIGHT=18>
<H2>What is Happening?</H2>
<UL>
<LI>CCSA held an international symposium in 1994 to develop a methodology for cost estimation
<LI>An extensive literature review was conducted:<BR>
<A HREF="/costslit.htm">Literature Review of Studies on the Economic Costs of Substance Abuse</A><BR>
by Lynda Robson (Ph.D.) and Eric Single (Ph.D.)
<LI>The resulting guidelines have been published:  <A HREF="/guidelns.htm">International Guidelines for Estimating the Costs of Substance Abuse</A>
<LI>A second symposium was held in October 1995 to improve the methodology, examine avoidable costs 
and begin the cost/benefit analyses of policies and programs
<LI>The guidelines have been tested in Canada and Australia, and are being tested in the U.S.
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/costhigh.htm">The Costs of Substance Abuse in Canada</A><BR>
Highlights of a major study of the health, social and economic costs associated with the use of alcohol, tobacco and illicit drugs
<LI><B>The social costs of drug abuse in Australia in 1988 and 1992.</B>  David J. Collins and Helen M. Lapsley.  Report prepared for the Commonwealth Department of Human Services and Health, February 1996.  National Drug Strategy Monograph Series, No. 30.  ISBN 0 664 35742 8
</UL>
</UL><P>
<B><I><A HREF="/ordcosts.htm">To order the Canadian cost study publications, click here</A></I></B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/bluefade.gif" WIDTH=595 HEIGHT=18>
<H2>Who is Supporting the Process?</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The UN, ILO, WHO, World Bank and other organizations in Europe, North America, Asia and 
Australasia
<LI>Several federal departments and some provincial governments
</UL>
<P>
