<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse annual report</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Annual Review 1994/95</H2>
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000077">Creating</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#990099">k</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#ff0099">n</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#cc0000">o</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#ffff00">w</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#33ff66">l</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#009900">e</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#0099cc">d</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#3300ff">g</FONT><FONT SIZE=7 COLOR="#000077">e</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000077">from information...</FONT><P>
<B><I>Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse<BR>
75 Albert St., Suite 300, Ottawa, ON, K1P 5E7<BR>
Tel: (613) 235-4048 Fax: (613) 235-8101</B></I><P>
<I>Optimized for Netscape 2.0</I><P>
<HR>
Throughout its seven-year existence, the Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse has worked hard to live up 
to the mandate it received from Parliament to contribute "to the development and application of 
knowledge and expertise" in the substance abuse field.  Although CCSA fulfils other functions, we see this 
role as our main raison d'être.  Our long-term goal is to develop a Canadian knowledge system on alcohol 
and other drugs.<P>
That is why we established the National Clearinghouse on Substance Abuse, and why, more recently, we 
initiated projects on estimating the social and economic costs of alcohol and other drug abuse.  That is 
also the reason we are spearheading new information partnerships such as the Canadian community 
Epidemiology Network on Drug Use (CCENDU), and the Workplace Substance Abuse Information 
Network.  For us the impetus in each of these cases is simple: we cannot make sound decisions about 
alcohol and drug policy and programming in this country if our knowledge of the problem is lacking.<P>
This report is intended as a "snapshot" of CCSA activity in the gathering, creation and dissemination of 
information.  Its focus is mainly quantitative; that is, how many people have we reached? This type of 
measurement is a necessary first step toward discovering something more important: did we really help 
those people? We have begun to work on mechanisms for making that determination and this effort will 
be reflected in future annual reports.<P>
Jacques LeCavalier<BR>
Chief Executive Officer<P>
William Deeks<BR>
Chairman of the Board<P>
