<H3>The official newsletter of the Canadian Centre on 
Substance Abuse</H3>
<H2>Important notice to <I>Action News</I> readers</H2>
The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse began publishing <I>Action News</I> more than six years ago as a way of disseminating news about drug and alcohol abuse to a wide variety of people involved in, or at least concerned with, the prevention of addiction-related problems. Despite endless cost-saving measures, and the introduction of paid subscriptions, the cost of publishing and distributing <I>Action News</I> was a drain on <A HREF="/funding.htm#funding">CCSA's core funding</A>. Now this funding has been severely cut, and as a result, we have suspended formal publication of <I>Action News</I> (<A HREF="/anletter.htm">click here for more details</A>). We will continue to mail out a scaled-down version of our newsletter to paid subscribers for as long as resources allow. We will also post this abbreviated material on our web site. We'll still call it <I>Action News</I> (why reinvent the pretzel?) and, to make librarians' lives easier, we will retain the volume and number system of the old <I>Action News</I>.<P>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=50%>
<FONT COLOR="0000FF"><H1>Action News, Vol. VII No. 2, 1996</H1></FONT>
<H2>National collaboration paves the way for a Canadian prevalence study of problem gambling</H2>
Gambling losses averaged $166 for every person in Canada in 1995. For some families, the cost was 
devastating. A new project could help reduce the harm.<P>
Gambling has become big business in Canada, and big trouble for many people who take a chance on 
lotteries, casinos, and video lottery terminals (VLTs). Provincial governments, quick to em-brace this form of 
voluntary taxation, raked in more than $5 billion in 1995 in lottery revenues alone.<P>
VLTs, described as the "crack cocaine of gambling" by some addictions specialists, are popping up 
everywhere, including Ontario where 20,000 new machines will soon go into service. Government casinos are 
siphoning money away from local charity bingos, and swelling the ranks of impoverished people showing up at 
soup kitchens.<P>
Some provinces are starting to plow a small percentage of gambling revenues back into prevention and 
treatment, and agencies such as the Alberta Alcohol and Drug Abuse Commission (AADAC) are making great 
strides in preparing addictions professionals to deal with the emerging problems.<P>
However, the job of understanding and treating compulsive gambling is severely hampered by a lack of in-
formation about the nature and extent of the problem. We don't have the depth of knowledge around gambling 
that we have around alcohol and drug abuse where we can draw on decades of prevalence studies. As well, the 
methods used to measure problem gambling are not totally satisfactory.<P>
The standard instrument, the South Oaks Gambling Screen (SOGS) was designed for clinical use, not for surveying general populations.<P>
<H3>Provinces unite in project</H3>
The need for more reliable data has led to a promising exercise in national collaboration. In August, Nova 
Scotia hosted a video-conference bringing together officials from nine provinces to talk about gambling and the 
need to collaborate on ways to gather prevalence data. Another meeting of these representatives was held the 
following month in Winnipeg in conjunction with a conference on problem gambling organized by AADAC, 
Saskatchewan Health, and the Addictions Foundation of Manitoba (AFM). The event, Profiling the Canadian 
Experience, attracted more than 250 participants, including 27 representatives from eight provinces who 
agreed to continue discussions on the new Canadian Problem Gambling Prevalence Project.<P>
The project will define problem gambling, and affected populations, using common criteria and standard 
terminology; determine indicators of socio-economic impact; and provide provinces with data they can use to 
decide how to best spend resources. Project participants are communicating by means of an Internet listserv 
provided by CCSA. For more project information, contact <A HREF="mailto:groberts @ccsa.ca">Gary Roberts</A> at CCSA, (613) 235-4048, ext. 225. 
<P>
<H3>What the CADS says about gambling</H3>
CCSA research associate Eric Single has written a chapter on gambling in <I>Canada's Alcohol and Other 
Drugs Survey,</I> soon to be released by Health Canada. The CADS questions were designed to measure 
gambling activity, not problem severity. They reveal:<P>
<UL>
<LI>61.4% of Canadians over the age of 15 played a lottery or cards for money in the previous 12 months;
<LI>46.3% reported playing a lottery, betting on sports, or playing cards for money once a month or more;
<LI>14.8% of respondents played bingo, with 7.7% playing once a month or more;
<LI>8% of those who reported betting on a lottery, sports or cards, or playing bingo travelled to places such as 
Las Vegas, Atlantic City or other Canadian cities with casinos in order to gamble;
<LI>6.8% engaged in some other form of gambling in the past 12 months such as VLTs (0.8%) or buying a 
raffle ticket (0.7%);
<LI>men are more likely than women to bet on lotteries (66.1% v. 59.4%), whereas women are more likely to 
play bingo (18.5% v. 8.2%);
<LI>betting on lotteries, cards or sports increases from ages 15-17 (28.6%) to ages 55-64 (70.6%), then 
declines.
</UL>
<P>
<H2>news and events</H2>
<H3>Long-awaited statement on FAS advises abstention</H3>
A joint statement on fetal alcohol syndrome and fetal alcohol effects, issued by Health C and the Canadian Pediatric Society (CPS), calls FAS the "leading cause of developmental delay" in North America and recommends that "the prudent choice for women who are or may become pregnant is to abstain from alcohol". However, "women who have consumed small amounts of alcohol occasionally during pregnancy" should be told that "the risk is likely minimal".<P>
The FAS/FAE prevention statement was developed and supported by 19 national associations representing medical, nursing and midwifery disciplines, aboriginal and multicultural groups, and other organizations, including CCSA, known for their work in FAS. More than two years in preparation, the statement says prevention efforts should be "family-centred culturally sensitive, and comprehensive".<P>
<A HREF="fasstmnt.htm">To read the Statement.</A><P>
<I>For more information on FAS/FAE, call 1-800-559-4514.  </I><P><I>
</I><H3>Lynda Price goes south</H3>
Lynda Price, president of the Addictions Intervention Association, and executive director of the Peel Addiction 
Assessment and Referral Centre in Brampton, Ontario, has taken a term position as treatment director with the 
National Drug Commission of Bermuda. The job started Oct. 1 and ends next spring.<P>
<H3>Colin Mangham goes west</H3>
Colin Mangham, formerly with Dalhousie University in Nova Scotia, has been hired as director of the new BC 
Prevention Resource Service. The service replaces the former BC Prevention Resource Centre and will expand 
BCPRC's mandate to include seniors and drug use, as well as tobacco. CCSA has been asked to help create 
an Internet presence for the service.<P>
<H3>Big-city police chiefs pick treatment over prisons</H3>
An article in the <I>RCMP Gazette</I> (Vol. 58, No. 7 and 8, 1996) says a majority of US police chiefs 
regard drug abuse as the most serious crime problem in their community and call for major changes in 
approaches to reducing drug use. In a 1995 survey, 60% of the chiefs said law enforcement efforts have been 
unsuccessful. However, they overwhelmingly rejected decriminalization of drugs as an alternative measure.<P>
Two-thirds of large-city chiefs said it is a step in the wrong direction to shift federal funds from drug prevention 
and treatment programs to law enforcement and prison construction. The majority said treatment programs for 
offenders are hard to find in their communities. <P>
<I>Contact the Police Foundation, 1001-22nd Street NW, Washington, DC 20037. Tel.: (202) 833-
1460; fax (202) 659-9149.</I><P><I>
</I><H3>Yukon finds formula for cost-recovered training</H3>
Some innovative thinking by a small team of prevention consultants with Alcohol and Drug Services (ADS) in 
Whitehorse resulted in three days of professional development training for nine ADS staff members, as well as 
the creation of a new network of allied professionals committed to community mobilization-all at no cost to 
ADS.  <P>
The staff at ADS wanted to take the training in Prevention and Community Mobilization offered by the Alberta 
Alcohol and Drug Abuse Commission (AADAC), but couldn't afford it. So they organized a three-day 
workshop by AADAC in September and opened it up to allied professionals, including people from justice and 
law enforcement, who paid $95 each to attend. Nine ADS staff and 31 allied professionals took the training. 
<P>
Addictions prevention consultant Jocelyn Gauthier said ADS not only recovered more than the cost of training, 
but they also built a network of people interested in community mobilization. By keeping the event small and 
making it a workshop rather than a conferee, they were able to handle the administrative chores without extra 
staff.<P>
<H3>meetings etcetera</H3>
Nov. 13-15.  New Directions in Public Health: From Reality to Opportunity, 47th Annual Conference of the 
Ontario Public Health Association, Toronto<P>
Nov. 14-16 Coming Together to Meet the Challenges of FAS/NAS:  Identifying Issues and Finding Solutions, 
Interprofessional Continuing Education Conference, Vancouver  <P>
Nov. 19-20 Opening Eyes, a Drug Awareness Week Alcohol Policy Forum for people interested in community 
health and safety, Nepean, Ontario<P>
March 23-27, 1997 4th International Conference on the Reduction of Drug-Related Harm, Paris<P>
You'll find more information about these and other events at CCSA's web site, <A HREF="calendar.htm">Calendar of Events.</A> 
<P><P><P><P>
<HR>
<FONT COLOR="0000FF"><H1>Action News, Vol. VII No. 1, 1996</H1></FONT>

<H2>New survey results paint a clear picture of rising illicit drug use by North American youth</H2>
<FONT SIZE=4>Figures for 1993-95 show the first upsurge in adolescent drug use–including heroin–in more than a decade. No one knows why for sure, but shifting government priorities could be part of the answer.</FONT><P>
The good news is that illicit drug use by youth in Canada and the US is still well below levels recorded in the late 1970s and early '80s. It was these soaring rates that prompted the US to declare a "war on drugs", and Canada to launch Canada's Drug Strategy in the mid-1980s.<P>
We may never know with any certainty what role these well-funded efforts played in the reduction of drug use that followed; there are too many confounding factors. But we do know–and here's the bad news–that drug use is starting to trend upwards again, at a time when political commitment to the areas of prevention, education and treatment is gradually evaporating. Here is some recent evidence of rising drug use:<P>
<UL>
<LI>The latest edition of The Ontario Student Drug Use Survey, which has been carried out every two years since 1977 by the Addiction Research Foundation (ARF), shows that between 1993 and 1995, past-year use of eight of 20 drugs increased significantly, while no drug declined in use. Attitudes and beliefs about drug use, particularly marijuana, became more liberal in this period.
<LI>Drugs whose use increased significantly included cannabis (12.7% to 22.7%), glue (1.6% to 2.4%), methamphetamine ("speed") (2% to 4.6%), hallucinogens other than LSD or PCP (3.1% to 7.6%), PCP (0.6% to 1.7%), cocaine (1.5% to 2.4%), and ecstasy (0.6% to 1.8%)
<LI>The ARF survey also showed a disturbing increase in heroin use by 9th graders, from 1.2% to 2.2%.
<LI>The survey also revealed that the percentage of students injecting drugs increased from 5.4% in 1993 to 8.8% in 1995.
<LI>In the US, Preliminary estimates from the 1995 National Household Survey on Drug Abuse, released in August, show that the percentage of adolescents (12-17 years old) using drugs increased between 1994 and 1995, continuing a trend that began in 1993. The rate in 1995 (10.9%) was twice that of 1992.
<LI>Significant increases in past-month marijuana use (from 6% to 8.2%), cocaine use (from 0.3% to 0.8%), and hallucinogen use (from 1.1% to 1.7%) were recorded between 1994 and 1995.
</UL>
<H3>Perceived risk is less</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Another US report, the 21st Annual Monitoring the Future Study, showed similar results for 8th, 10th, and 12th graders, but added heroin and stimulants to the list of drugs whose use is growing. As well, the perception of risk connected with drug use has dropped and the perceived availability of drugs has increased.
<LI>Preliminary estimates from the US Drug Abuse Warning Network (DAWN), released in August, show increases in marijuana/hashish-related hospital emergencies among those 12 to 17 years old, and 35 and older, between 1994 and 1995.
</UL>
US authorities are bracing for more bad news about marijuana. The 1995 Household Survey notes that "the decrease in prevalence of marijuana use that occurred in the 1980s did not begin until several years after the peak in incidence (initiation) estimates. This suggests that unless there are changes in the factors that influence drug use behaviours, we should not expect decreases in prevalence to occur soon, since incidence was still rising in 1994."<P>
A final sobering note: "The recent upturn in illicit drug use . . .has important implications for substance abuse prevention and treatment efforts. In terms of prevention, there is an obvious need to focus immediate attention on children and adolescents. In the long run, the increasing proportion of young people using illicit drugs will probably result in continuing pressure on the substance abuse treatment system in future years, as many new drug users progress to addiction and require intervention."<P>
For a more detailed look at these surveys, go to <A HREF="/youtstat.htm">Update on Youth and Substance Abuse</A> at CCSA's web site.  <P><P>
<H2>news and events</H2><P>
<H3>Canadian drug policy under House scrutiny</H3>
The House of Commons Standing Committee on Health will focus on demand reduction when it begins its 
review of substance abuse policies in October. The Committee will look at education, prevention, treatment and 
rehabilitation, and does not plan to re-open the debate on supply reduction that marked the lengthy passage of 
Bill C-8 (the Controlled Drugs and Substances Act) through Parliament.<P>
The Committee will examine the impact of legal and illegal drugs on the social behaviour and physical health of 
Canadians, and will assess demand reduction measures implemented under Canada's Drug Strategy over 
nearly 10 years. It will then make appropriate recommendations on future policy directions no later than June, 
1997.<P>
<I>For more information, contact the Clerk of the Health Committee, 6th floor, 180 Wellington St., 
Ottawa, ON K1A 0A6; tel. 613-992-1775, fax 613-996-1626.</I><P>
Would you like to read <A HREF="/presentn.htm">CCSA's submission</A> to the Standing Committee?
<P><P>


<H3>CACP asks Ottawa for renewed commitment</H3>
The Canadian Association of Chiefs of Police has strongly urged the Government of Canada to renew its 
commitment to a "coordinated and balanced drug strategy with appropriate resources" to deal with drug 
trafficking and money laundering "in a collaborative fashion with health, enforcement, prevention and treatment 
programs". The message was contained in a resolution passed at the CACP's annual general meeting in Ottawa 
in August.<P>
In another resolution, the CACP objected to the growing of low-THC hemp "without appropriate regulations, 
monitoring systems, security and enforcement procedures being implemented by Health and Welfare 
Canada".<P>
<I>For more information, write CACP, 130 Albert St., Suite 1710, Ottawa, ON  K1P 5G4 Tel 613-233-
1106, fax 613-233-6960</I><P><P>
<H3>CRTC eases restrictions on broadcast alcohol ads</H3>
The Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission is proposing to do away with the requirement for pre-clearance of scripts advertising alcoholic beverages. Instead, the CRTC will "encourage" the broadcast industry to establish its own mechanisms for weeding out ads that don't meet the CRTC's advertising code.<P>
Another proposed change to CRTC regulations is the lifting of restrictions on who may advertise alcoholic beverages. Current rules prohibit advertising by anyone other than brewers, distillers, wineries and cider-houses. Now any retailer could advertise as long as they follow the CRTC's code. <P>
The CRTC's proposed amendments would see its advertising code incorporated into the regulations, but there is no explanation of how the code will be enforced once the CRTC ends its involvement with the pre-clearance process. As well, an interpretation section has been written, but this will not be part of the code itself. The Canadian Association of Broadcasters, which would take over responsibility for pre-clearance, had recommended that the interpretation section be dropped altogether.<P>
The CRTC expressed the "expectation" that broadcasters would expand their efforts to inform the public about alcohol-related problems and will require the industry to report annually on these efforts.<P>
However, it is not clear what objective test the CRTC will use to determine whether the public has been presented with a balanced view. The CRTC rejected the notion of specifying a ratio of counter-advertising to brand promotion.<P>
<I>The CRTC wants reaction to Public Notice CRTC 1996-108 by Oct. 1. Write the Secretary-General, CRTC, Ottawa, ON  K1A 0N2 Tel. 819-997-0313, fax 819-994-0218</I><P>
Read <A HREF="anltcrtc.htm">CCSA's response</A> to the new CRTC regulations.
<P><P>
<H3>meetings and cetera</H3>
<B>Oct. 18-20</B>–<I>The Art of Addiction Medicine</I>, 8th annual meeting of the Canadian Medical Society on Alcohol and Other Drugs, Toronto<P>
<B>Oct. 30-Nov. 2</B>–<I>We're Making Smoking History,</I> 2nd National Conference on Tobacco or Health, Ottawa<P>
<B>Nov. 6-9</B>–<I>The Social and Political Aspects of Information</I>, 18th annual conference of Substance Abuse Librarians and Information Specialists (SALIS), Vancouver<P>
<B>March 23-27, 1997</B>–8th International Conference on the Reduction of Drug-Related Harm, Paris<P><P>
<B>You'll find more information about these and other events at <A HREF="/calendar.htm">CCSA's web site, Calendar of Events.</A></B><P><P><P>

<FONT COLOR="000077"><I>Action News</I> is written and assembled by Richard Garlick, CCSA Communications, with the indispensable help of Margo Hawley and Susan Rosidi of the National Clearinghouse on Substance Abuse. Contributions to our news&amp events page are more than welcome. Please write us: Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse, 75 Albert St., Suite 300, Ottawa, ON K1P 5E7. Tel. 613-235-4048, ext. 230, fax 613-235-8101, e-mail <A HREF="mailto:rgarlick@ccsa.ca">rgarlick@ccsa.ca</A><P></FONT><P>
