<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Alcohol and Drug Use: Results from the 1993 General Social Survey</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<H1>Alcohol and Drug Use: Results from 
the 1993 General Social Survey</H1>
<H3>Report prepared for the Studies Unit, Health 
Promotion Directorate, Health Canada, January 1995</H3>
<B>by Eric W. Single, Joan M. Brewster, Patricia MacNeil, Jeffrey Hatcher, and Catherine 
Trainor</B><P><B>
</B><HR>
<H4>Highlights</H4>
<UL>
<LI>The proportion of Canadians who report drinking in the past twelve months decreased from 79.0% 
in the 1991 General Social Survey to 74.4% in 1993.  Levels of use among drinkers also continues to 
decline in Canada.  The portrait of the Canadian who is most likely to drink and drink heavily is that of a 
young adult male who is not married, relatively well-off, speaks English or French at home and rarely or 
never attends religious services.  Residents of the Prairies and British Columbia tend to drink less often 
and in lower quantities than other Canadians, but community size accounts for little variation in rates of 
drinking.
<LI>In a multivariate analysis of the combined impact of socio-demographic factors on drinking and 
drinking levels, it is found that the frequency of religious attendance and age are the strongest predictors 
of current drinking.  Language spoken at home, gender, income adequacy, education and employment 
status are also significantly related to drinking status.  Gender is the strongest predictor of volume of 
alcohol consumption.  The higher volume of consumption by males is not accounted for by other variables 
in the analysis.  The second strongest predictor of volume of consumption is religious attendance, 
followed by age, marital status and employment status.
<LI>Slightly less than one in ten Canadian drinkers (9.2%) report that drinking has had an adverse effect 
on their social life, physical health, happiness, home life or marriage, work, or finances in the past year.  
The most commonly reported problems were deleterious effects on physical health (5.1%), and effects on 
financial position (4.7%).  Approximately one in eight Canadian drinkers (12.9%) drove a car within an 
hour after consuming two or more drinks in the past year.
<LI>The portrait of the individual most likely to report a drinking problem is that of a young adult male, 
single or divorced, who is unemployed and/or has relatively low income.  In a multivariate analysis, age, 
marital status, gender, religious attendance and employment status are the strongest predictors of the 
likelihood that the individual has a problem with his or her drinking.
<LI>The number of heavy drinking occasions is a stronger predictor of drinking problems than overall 
level of consumption.  The likelihood of experiencing a drinking problem is greater for a moderate level 
drinker who occasionally drinks immoderately than for a high volume drinker who rarely or never 
consumes immoderately.
<LI>More than two of every five Canadians (43.9%) report that they have experienced some problem due 
to other people's drinking.  The problems most commonly reported are being disturbed by loud parties or 
other behaviour (23.8%), being insulted or humiliated by someone who had been drinking (20.9%), and 
having a serious argument or quarrel as a result of someone's drinking (15.6%).  The likelihood of 
reporting a problem as the result of someone else's drinking is approximately the same for men (45.5%) 
and women (42.5%).
<LI>With regard to use of licit drugs, 69.8% of Canadians report using aspirin in the month prior to the 
survey, 8.2% codeine, Demerol or morphine, 4.2% sleeping pills, 3.8% tranquilizers, 2.5% anti-
depressants and 0.6% diet pills.  Women are more likely than men to use aspirin.  The use of aspirin is 
also associated with higher income and education.  Women and the elderly are more likely to use 
tranquilizers, sleeping pills and anti-depressants.  The use of codeine, Demerol or morphine is particularly 
high among anglophone Canadians and among those who are not working due to illness.  In contrast to 
these pain killers, francophone Canadians are more likely to use tranquilizers and sleeping pills.
<LI>The most prevalent illicit drug is cannabis.  In 1993, 4.2% of Canadians report using marijuana in 
the past year, 0.3% report using cocaine, and 0.3% report using heroin, LSD, or speed.  The use of 
cannabis and other illicit drugs is strongly associated with being young, male and single.  British 
Columbians have the highest rates of illicit drug use.
<LI>A multivariate analysis of the combined impact of socio-demographic factors on cannabis use 
confirmed the findings that young males who are relatively unattached (i.e., single and not closely tied to 
religion) are the most likely to use cannabis.  The high rate of cannabis use in British Columbia is partly 
attenuated by taking socio-demographic factors into consideration.  The relatively high rate of cannabis 
use in Québec is largely explained by socio-demographic differences -- once these factors are taken into 
account, the predicted rate of cannabis use in Québec is the same as the national average.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
All correspondence regarding this analysis should be directed to Dr. Single at Canadian Centre on 
Substance Abuse, 100 College Street, Suite 511, Toronto, ON Canada M5G 1L5.  The CCSA Policy and 
Research Unit is affiliated with the Centre for Health Promotion at the University of Toronto.  Funding for 
the analysis reported in this article was provided by the Studies Unit, Health Promotion Directorate, 
Health Canada.<P>
For a copy of the full publication, contact CCSA Books, Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse, 112 Kent 
St., Suite 480, Ottawa, ON Canada  K1P 5P2.<P>
<HR>
