http://www.ccsa.ca:80/statsus.htm 199.126.12.34 19961231213628 text/html 14828
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 31-Dec-96 21:46:40 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 22-Nov-96 17:52:48 GMT
Content-length: 14643
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Community Epidemiology Work Group, National Institutes of Health</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY>
<H3>Epidemiologic Trends in Drug Abuse</H3>
<H1>COMMUNITY EPIDEMIOLOGY 
WORK GROUP</H1>
<H2>National Institutes of Health</H2>
<H4>December 1994</H4>
<HR>
Division of Epidemiology and Prevention Research<BR>
National Institute on Drug Abuse<BR>
5600 Fishers Lane<BR>
Rockville, Maryland 20857<P>
The Community Epidemiology Work Group (CEWG) is a network of researchers from major metropolitan 
areas of the United States and from selected foreign countries.  The CEWG meets semiannually with the 
primary objective of providing ongoing community-level public health surveillance of drug use and abuse, 
principally through collection and analysis of epidemiologic and ethnographic research data.  Through this 
program, the CEWG provides current descriptive and analytical information regarding the nature and 
patterns of drug abuse, emerging trends, and characteristics of vulnerable populations.<P>
All material in this volume is in the public domain and may be reproduced or copied without permission from 
the Institute or the authors.  Citation of the source is appreciated.  The data in Volume I (this volume) of this 
publication were extracted from 19 city drug abuse indicator trend reports whose full edited text appear in 
Volume II.  Volume II also contains the full edited text of reports on specialized topics and international 
reports.<P>
<HR>
<H1>Highlights</H1>
<H3>COCAINE AND CRACK</H3>
<B>Cocaine (including crack) remains the Nation's most serious drug problem.  
However, most indicator data are corroborating previous ethnographic observations: 
the epidemic appears to be leveling off or decreasing in many areas.</B><P>
Partial 1994 mortality figures were available in 10 CEWG cities:  compared with 1993 data, 
cocaine involvement in deaths appears level or declining in 7 of those cities and increasing in 
3.<P>
<A HREF="/totaled.gif">Similarly, cocaine ED rates declined or were stable between 1992 and 1993 in 13 of the 18 
CEWG cities in DAWN.</A>  However, cocaine remains the most frequently reported nonalcohol 
illicit drug ED mention in all but three CEWG cities in DAWN:  heroin is more frequently 
mentioned in Newark and San Francisco, and the two drugs are mentioned approximately equally 
in Seattle.  <A HREF="/cocained.gif">The highest population-based rates during 1993 occurred in New York, Detroit, 
Philadelphia, and Newark, and the lowest rate occurred in Minneapolis/St. Paul.</A>  Nationally, 
cocaine vastly outnumbered heroin in mentions per 100,000 population (53.8 versus 27.5).  In 
several CEWG cities, the cocaine-to-heroin ratios were strikingly high:  Atlanta (17:1), Miami 
(11:1), and New Orleans (8:1).<P>
Like the mortality and emergency indicators, rates of cocaine use among arrestees between 1992 
and 1993 were generally unchanged or decreased.<P>
In 10 of the 17 CEWG areas where treatment data were available, cocaine (including crack) as 
the primary drug of abuse accounts for the largest proportions of admissions (excluding alcohol-
only, but including alcohol-in-combination).  <P>
In all reporting cities, the vast majority of cocaine admissions report smoking the drug.  Mode of 
administration, however, is often correlated with gender, race/ethnicity, age, and other 
demographics.  Additionally, multisubstance use is often the norm, rather than the exception.<P>
Observational and indicator data suggest a generally aging population of cocaine users in most 
cities. For example, the largest populations comprising deaths, ED mentions, and treatment 
admissions fall into the oldest age groups.  Youth involvement remains confined largely to street 
sales, often involving gangs. <P>
Males generally continue to dominate the mortality, emergency, and treatment data;  females, 
however, account for the majority of cocaine admissions in Newark, Los Angeles, and San Diego, 
and they predominate at most arrestee urinalysis sites.  <P>
Cocaine remains readily available in all CEWG areas at both the distribution and street levels.  
Prices were either stable or down in virtually all areas.  The price of powdered cocaine ranges 
widely both within and across CEWG sites: the lowest gram prices are reported in Seattle ($30) 
Chicago ($35), and St. Louis ($36), and the highest prices are reported in New Orleans and 
Honolulu ($125 each) and Washington, DC ($120).  Crack prices also vary widely within and 
across CEWG cities.  In Detroit, for example, a rock of crack can range from $5 to $50.  Of cities 
that reported ounce prices, Los Angeles had the lowest prices ($425) and St. Louis had the 
highest ($1,500).<P>
<P>
<H3>HEROIN</H3>
<B>Negative consequences of heroin use continue to increase in most areas.  In 
several areas, ethnographic and epidemiologic sources suggest a new cohort of young 
users.</B><P>
Heroin-related mortality increased in seven of the nine areas where partial-1994 data were 
available.  <A HREF="/heroined.gif">Similarly, heroin ED rates increased between 1992 and 1993 in 13 of the 18 CEWG 
cities in DAWN;</A> they were relatively level in 2 cities (Phoenix and St. Louis); and they declined 
slightly in 2 cities (New Orleans and Washington, DC).  Only in San Diego did they decline 
sharply (by 28 percent).  Newark and San Francisco, followed by New York and Seattle, had the 
highest rates per 100,000 population in 1993.<P>
These increased consequences of heroin use may be the result of relatively low prices and high 
purity and availability of white heroin (mostly from Southeast and Southwest Asia and (more 
recently) from Colombia) in several CEWG areas, particularly in most northeastern cities and 
some midwestern areas (such as Chicago).  Lower purity black tar and brown heroin (from 
Mexico), however, still predominate in western areas.  But most indicators show increases even in 
those areas (except for DAWN data in San Diego).<P>
Increased consequences, however, are not yet reflected in arrestee use:  opiate-positive urinalyses 
remained largely unchanged from 1992 to 1993.<P>
With increased purity levels, intranasal use has continued to replace injection in many areas, such 
as Newark, New York City, Chicago, and Detroit.  Injection, however, remains the primary route 
of administration in the West.  Smoking is reported in some areas (such as Atlanta, Chicago, 
Minneapolis/St. Paul), especially among younger users, and often in combination or sequentially 
with crack.   For example, "primos" or "flamethrowers" (mixtures of heroin, cocaine, and tobacco 
that are smoked) are common in Chicago and among young African-American users in St. Louis.  
Other practices involving smoking crack and heroin include "chasing the dragon" (sequential use), 
as reported in Chicago and Miami, and "speedballing" (simultaneous use), as reported in Chicago 
(in other areas, "speedballing" refers to simultaneous injection). <P>
Along with the increased intranasal use and smoking, ethnographic observations and treatment 
demographics in several areas suggest that young people are increasingly initiating heroin use.  In 
Chicago, for example, admissions fall into a bimodal distribution of younger inhalers and older 
injectors.  Similarly, the 18-25 age group constitutes 10 percent or more of heroin admissions in 
Boston, Minneapolis/St. Paul, Newark, New York City, and St. Louis.  Ethnographic data also 
indicate a new cohort of young users in Atlanta, Chicago, Miami, New Orleans, New York City, 
St. Louis, San Francisco, and Washington, DC.<P>
Males predominate in heroin mortality and treatment figures.  Women, however, are increasingly 
entering treatment for opiate abuse in many areas.  The proportion of women is particularly high in 
Newark, San Diego, and Minneapolis/St. Paul.<P>
Whites are predominant in heroin mortality figures, but treatment data indicate more diverse 
racial/ethnic distributions in different areas of the country.  Multiple ethnic groups are mentioned 
as major traffickers and distributors in an increasing number of CEWG areas, such as New York 
City, Boston, Detroit, Texas, and the Pacific Northwest.  In New York City, especially, rarely 
have so many groups been involved in the heroin trade.<P>
<P>
<H3>MARIJUANA</H3>
<B>Qualitative and quantitative data continue to indicate increasing marijuana use, 
especially among adolescents, across the country.</B><P>
<A HREF="/marijuan.gif">Marijuana ED mentions per 100,000 population increased in 13 of the 18 CEWG cities in DAWN 
between 1992 and 1993.</A>  The largest increases occurred in Detroit and Washington, DC.  Rates 
were highest in Detroit, Washington, DC, New Orleans, and Philadelphia; St. Louis had the lowest 
rate. <P>
Marijuana was reported as the primary drug of abuse by sizable proportions of non-alcohol 
treatment admissions in Honolulu, New Orleans, Seattle, and Texas. The proportions increased 
recently in Chicago, Minneapolis/St. Paul, New Orleans, New York City, St. Louis, Seattle, and 
Texas.  Young males constitute the majority of primary marijuana admissions in all areas.  <P>
Increased use by juveniles is especially evident in arrestee urinalysis:  juvenile marijuana rates 
generally increased between 1992 and 1993, particularly in St. Louis, San Antonio, and 
Washington, DC.  Marijuana now outranks cocaine for juveniles at every DUF site; for adult 
arrestees, it has now surpassed cocaine in Detroit, Phoenix, San Antonio, and San Diego.<P>
The "blunt" phenomenon (gutted cigars refilled with marijuana) continues to spread to diverse 
parts of the country, including Chicago, Minneapolis/St. Paul, New York City, Philadelphia, San 
Francisco, Texas, and Washington, DC.  In many cities, blunts involve other drugs, such as crack, 
PCP, or even embalming fluid.  Blunts are sold on the street in some areas; in other areas, users 
prefer to prepare their own mixtures.<P>
Large-scale domestic indoor growing operations are becoming increasingly problematic, 
contributing to both increased potency and supplies.<P>
<P>
<H3>STIMULANTS</H3>
<B>Abuse of stimulants, especially methamphetamine, is generally a regional 
phenomenon.  The most affected areas are in the West.  To a lesser extent, some rural 
midwestern and southeastern areas also have problems with abuse and trafficking.  
The Northeast remains largely unaffected.</B><P>
Methamphetamine-related mortality has increased in San Diego, Honolulu, Phoenix, and San 
Francisco; it is stable in Seattle (averaging one death per year).<P>
Methamphetamine has increased as a primary drug of abuse among treatment admissions in San 
Diego (where it is the foremost problem) and Honolulu (where it ranks a close second to 
marijuana).  Similarly, amphetamine/methamphetamine detections continue to increase among San 
Diego adult arrestees.<P>
Injection is the most common route of administration among methamphetamine admissions in San 
Francisco, while intranasal use and smoking are more common in Los Angeles and San 
Diego.<P>
Much of the methamphetamine reported in different areas (for example, Atlanta and New 
Orleans) is transported from Los Angeles or Texas by Mexican trafficking organizations, who also 
broker in precursor chemicals.  Clandestine labs, however, operate in other areas, such as 
Phoenix, Florida, and Missouri.  Availability and abuse of 3,4-methylene dioxymethamphetamine 
(MDMA or "ecstasy") is reported in Atlanta, Dallas, Honolulu, Miami, St. Louis, San Francisco, 
and Texas.<P>
The spread of methcathinone ("cat") labs appears centralized in Michigan, Wisconsin, and Indiana.  
The drug has been reported in Detroit treatment programs.<P>
<P>
<H3>HALLUCINOGENS</H3>
Qualitative data, supported by ED data, indicate increased use of <A HREF="/lsder.gif">LSD (possibly associated with 
the rave phenomenon)</A> and <A HREF="/pcper.gif">PCP (possibly associated with the blunt phenomenon)</A> among youth in 
many CEWG areas.<P>
Datura stramonium ("jimsonweed," also known as "locoweed" or "stinkweed") is a poisonous 
hallucinogenic plant the use of which may be increasing among young people in the Northeast 
(particularly New York and New Jersey), Canada, and areas of Texas.  Two deaths and 
numerous emergency department episodes were reported in El Paso, and about a dozen youth 
from a New Jersey high school were rushed to emergency departments after chewing the 
seeds.<P>
Qualitative information in Philadelphia indicates that increased use of phencyclidine (PCP) is 
associated with the growing use of blunts.  PCP is also easily obtained in most other CEWG 
areas. It is available in a variety of forms:  sprinkled on marijuana, mint leaves, or tobacco; as a 
liquid; or dipped and dried onto cigarettes.  <P>
Ethnographic, school, and hotline data indicate that lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD) is reemerging 
as a drug of abuse <P>
among youth in several cities, including Atlanta, Detroit, Miami, and San Francisco.  It is 
frequently reported in connection with the "rave" scene.  The drug is readily available in most 
CEWG areas, and prices are declining in several.  The western part of the country appears to be 
a major source area for several cities, including Atlanta, New Orleans, and St. Louis.<P>
Two other hallucinogens increasingly used as "club drugs" are ketamine ("Special K"), which is 
reported in Miami and St. Louis, and 4-bromo-2,5-dimethoxyphenylalamine ("nexus"), which is 
reported in Atlanta.<P>
Hallucinogens are rarely reported as the primary substance of abuse by treatment admissions.  In 
many cities, however, they are notable secondary and tertiary drugs among younger 
admissions.<P>
<P>
<H3>OTHER DRUGS</H3>
Various cough and cold medications, in both prescription and nonprescription form, are reportedly 
overutilized, sold on the streets, or mentioned by treatment admissions in Minneapolis/St. Paul, 
Houston, Newark, and Phoenix.  Substances mentioned include dextromethorphan (DXN, a 
synthetic nonopioid), various forms of guaifenesin (Robitussin, known in Newark as "robo"), 
butorphanol tartrate (Stadol), and nalbuphine hydrochloride (Nubain).<P>
Abuse of inhalants and anabolic steroids is reported as a problem in Texas.<P>
<HR>
