<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Standing Committee on Health - Substance Abuse Policy Review</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>House of Commons</H3>
<H2>Standing Committee on Health</H2>
<H1>Substance Abuse Policy Review</H1>
<HR>
The Standing Committee on Health is beginning a review of Policies on the Misuse and Abuse of 
Substances.  The review will commence October 1996, to be completed in June 1997.  The following is 
taken from a letter sent to the CCSA by the Clerk of the Committee:<P>
"As you may be aware, the federal initiative called Canada's Drug Strategy was launched in 1987 and 
renewed in 1992.  In May, 1996, pursuant to a recommendation from the Sub-Committee that had studied 
Bill C-7 (now C-8) (Controlled Drugs and Substances Act), the Minister of Health encouraged the Health 
Committee to review Canada's drug policy.  The Minister suggested that the review focus on the demand 
reduction rather than the supply reduction side of the existing Drug Strategy. This demand reduction 
component falling within the broader "harm reduction" concept focused on education, prevention, 
treatment and rehabilitation.<P>
"At a recent meeting of the Health Committee, Members agreed on the following <B>Terms of 
Reference:</B><P>
<OL>
<LI>To receive evidence about the harmful impact of misuse and abuse of legal and illegal drugs on the 
social behaviour and physical health of Canadians;
<LI>To identify the relevance of variables such as age, sex, ethnicity, socio-economic status and 
geographic area on the demand for and effect of such substances;
<LI>To examine effective measures for reducing the demand for and use of such substances through 
education, prevention, treatment, and rehabilitation;
<LI>To make appropriate recommendations on future policy actions to reduce the demand for such 
substances.
</OL>
"The Committee plans to study substances that have the potential to cause harm to individuals when 
abused or misused, including legal drugs such as those contained in alcoholic beverages, tobacco products, 
solvents and prescription drugs as well as illegal drugs such as cannabis, heroin and LSD.<P>
"The Committee has decided that the study will be divided into a number of segments as follows:<P>
<UL>
<LI>overview of substance abuse policy issues,
<LI>specifics about relevant substances,
<LI>focus on affected individuals, families and communities,
<LI>overview of international policy and program experience,
<LI>assessment of provincial, territorial and municipal policy, programs and services,
<LI>and a final segment for filling any gaps in knowledge identified over the course of the study.
</UL>
"The Overview segment will focus on questions about the current Canadian system and will assess 
changes since the 1969 to 1973 review by the LeDain Commission of Inquiry into the Non-medical Use of 
Drugs as well as an identification of what substances are abused most frequently and are most harmful 
when used singly or in combination. We are hoping to obtain from witnesses an outline of the education, 
prevention, treatment and rehabilitation efforts that have been effective in the almost ten years of Canada's 
Drug Strategy, as well as an assessment of those efforts that have not worked.<P>
"We anticipate that the hearings on this study will commence in early October, and that the Overview 
segment of the hearings will run for the first two weeks in October."<P>
For further information, contact the Clerk of the Committee at (613) 992-1775; fax: (613) 996-1626, c/o 
Standing Committee on Health, 6th Floor, 180 Wellington Street, Ottawa, ON K1A 0A6.<P>
The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse will be presenting to the Committee early in the review, and 
information related to the progress of the Committee will be posted to our Web site, as it becomes 
available.<P>
<HR>
