<CENTER><H1><A NAME = exec></A>Executive Summary</H1></CENTER>
Substance abuse is one of Canada's most serious health and social problems. 
In an economic cost study of the year 1992, released by the Canadian Centre 
on Substance Abuse in June, 1996, alcohol, tobacco and illicit drug abuse 
accounted for 21% of total deaths in Canada, and 23% of years of potential life 
lost.<P>
Hospitalizations due to substance abuse constituted 8% of total hospitalizations 
and 10% of the total days spent in hospital for any cause.<P>
The CCSA estimated that substance abuse cost the Canadian economy more 
than $18.4 billion in 1992. This represents $649 per capita, or about 2.7% of the 
total Gross Domestic Product. <P>
<H2><A NAME = rising></A>Rising drug use<P></H2>
After more than a decade of decline, there are disturbing indications that illicit 
drug use is on the rise again. The proportion of Canadians who report using 
cannabis in the past year increased from 4.2% in 1993 to 7.4% in 1994. 
Increased cannabis use is particularly marked among youth and young adults. 
<P>
Cocaine use increased from 0.3% in 1993 to 0.7% in 1994, and the proportion 
of people who report using LSD, heroin or speed in the prior year increased 
from 0.3% in 1993 to 1.1% in 1994.<P>
The Addiction Research Foundation of Ontario has also reported significantly 
higher rates of smoking and drinking among youth in Grades 7, 9, 11, and 13 
between 1993 and 1995.<P>
<H2><A NAME = end></A>The end of Canada's Drug 
Strategy<P></H2>
Canada's Drug Strategy, launched in 1987 and renewed in 1992, is now due to 
sunset on March 31, 1997. Health programming developed under the Strategy 
is being merged with many other health and social issues under the label of 
population health. It is not clear what priority drug and alcohol programs will be 
given within this new framework, or what level of funding they will receive. 
Current indications are that they will be severely cut back.<P>
The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse, created by an Act of Parliament to 
provide a national focus for substance abuse issues, will cease to exist on 
March 31, 1997, if no new commitment of funding is made in the months to 
come. The Standing Committee on Health is scheduled to make its report three 
months after Canada's Drug Strategy sunsets and the Centre closes its 
doors.<P>
The CCSA has occupied a unique position in the substance abuse field as a 
multi-disciplinary bridge between the private and public sectors, programmers 
and policy-makers, theorists and practitioners, epidemiologists and economists, 
information providers and consumers, Native researchers and mainstream 
academics, and prevention specialists and police. The CCSA has been 
particularly well supported by the justice and enforcement community, and 
especially by the Office of the Solicitor General and the RCMP.<P>
CCSA's role has become even more essential since the systematic dismantling 
of independent provincial/territorial drug and alcohol agencies began several 
years ago. Only three of these now remain in Canada. The resulting void in 
knowledge and expert counsel has created a growing demand for CCSA's many 
information products and services such as the Canadian Profile, the National 
Clearinghouse on Substance Abuse, and CCSA's national FAS/FAE information 
service.<P>
The CCSA has tried to cope with severe cuts to its funding by relying more and 
more on the World Wide Web to get information out, and by providing its 
products and services on a cost-recovery basis. However, many clients cannot 
pay and the CCSA must continue to rely at least to some degree on public 
funding.<P>
<H2><A NAME = federal></A>Federal leadership and 
commitment<P></H2>
The CCSA is asking the Standing Committee on Health to seek a strong re-
affirmation of the Government of Canada's leadership and commitment on the 
critical issues of substance abuse. There is a pressing need to assure the 
people of Canada that the federal government will not neglect its responsibility 
to protect the health and well-being of our most vulnerable citizens, including 
our children.<P>
We ask the Committee to urge Health Canada to dispel the confusion that 
exists around the population health approach and to state clearly to Canadians 
that their long-standing confidence in the preventive value of targeted drug and 
alcohol programs and policies is still justified.<P>
<CENTER><H1><A NAME = intro></A>Introduction and overview</H1></CENTER>
<H2><A NAME = about></A>About CCSA<P></H2>
CCSA was created by an Act of Parliament in August, 1988, to serve as a 
national focus for drug and alcohol issues in Canada. It has three broad 
goals:<P>
<UL>
<LI>to promote increased awareness by Canadians of issues related to alcohol and drug abuse;
<LI>to promote increased participation by Canadians in the reduction of harm associated with alcohol 
and drug abuse; and
<LI>to promote the use and effectiveness of programs of excellence relevant to alcohol and drug abuse.
</UL>
The Centre operates the National Clearinghouse on Substance Abuse which 
collects and disseminates information, compiles and maintains a variety of 
databases, and coordinates the Canadian Substance Abuse Information 
Network. CCSA also runs the Fetal Alcohol Syndrome Information Service with 
financial assistance from Health Canada and the Brewers Association of 
Canada. The Centre provides free access to substance abuse information and 
"hot links" to many other knowledge providers around the world through its site 
on the World Wide Web. It also publishes a variety of directories, statistical 
profiles, pamphlets, research and policy papers, and special reports.<P>
The Centre is in a unique position to bring a variety of partners together from 
the public and private sectors to pursue projects that would be impossible to do 
unilaterally. As well, with the disappearance of all but three independent 
provincial drug and alcohol agencies in recent years, the Centre is being called 
on more and more to provide expert advice and counsel to our provincial clients, 
and to coordinate a variety of cross-jurisdictional activities.<P>
The following examples illustrate some of CCSA's accomplishments in joint 
project initiation and coordination:<P>
<UL>
<LI>The Costs of Substance Abuse in Canada–a two-year study of the health, social and economic costs 
of substance abuse, involving the financial and/or in-kind participation of six provinces and two federal 
departments; published in June, 1996
<I><LI>Canadian Profile</I>–an annual compilation of statistics on alcohol, tobacco and illicit drug 
use, developed in partnership with the Addiction Research Foundation of Ontario with financial assistance 
from Health Canada
<LI>The Canadian Community Epidemiology Network on Drug Use (CCENDU)–monitoring of drug use 
trends in six Canadian cities, bringing together experts from several fields, including public health and 
enforcement
<LI>Health and Enforcement in Partnership (HEP)–a study of alternative approaches to drug 
enforcement, involving the Canadian Association of Chiefs of Police, the RCMP, and the office of the 
Solicitor General
<LI>Drug Awareness Week–national coordination of annual prevention and public education campaigns, 
involving a working group of drug awareness coordinators from all 12 provinces and territories
<LI>National Award Program–recognition of accomplishment in the substance abuse field with an annual 
award of excellence presented at Rideau Hall, and medallions of distinction presented in the provinces and 
territories
</UL>
<H2><A NAME = reviewing></A>Reviewing Canada's drug 
policy<P></H2>
Canada's most celebrated review of substance abuse policy, the LeDain 
Commission, spanned four years and generated several volumes of research 
and analysis. In some ways, this Committee has an easier job than LeDain's. By 
focusing exclusively on demand reduction strategies–prevention, education, 
treatment and rehabilitation–it may avoid some of the issues of law enforcement 
and supply reduction that split the ranks of the LeDain Commission.<P>
However, in another sense this Committee's job is actually more difficult than 
LeDain's. It will look at all psychoactive substances, licit and illicit, including 
alcohol and tobacco, and it must finish its work in only nine months. We 
commend the Committee for taking on this challenging mandate, and we are 
particularly pleased that Canada's two deadliest drugs–alcohol and tobacco–will 
be included in the review.<P>
It is important that we not allow the media and their love affair with illicit drug 
stories to dictate policy and to override issues related to smoking and drinking. 
To do so would be tantamount to looking down the wrong end of a telescope, 
and would seriously undermine the credibility of any group purporting to be 
conducting a serious study of substance abuse in this country.<P>
The LeDain Commission set the standard for every drug policy review that 
followed it, but in the end it failed to make a tangible impact on the drug problem 
itself. This was not the case with another substance abuse review in this country 
that began almost exactly 10 years ago. In December, 1986, the House of 
Commons Standing Committee on National Health and Welfare undertook a 
study of drug abuse in Canada, focusing initially on illegal drug use. At the 
insistence of witness after witness, the scope of the study soon expanded to 
encompass other forms of substance abuse, including the misuse of 
alcohol.<P>
<H2><A NAME = role></A>The role of the federal government 
</H2>
Across Canada, witnesses appearing before the Standing Committee called for 
a renewed role for the federal government in the area of alcohol and drug 
abuse. While acknowledging that health care, prevention services and 
educational programs fall under provincial jurisdiction, witnesses nonetheless 
saw the need for coordination and leadership at the federal level to ensure a 
balanced approach to tackling drug problems. The government was urged to 
"invest" in demand reduction measures that would complement existing efforts 
to contain the supply of drugs on the street.<P>
Through the development of appropriate funding and cost-sharing mechanisms, 
by providing coordination and leadership, by developing and disseminating 
model programs, and through improved legislation and enforcement, an active 
role for the federal government was suggested.<P>
On May 25, 1987, the Government of Canada announced a new "National Drug 
Strategy"–later Canada's Drug Strategy–involving a five-year commitment of 
additional funds amounting to $210 million to combat drug abuse. At that time, 
the federal government had been spending approximately $168 million a year 
on both supply and demand reduction programs.<P>
In 1992, Canada's Drug Strategy was renewed with additional funding and an 
expanded mandate that included Health Canada's existing Impaired Driving 
program. Total expenditures for the second five-year phase was set at $270 
million.<P>
The Strategy was a comprehensive societal response to a serious and complex 
problem, but it was deficient in one key area. It set no measurable goals for 
itself and therefore could not be evaluated in a meaningful way. If you ask if the 
Strategy was successful, most of us in the substance abuse field would 
probably say yes, but we can't prove it. Whatever measures this Committee 
recommends next June, top priority should be given to the setting of clearly 
defined targets by which these measures can be judged in the future.<P>
<H3>The future of CCSA</H3>
Included as part of the Strategy's budget for Phase I was a proposed $2 million 
annual expenditure to fund the operations of the Canadian Centre on 
Substance Abuse. It is worth noting that when the Centre's founding legislation 
came before Parliament, only one member rose to oppose it. The reason? The 
MP felt the Centre's ambitious goals could not be accomplished on a $2 million-
a-year budget. The legislation passed nonetheless with all-party support.<P>
Despite the injection of new money into Phase II of the Strategy, the Centre's 
allocation was incrementally reduced to a level of $1.4 million. Then, in April of 
this year, we learned that this figure was to be cut almost in half to $0.75 million 
for the 1996-97 fiscal year. CCSA was advised at the time that this would be the 
last year of funding with no further commitment for future years.<P>
<H2><A NAME = sunsetting></A>The "sunsetting" of Canada's Drug 
Strategy<P></H2>
By the time this Committee presents its recommendations in June, 1997, 
Canada's Drug Strategy will have sunset three months earlier, and unless there 
is a significant change in the current course of events, the Centre will have 
ceased to exist. As far as we have been able to determine, federal government 
expenditures on substance abuse will return to pre-1987 levels or worse. It is 
not at all clear what priority drug education and prevention will be given within 
the new and little understood population health framework.<P>
An outside observer might look at the direction this country is taking in its 
commitment to substance abuse prevention and conclude that we have 
successfully dealt with our problems and are ready to move on to other issues. 
Regrettably, as we will demonstrate elsewhere in this presentation, this is not 
the case.<P>
The same observer might be struck by the discrepancy between the billions of 
dollars collected every year in the form of federal alcohol and tobacco taxes, 
seized assets and proceeds of drug-related crime, and the comparatively 
minuscule amount the Government of Canada spends to reduce drug-related 
harm. As the government withdraws further from investment in demand 
reduction, the economics become even more skewed. The ounce of prevention 
that we fail to provide will take its toll in a ton of illness and death, health care 
costs, unsafe streets and crime-ridden communities, crowded courts and 
prisons, and a growing stain on Canada's international reputation.<P>
Canada has gone as far as public opinion and our overburdened justice system 
will tolerate on the supply reduction side. Bill C-8, the Controlled Drugs and 
Substance Act gives police unprecedented powers to stop the flow of drugs into 
our communities. But the police are the first to admit they cannot continue to 
plug the leaking dam of enforcement if more–much more–is not done to reduce 
demand. They are pleading with us to send in the reinforcements.<P>
<H2><A NAME = reaffirm></A>Re-affirming the need for 
leadership<P></H2>
We are confident this Committee will play a pivotal role in rekindling Canadian 
efforts to combat substance abuse. Our hope is that it will re-affirm the need for 
leadership and commitment by the Government of Canada in this area, and 
recommend continued investment in prevention, education and treatment. We 
are not merely asking for the automatic re-instatement of Canada's Drug 
Strategy. It may be that the specific initiatives of the Strategy have outlived their 
usefulness. However, in their absence, we hope and trust that this Committee 
will recommend equally bold and innovative measures to combat a growing 
problem.<P>
<CENTER><H1><A NAME = nature></A>Nature, extent and consequences of 
substance use</H1></CENTER>
<H2><A NAME = natintro></A>Introduction<P></H2>
The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse is involved in a number of projects–
including the publication of a variety of information products–which monitor 
trends in the use and misuse of licit and illicit drugs in Canada. For detailed 
information, the Committee is asked to refer to the <I>Canadian Profile: Alcohol, 
Tobacco and Other Drugs</I>. The most recent information on substance abuse 
is also available through the CCSA's website (http://www.ccsa.ca).<P>
The information provided in these sources indicates that the use of alcohol, 
tobacco, and other psychoactive drugs is a source of major health and social 
problems in Canada. Substance abuse is among the leading causes of 
preventable death and illness, and its impact on the economy is enormous.<P>
Alcohol continues to exact a heavy toll on the well-being of Canadians, 
particularly among youth and high-risk populations such as First Nations 
peoples, pregnant women, the disabled and the elderly. The use of alcohol in 
combination with other drugs, including pharmaceutical products, is largely 
unexplored. The disinhibiting effects of alcohol and other psychoactive 
substances contribute to the spread of HIV/AIDS through risky activities such as 
unprotected sex and the use of contaminated needles.<P>
Tobacco use continues to decline within the general population (15 years and 
older), but has shown a significant increase among adolescents since 1993 in at 
least one major survey (Ontario Student Drug Use Survey, ARF, 1995). Some 
critics within the anti-tobacco lobby blame this rise on the lowering of taxes on 
cigarettes by the Government of Canada in 1994. The long-term implications of 
an upward trend in adolescent tobacco use are of great concern since we know 
that a high percentage of people who begin smoking before the age of 20 will 
become lifetime smokers.<P>
Illicit drug use is on the rise for the first time in more than a decade and the 
increase is being led by younger Canadians. The Ontario Student Drug Use 
Survey, for example, indicates sharp increases in the use of drugs such as 
cannabis, methamphetamine ("speed"), PCP, cocaine and ecstasy. Studies in 
the US have produced similar results, painting a disturbing picture of growing 
adolescent drug use across North America.<P>
<H3>Why is illicit drug use increasing?</H3>
The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse is often asked by the media why 
illicit drug use is growing after such a long period of decline. There is no clear 
answer. Rebellion against a decade of post-war materialism and conservative 
thinking fueled the drug revolution of the '60s. Today's economic despair, 
collapse of the family and community, and a general sense of hopelessness 
may be even more powerful engines of abuse, particularly when combined with 
greater availability and variety of drugs than we could have imagined 30 years 
ago, and, some have argued, more liberal parental attitudes.<P>
Social policy also has an impact on drug use, although its effects are extremely 
hard to measure and evaluate. We can observe that drug use declined 
significantly concomitant with the first five years of Canada's Drug Strategy, and 
started rising again during Phase II. Prevention and education efforts in Phase I 
targeted "mainstream" populations, especially youth who were still in school. In 
Phase II the focus shifted to street youth and other high-risk groups.<P>
The resurgence of drug use we are now witnessing is led largely by mainstream 
youth, indicating that we may have paid a heavy price for changing our focus 
and neglecting this group in Phase II. Ultimately we must aim our prevention 
messages at all youth. The Centre believes that all young people–drop-outs and 
A students alike–are vulnerable to drug use and should be viewed as an at-risk 
population.<P>
Although individual reasons for drug-taking may be hard to get at, one thing is 
clear: all things being equal, total drug use in a given population will rise and fall 
with the size of that group. We should be aware of the compelling fact that the 
children of the "baby boom" generation–often referred to as the "echo-boom" or 
"mini-boom"–have begun to move through adolescence when the lure of risk-
taking is at its strongest.<P>
The quantum leap in illicit drug use that began in the mid-1960s was in many 
respects a simple matter of numbers as the huge contingent of children born 
after 1946 reached their teenage years. Anyone who doubts the potential 
impact of the "echo-boom" on total drug use over the next decade should be 
reminded of the steady rise in demand that occurred from the mid-1960s until 
the late 1970s and early 1980s.<P>
<H2><A NAME = preval></A>Prevalence and trends in substance use 
and abuse in Canada<P></H2>
<UL>
<LI>The proportion of Canadians who report drinking in the past 12 months in national surveys has 
declined from 80% in 1979 to 72% in 1994. 
<LI>The proportion of Canadians who report smoking in national surveys decreased steadily from 50% in 
1960 to 44% in 1975, 40% in 1981, 32% in 1989 and 27% in 1995. Recent studies indicate that young 
females are now just as likely to smoke as young males. As well, the ARF has reported a significant 
increase in smoking (from 23.% in 1993 to 27.9% in 1995) among Ontario students in Grades 7, 9, 11 
and 13.
<LI>Approximately one in four adult Canadians report having used an illicit drug at some point in their 
lives. After more than a decade of decline, there are disturbing indications that illicit drug use is on the 
rise again. The proportion of Canadians who report using cannabis in the past year increased from 4.2% 
in 1993 to 7.4% in 1994. Increased cannabis use is particularly marked among youth and young adults. 
Cocaine use increased from 0.3% in 1993 to 0.7% in 1994, and the proportion who report using LSD, 
heroin or speed in the prior year increased from 0.3% in 1993 to 1.1% in 1994.
</UL>
<H2><A NAME = health></A>Health consequences and social 
harm<P></H2>
The use of psychoactive substances entails enormous adverse consequences 
to the health of Canadians. The misuse of alcohol and illicit drugs is also 
associated with adverse social consequences such as crime, violent behaviour, 
unemployment and poor productivity, family discord, as well as spousal and 
child abuse.<P>
<UL>
<LI>It is estimated that 6,701 Canadians lost their lives as a result of alcohol consumption in 1992, the 
year on which CCSA based its Canadian cost study. Many of these deaths involved relatively young 
Canadians. The number of potential years of life lost was estimated to be 186,257 years, representing 27.8 
years of life lost for every alcohol-related death. 
<LI>he 6,701 deaths attributed to alcohol in the CCSA study represented 3% of total mortality in Canada 
for 1992, the 186,257 years of potential life lost due to alcohol constituted 6% of the total years of 
potential life lost due to any cause, the 86,076 hospitalizations due to alcohol represented 2% of all 
hospitalizations, and the 1.15 million days of hospitalization due to alcohol represented 3% of the total 
days spent in hospital for any cause.
<LI>The CCSA estimated the total number deaths in Canada attributable to smoking to be 33,498 in 
1992. Cancer accounted for the largest number of tobacco-related deaths (11,704), representing 35% of all 
such deaths.
<LI>The 33,498 deaths due to tobacco estimated in the CCSA study represented 17% of total mortality in 
Canada for 1992. Smoking also accounted for 16% of the total years of potential life lost, 6% of all 
hospitalizations and 7% of all hospitalization days for any cause in Canada in 1992.
<LI>The CCSA estimated that there were 732 deaths attributable to illicit drugs in Canada in 1992. The 
vast majority (87%) of these deaths involved males and most of the victims were relatively young adults.
<LI>The largest proportion of drug-related deaths were due to suicide (42%), opiate poisoning (14%) or 
cocaine poisoning (9%). The use of contaminated needles by intravenous drug users accounted for 61 
AIDS deaths, representing 8% of all illicit drug-related deaths. The spread of HIV infection among illicit 
drugs users remains a major vehicle by which AIDS can spread to the general population.
<LI>Although the number of deaths attributed to illicit drug use is smaller than the number of deaths 
attributable to alcohol and tobacco, illicit drug deaths tend to involve younger victims. The 732 illicit 
drug-related deaths resulted in 31,147 potential years of life lost, representing 42.6 years for each death 
and about 1% of total years of life lost due to any cause. 
<LI>Taken together, substance abuse accounted for 21% of total mortality in 1992, and 23% of years of 
potential life lost. Hospitalizations due to substance abuse constituted 8% of total hospitalizations and 
10% of the total days spent in hospitals for any cause in Canada in 1992.
</UL>
<H2><A NAME = economic></A>Economic costs<P></H2>
<UL>
<LI>The CCSA estimated that substance abuse cost the Canadian economy more than $18.4 billion in 
1992. This represents $649 per capita, or about 2.7% of the total Gross Domestic Product. 
<LI>Alcohol accounted for approximately $7.5 billion in costs, or $265 per capita. The costs of smoking 
were $9.5 billion in 1992, or approximately $340 per capita. The economic costs of illicit drugs were 
estimated at over $1.4 billion.
</UL>
There are two key factors to keep in mind when considering the results of 
CCSA's economic cost study.<P>
First, the study was extremely conservative and measured only those harms 
which could be reliably linked to substance use. For example, it has been 
argued that a portion of property crime (i.e. theft) could be attributed to illicit 
drugs, but unfortunately we could find no studies indicating the attributable 
fraction of property crimes to illicit drugs.<P>
Second, drug use in 1992 appears in retrospect to have been at the lowest level 
since the late 1970s and early 1980s. We now know that this "bottoming out" 
was followed by an increase between 1993 and 1995. Therefore, 1992 presents 
us with the most optimistic picture of drug use in Canada. A similar study carried 
out in 1996 would undoubtedly reveal a much grimmer snapshot.<P>
<CENTER><H1><A NAME = societal></A>Societal response to substance 
use</H1></CENTER>
<H2><A NAME = public></A>Public policy<P></H2>
<H3>Alcohol</H3>
Today alcohol policy in Canada is a shared responsibility of the federal government, and the provinces 
and territories. The federal government has authority over the importing and exporting of alcohol 
products, alcohol-related excise taxes, and broadcast advertising. The broadcasting regulations, developed 
by the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC), and referred to as the 
"Code", prohibit a range of messages, including any that<P>
<UL>
<LI>attempt to influence non-drinkers to drink, 
<LI>appeal to minors, 
<LI>associate consumption with high-risk activities,
<LI>suggest consumption is associated with success or achievement, or 
<LI>violate the relevant provincial advertising law.
</UL>
In a public notice issued in August, 1996, the CRTC proposed a new regulatory 
framework that would hand over responsibility for the Code to the broadcast 
industry. This responsibility would include the pre-screening of alcohol 
advertisements previously done by the CRTC. The Canadian Centre on 
Substance Abuse has urged the CRTC not to abandon its responsibility for 
enforcing compliance with its own Code and to explain what mechanism it 
envisages for ensuring compliance under the new regulatory framework.<P>
In the same public notice, the CRTC said it "expected" broadcasters to present 
a balanced view of alcohol in our society by broadcasting messages about the 
dangers of alcohol abuse. However, there are no rules stipulating how much 
counter-measure advertising must be broadcast, and no definition of what 
constitutes a balanced view of alcohol. The CCSA has recommended that the 
CRTC involve public health representatives in a proposed annual performance 
review of counter-measure advertising.<P>
<H3>Tobacco</H3>
Two key developments in tobacco policy since 1994 have undermined efforts at 
convincing young Canadians not to smoke. The first was the lowering of federal 
tobacco taxes to counteract a serious cigarette smuggling problem. The second 
was the Supreme Court decision of September, 1995, striking down sections of 
the Tobacco Products Control Act prohibiting cigarette advertising.<P>
Canada desperately needs a bold new initiative to fill the tobacco policy gap that 
now exists. The Government of Canada has a powerful tool at its disposal in the 
form of taxation, yet it clearly wants to avoid raising cigarette prices to the point 
where smuggling once again becomes an attractive option. If higher taxes were 
reinstated, Canada might initiate negotiations with Washington to close the gap 
between Canadian and US prices. Or the use of specialized enforcement could 
be considered. Ultimately, however, adjustments to the supply side of the 
tobacco question–or, indeed, the alcohol and illicit drug situation–will have little 
impact if we cannot reduce the demand through effective programs of education 
and prevention.<P>
<H3>Illicit drugs</H3>
By now this Committee will be very familiar with Bill C-8, the Controlled Drugs 
and Substances Act. It was the Sub-Committee studying the bill that 
recommended the review process we are now engaged in. Clearly the Sub-
Committee believed that this new drug legislation–the first in more than 30 
years–needed to be seen in the larger context of Canadian efforts to combat 
substance abuse. The CCSA wholeheartedly shares that belief.<P>
CCSA presented its views on the new drug legislation two years ago when it 
was still known as Bill C-7. Some of our comments may be worth repeating 
here, although the opportunity to make changes to Bill C-8 has now passed.<P>
CCSA had asked that the legislation be prefaced with a clear statement of 
purpose–much in the same way that the Sub-Committee saw a need to put it in 
context by recommending a review of drug policy. A statement of purpose might 
have helped explain to the Canadian public why a piece of legislation sponsored 
by the Department of Health focuses exclusively on issues of police powers, 
enforcement and penalties.<P>
CCSA also argued that the bill did not take full advantage of the treatment 
options in lieu of prison permitted under the UN drug conventions. We were 
pleased to note the passage of Bill C-41 which makes allowance for alternate 
forms of sentencing for a vast array of offences, and we hope that the courts 
will make the link between the two pieces of legislation.<P>
At this point we need to sound a warning that we have received from our 
colleagues in the treatment field: although they strongly support the use of 
treatment in lieu of prison, their resources are already stretched to the breaking 
point. A further influx of treatment cases from the court system will need to be 
accompanied by a refocusing of resources. The money to be saved by 
streamlining our current "revolving-door" justice system should more than cover 
additional treatment costs.<P>
<H2><A NAME = scope></A>Scope and depth of program 
interventions<P></H2>
<H3>Population health: what is it?</H3>
Drug and alcohol programming in Canada has lost much of its focus in recent 
years because of shrinking budgets and shifting political philosophies. At the 
provincial/territorial level, a majority of independent provincial drug and alcohol 
agencies have been dismantled, and prevention, education and treatment 
activities have been absorbed into the overall provincial health care system. 
This has resulted in an erosion of specialized knowledge and expertise, and the 
loss of valuable personnel.<P>
At the federal level, the remnants of health programs developed under 
Canada's Drug Strategy are now destined to be merged with a host of other 
concerns under the label of population health. It is not clear at this time what 
priority Health Canada will give to substance abuse within this new framework, 
or what types of programming will emerge as a result.<P>
Population health, also known as the determinants of health model, was a 
concept first introduced to Canada more than 20 years ago by former Health 
Minister Marc Lalonde. The approach is attractive because it treats health in a 
holistic way and claims that people can improve their health by making sensible 
lifestyle choices. It has a strong cost-effectiveness appeal as well because it 
suggests that access to costly, high-tech medical services has little real impact 
on our health compared with simple, low-cost measures such as diet and 
exercise.<P>
However, from a programming perspective, population health presents us with a 
conundrum. For example, the literature on population health tells us that job 
status has a significant impact on an individual's health. The more senior the 
worker, the fewer health problems he or she experiences. What type of health 
programming do we devise to address this fact? Do we give everyone a 
promotion? A major study done in the UK a few years ago found that having 
access to a car had a marked influence on the health of people living in London. 
Are we really ready to deal with the implications of population health?<P>
Population health looks at a whole range of determinants that may or may not 
fall within the traditional health context. That makes sense. Perhaps substance 
abuse is not a cause of ill health, but only a symptom. The real determinants 
may be social, economic or biological, or a combination of these and many 
other root causes. These antecedents should be addressed, although we have 
yet to see how this will be done. However, we will still need to deal in a specific 
and focused way with the problems of substance abuse–symptom or 
otherwise.<P>
The CCSA believes that substance abuse is both a catalyst to poor health and 
an inhibitor of success in health and social programming. The population health 
approach will only be viable in an environment which simultaneously 
acknowledges such issues.<P>
Earlier in this paper, we referred to the absence of goals, and a mechanism for 
evaluating those targets in Canada's Drug Strategy. Goal setting and evaluation 
will be a much more complex process within the population health model. Again, 
we are anxiously awaiting word on how this will be done.<P>
We believe CCSA can be of assistance to programmers and policy-makers 
working to flesh out the population health vision. Addressing the health of 
individual population groups will depend heavily on the kind of detailed data we 
gather on those groups and on how each reacts to various health and social 
stressors. In other words, population health is grounded to a large degree in 
epidemiology. The Canadian Community Epidemiology Network on Drug Use 
(CCENDU), currently monitoring drug use trends in six Canadian cities, can 
provide a wealth of information to support the implementation of population 
health.<P>
If properly implemented population health could allow us to look at addictions in 
a more holistic way. For example, the CCSA is coming under increasing 
pressure to be a national provider of information on gambling. Although we have 
started to accumulate material on gambling in the National Clearinghouse on 
Substance Abuse, we are somewhat limited by the fact that this is not officially 
part of our mandate. There is a need that clearly could be filled if the CCSA had 
the flexibility to do so.<P>
<CENTER><H1><A NAME = internat></A>International considerations</H1></CENTER>
Canada is not alone in its struggle with substance abuse. Drug use in the US is 
also increasing and the same populations are leading the trend–adolescents 
and young adults. The Clinton administration has reacted by committing the US 
to a 10-year drug strategy with a new emphasis on demand reduction. President 
Clinton has pledged more than $15 billion in the first year alone.<P>
Drug trafficking and money laundering are huge global enterprises and no 
country can deal with its drug problems in isolation. Events halfway around the 
world are felt in a direct and usually devastating way on our city streets. Heroin 
purity rises, people die. Prices drop, people die. Drug deals turn sour, people 
die.<P>
Global free trade in legitimate goods has opened the door to trafficking in drugs. 
Organized crime has taken hold in many countries where the legitimate 
economy is in tatters. Parts of the former Soviet Union, now set adrift, have 
become open channels for drug trafficking. We know also that as drugs make 
their way to market, transit countries increasingly become consumer countries. 
Canada itself is a transit country.<P>
Legal drugs are also an international problem. There are many countries where 
alcohol consumption is at dangerous levels and the only options open to 
government are heavy-handed attempts at prohibition. This was tried in the 
Soviet Union with devastating results.<P>
Tobacco use is growing, especially in Third World countries and emerging 
Soviet bloc nations, as tobacco manufacturers exploit the kind of voracious 
demand for their products that no longer exists in North America. In such 
countries, there are no Health Canada-type warnings on cigarette packages, 
and no real awareness that smoking is deadly.<P>
Science and the information age have combined to create yet another new 
global drug hazard: potent synthetic stimulants are now promoted on the 
Internet, complete with easy-to-follow recipes that can be cooked up on kitchen 
tables around the world.<P>
The United Nations continues to view the fight against substance abuse as one 
of its top priorities, along with terrorism, peace-keeping and the environment. A 
special session of the UN General Assembly will be held in June, 1998, to look 
at the drug problem. It is critical that Canada have a strong presence at that 
meeting.<P>
<CENTER><H1><A NAME = issues></A>Issues and opportunities</H1></CENTER>
<H2><A NAME = right></A>Drug policy: Have we got it 
right?<P></H2>
Does Canada need to get "tougher on drugs" by moving to a US-style zero-
tolerance approach, or should we learn to accept some drug use as part of 
normal human existence as the Dutch have done, for example? It is tempting to 
view the problem in such clearly defined terms, but the truth is that Canada 
must find subtle and innovative solutions that work for Canadians.<P>
Some things are almost self-evident. As a society, we don't need freer access to 
more psychoactive substances. Do we really need to legalize marijuana, for 
instance? We are already inundated by drugs, both legal and illegal. Isn't the 
devastation caused by alcohol and tobacco a sufficient deterrent to making 
other intoxicants readily available? We are generally too quick to look for 
chemical solutions to problems that threaten to overwhelm us.<P>
On the other hand–and there is considerable irony here–we tend to stigmatize 
people who become drug-dependent, and where illicit drugs are involved, we 
often penalize them in ways that simply add to the harm they are already 
inflicting on themselves.<P>
Discussions of drug policy tend to polarize into support for prohibition at one of 
the spectrum and arguments for decriminalization or legalization at the other 
end. The first group contends that a more liberal approach will lead to a 
dramatic increase in drug use. The second believes that decriminalization or 
legalization will eliminate many drug-related problems by removing the profit 
motive from the drug trade. We aware of no hard evidence to substantiate either 
claim.<P>
The debate over prohibition versus legalization makes interesting newspaper 
copy, but it distracts us from the real issue, namely that no amount of tinkering 
with drug enforcement and supply reduction mechanisms can hope to be as 
effective as a strong, national demand reduction strategy based on prevention, 
education, treatment and rehabilitation.<P>
<H2><A NAME = focus></A>Focus on youth and high-risk 
groups<P></H2>
In its 1987 report, <I>Booze, Pills &amp  Dope: Reducing Substance Abuse in 
Canada</I>, the House Standing Committee on National Health and Welfare 
recommended that the Department of National Health and Welfare identify 
children and youth as the first priority for funding under a cost-shared substance 
abuse prevention program. That recommendation was made at a time when 
youth drug use was in decline, having peaked in the late 1970s and early 
1980s. It was a valid recommendation nonetheless, and it needs to be made 
again today all the more strongly as rates of drug use climb back up towards 
previous levels.<P>
We have learned much in the last decade about how to reach youth with 
credible prevention messages. We are learning to be more honest and 
pragmatic. We need to build on our knowledge as we enter what could be a 
decade of increasing drug use. Our biggest failing is that we have not been 
consistent. Prevention and education campaigns come and go as political 
interest and funding ebb and flow. We must find and support low-cost ways to 
incorporate these efforts into existing and ongoing educational programs.<P>
Policies and programs aimed at youth need to be individually tailored to address 
the specific needs of various youth sub-populations, including hard-to-reach 
street kids. Programs need to become part of the environment where children 
grow and learn, including school, the family, peer groups, and the 
community.<P>
<H3>A key strategy: building resiliency</H3>
In recent years, we have come to a greater appreciation of the role of protective 
factors in youth substance abuse prevention. We have learned that children and 
adolescents become more resilient to drug use if they have access to a 
significant source of social support, either from a sympathetic teacher, family 
member, or member of the community. It only takes one special person, or 
mentor, to provide that support and–just as important–to express high 
expectations of the individual.<P>
<H3>FAS and the labelling issue</H3>
Dwindling resources force us to rethink campaigns aimed at the general 
population and to focus instead on youth and other high-risk groups, including 
Aboriginal peoples, pregnant women, the disabled and the elderly. CCSA has 
done work in all of these areas, but one of our major concentrations at the 
moment is on the problem of fetal damage resulting from women who drink 
while pregnant. The Centre runs a national fetal alcohol syndrome and fetal 
alcohol effects information service in partnership with Health Canada and the 
Brewers Association of Canada.<P>
We raise this issue to draw attention once again to the strong support within the 
FAS/FAE community for warning labels on alcohol containers. We remind the 
Standing Committee that CCSA supported this demand in our appearance 
before the Sub-Committee studying Bill C-222 in April. We see this as a 
consumers' rights issue. But we repeat what we said at that time: warning labels 
and other isolated measures will have little or no effect unless they are part of 
an overall strategy aimed at reducing a wide range of health risks for women 
who abuse alcohol while pregnant, as well as for their developing fetus.<P>
<H2><A NAME = continuum></A>Continuum of cost-effective 
interventions<P></H2>
<H3>Abstinence and controlled use</H3>
Like the debate over prohibition and decriminalization, the arguments around 
abstinence and controlled use rage constantly. A huge battle arose over 
treatment of alcoholism more than 30 years ago when a British doctor reported 
that he had treated several severely alcoholic patients who later went on to 
become moderate "social drinkers". The doctor and his work were mercilessly 
attacked by those who believed in the abstinence approach (popularized by 
Alcoholics Anonymous) which does not acknowledge the possibility of an 
alcoholic learning to drink in a controlled manner.<P>
A similar kind of debate has at times surrounded the notion of maintaining 
heroin addicts on prescribed doses of methadone, or even heroin itself in some 
countries. Likewise, the battle lines are often drawn over the question of 
whether to issue clean needles and syringes to injection drug users in an effort 
to stop the spread of HIV/AIDS.<P>
The CCSA believes the polarization of these issues is counterproductive. No 
single solution can be applied successfully to each and every drug abuse 
problem. Substance abuse problems must be seen within a continuum of 
severity demanding appropriate responses. People differ, situations change. 
Where alcohol is concerned, we know that 5-10% of the population may be 
severely dependent drinkers. For them, abstinence is clearly the safest 
route.<P>
<H3>Abstinence and harm reduction</H3>
However, another 15-20% of the population experience occasional problems 
with drinking that may range from skipping a day of work to nurse a hangover to 
causing a serious car accident. Many of these people would be considered 
moderate drinkers, but from time to time, they drink too much. They may not 
accept abstinence as an appropriate option. Our programs and policies must 
reflect this reality and attempt to more precisely target the real source of harm–
not the drinking itself, but the drinking to excess, or abusive drinking. We refer 
to this approach as "harm reduction".<P>
Harm reduction becomes a trickier proposition where illicit drugs are involved. 
The majority of Canadians support methadone and needle exchange programs, 
but within fairly strict limits. How do we feel about handing out clean needles to 
people in prison to stop the rampant spread of HIV/AIDS, for example? How do 
we react to the BC coroner's suggestion that prescribing heroin to addicts under 
a doctor's supervision would reduce the skyrocketing number of fatal overdoses 
on the streets of Vancouver?<P>
<H2><A NAME = supporting></A>Supporting evidence-based 
decisions<P></H2>
These questions are not easily answered. They put society's values to the test. 
When we look beyond the emotional issues, we see a need for rational 
decision-making based on solid information. This begins with an honest 
assessment of all the harms that surround a drug use problem and then 
attempts to put these in priority order. We then try to manage the risks by 
applying strategies that deal with the greatest threats first.<P>
As an approach to intervention, harm reduction has helped to focus attention 
where it appears to be needed most. Where harm reduction has been less 
successful is in the evaluation of its results, and in the clear demonstration of its 
benefits. This is not an easy task. Even if detailed data are gathered, they aren't 
always interpreted correctly.<P>
Earlier this year the <I>Globe and Mail</I> published an article about a needle 
exchange program in Montreal that the newspaper suggested was contributing 
to the spread of HIV/AIDS. The reporter had looked at a study of the program 
that showed the rate of HIV was higher among its clients than among injection 
drug users who did not attend the clinic. CCSA contacted the Montreal doctor 
who did the study for clarification and discovered that the reason for the high 
rate of HIV among clients of the exchange was that a large percentage of them 
started coming to the clinic only <I>after</I> they had already contracted the 
virus. The study actually concluded that the needle exchange was reducing the 
spread of HIV.<P>
<H2><A NAME = enhancing></A>Enhancing private sector and community 
involvement<P></H2>
In recent years, the private sector has emerged as an area of keen interest for 
those of us in the substance abuse field. Many organizations facing the spectre 
of defunding have turned to business and industry for sponsorship and support 
of their activities. CCSA has enjoyed some success in identifying sources of 
private sector funding, notably for our FAS/FAE information service. But the 
members of the Standing Committee should be aware that the delivery of 
substance abuse programs in this country can never hope to depend to any 
significant degree on the largesse of business and industry, unless government 
can devise innovative incentives–perhaps through the tax system–to stimulate 
private sector involvement. We strongly encourage consideration of these kinds 
of strategies.<P>
Where the private sector may be able to help us is in areas where we can help 
them. The need is certainly there for expert advice and counsel. Employee 
substance abuse is viewed by a majority of managers and executives as a 
serious problem and many businesses seem ill-equipped to deal with it. 
Employee assistance programs are springing up in more and more workplaces, 
drug testing of workers has stirred up controversy and a number of appeals to 
human rights tribunals, and many business owners–especially in small and 
medium-size sector–are looking for a place to turn for information.<P>
Canada does not do as well as we might hope when it comes to drugs and the 
workplace. The 1995 World Competitiveness Report showed that Canada had 
moved up to 12th place among 48 countries in overall competitiveness, but 
ranked a dismal 40th in the category of alcohol and drug abuse in the 
workforce.<P>
The CCSA has attempted to fill the knowledge gap around workplace substance 
abuse by publishing a variety of specialized resource materials, including 
Canada's first directory of employee assistance programs and services. The 
centre has worked with the RCMP to develop books and presentations that 
Drug Awareness Officers can take into the workplace. As well, the Centre has 
offered a series of workplace telephone seminars to examine vital issues such 
as the new US transport regulations requiring the testing of all commercial 
drivers entering the US.<P>
<H3>Finding ways to involve communities</H3>
Community involvement is critical to the success of substance abuse policy and 
programming. Programs devised at the national level are cost effective because 
they can serve many people. But they also must be flexible enough to meet the 
needs of individual populations and locations. Only strong input from those 
communities will produce the right kinds of strategies. Only an effective 
mechanism for national communication will ensure that input.<P>
Part of the job of the community development process, particularly within the 
population health framework, is to find ways of stimulating involvement by so-
called non-traditional groups, which like the private sector have not typically 
seen themselves as part of substance abuse prevention strategies. Examples 
would include groups and individuals concerned with issues of housing, 
unemployment and poverty. Even those whose main preoccupation is finance 
need to become involved. We must develop incentives that will draw these 
groups into the overall effort.<P>
<CENTER><H1><A NAME = summary></A>Summary and conclusions</H1></CENTER>
<H2><A NAME = problem></A>The problem<P></H2>
<UL>
<LI>The use of psychoactive substances entails enormous adverse consequences to the health of 
Canadians. The misuse of alcohol and illicit drugs is also associated with adverse social consequences 
such as crime, violent behaviour, unemployment and poor productivity, family discord, as well as spousal 
and child abuse.
<LI>Alcohol continues to exact a heavy toll on the well-being of Canadians, particularly among youth and 
high-risk populations such as First Nations peoples, pregnant women, the disabled and the elderly.
<LI>Tobacco use continues to decline within the general population (15 years and older), but there are 
indications of a significant increase among adolescents since 1993.
<LI>Illicit drug use is on the rise for the first time in more than a decade and the increase is being led by 
younger Canadians.
<LI>Taken together, substance abuse accounted for 21% of total mortality in 1992, and 23% of years of 
potential life lost. Hospitalizations due to substance abuse constituted 8% of total hospitalizations and 
10% of the total days spent in hospitals for any cause in Canada in 1992.
<LI>Substance abuse cost the Canadian economy more than $18.4 billion in 1992. This represents $649 
per capita, or about 2.7% of the total Gross Domestic Product.
</UL>
<H2><A NAME = response></A>The federal response<P></H2>
<UL>
<LI>At the federal level, the health of programs developed under Canada's Drug Strategy are now 
destined to be merged with a host of other concerns under the label of population health. It is not clear at 
this time what priority Health Canada will give to substance abuse within this new framework, or what 
types of programming will emerge as a result.
<LI>By the time this Committee presents its recommendations in June, 1997, Canada's Drug Strategy will 
have sunset three months earlier, and unless there is a significant change in the current course of events, 
the The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse will have ceased to exist.
<LI>Two key developments in tobacco policy since 1994–the lowering of cigarette taxes and the striking 
down of the ban on advertising–have undermined efforts at convincing young Canadians not to smoke. 
Canada needs a bold new initiative to fill the tobacco policy gap that now exists.
<LI>The resurgence of drug use we are now witnessing is led largely by mainstream youth, indicating 
that we may have paid a heavy price for changing our focus and neglecting this group in Phase II of 
Canada's Drug Strategy.
<LI>The Standing Committee can play a pivotal role in rekindling Canadian efforts to combat substance 
abuse. Our hope is that it will re-affirm the need for leadership and commitment by the Government of 
Canada in this area, and recommend continued investment in prevention, education and treatment.
</UL>
<H2><A NAME = key></A>Key issues and considerations<P></H2>
<H3>Youth</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Policies and programs aimed at youth need to be individually tailored to address the specific needs of 
various youth sub-populations. Programs need to become part of the environment where children grow 
and learn, including school, the family, peer groups, and the community.
<LI>We need to explore the role of protective factors in youth substance abuse prevention. We are 
learning that children and adolescents become more resilient to drug use if they have access to a 
significant source of social support, such as a teacher or family member.
</UL>
<H3>Population health</H3>
<UL>
<LI>The CCSA considers substance abuse to be both a catalyst to poor health and an inhibitor of success 
in health and social programming. The population health approach will only be viable in an environment 
which simultaneously acknowledges such issues.
<LI>If properly implemented population health could allow us to look at addictions in a more holistic 
way, such as gambling. There is a need that clearly could be filled if the CCSA had the flexibility to do so.
</UL>
<H3>Drug control policy</H3>
<UL>
<LI>The debate over prohibition versus legalization distracts us from the real issue, namely that no 
amount of tinkering with drug enforcement and supply reduction mechanisms can hope to be as effective 
as a strong, national demand reduction strategy based on prevention, education, treatment and 
rehabilitation.
</UL>
<H3>Harm reduction</H3>
<UL>
<LI>As an approach to intervention, harm reduction has helped to focus attention where it appears to be 
needed most. Where harm reduction has been less successful is in the evaluation of its results, and in the 
clear demonstration of its benefits.
<LI>Our alcohol prevention and education programs and policies must reflect the reality that abstinence 
is not for everyone and must attempt to more precisely target the real source of harm–not the drinking 
itself, but the drinking to excess, or abusive drinking.
</UL>
<H3>Alcohol advertising</H3>
<UL>
<LI>The Canadian Centre on Substance Abuse has urged the CRTC not to abandon its responsibility for 
enforcing compliance with its own Code on the broadcasting of alcohol advertising, and has asked what 
mechanism it envisages for ensuring compliance with the Code under the CRTC's new regulatory 
framework. The CCSA has recommended that the CRTC involve public health representatives in a 
proposed annual performance review of counter-measure advertising in order to ensure a balanced view of 
alcohol in the electronic media.
</UL>
<H3>Alternate sentencing and treatment</H3>
<UL>
<LI>A further influx of drug treatment cases from the court system as a result of alternate sentencing will 
need to be accompanied by a refocusing of resources. The money to be saved by streamlining our current 
"revolving-door" justice system should more than cover additional treatment costs.
</UL>
<H3>Warning labels</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Warning labels on alcohol containers and other isolated measures will have little or no effect unless 
they are part of an overall strategy aimed at reducing a wide range of health risks for women who abuse 
alcohol while pregnant, as well as for their developing fetus.
</UL>
<H3>Community involvement</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Part of the job of the community development process, particularly within the population health 
framework, is to find ways of stimulating involvement by so-called non-traditional groups, which like the 
private sector have not typically seen themselves as part of substance abuse prevention strategies. 
Examples would include groups and individuals concerned with issues of housing, unemployment and 
poverty.
</UL>
<H3>Information</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Effective substance abuse programming and policy depend on good information. Mechanisms and 
infrastructures are needed to collect and disseminate data and information to support evidence-based 
decision-making.
</UL>
